<FIRST>r i PM-DangerousCucumber     10-06 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dangerous Cucumber,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robber Armed With Cucumber Stole More Than $19,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed only with a cucumber, which he pretended was
a shotgun, a 36-year-old man stole $19,868 in 16 holdups over two
months to finance a drug habit, a prosecutor said.
   Pointing the cucumber wrapped in a plastic bag at terrified
cashiers and screaming ``Give me the money or I'll blow your head
off!'' the man raided 15 financial institutions and a post office,
prosecutor Michael Warren told London's Old Bailey Central Criminal
Court.
   Ernest Coveley pleaded guilty to 10 counts of robbery and six
counts of attempted robbery.
   He had initially faced 16 charges of using fake weapons in the
raids. But his plea of innocent to these was accepted by the court
on grounds that cucumbers cannot be classed as imitation firearms.
   Judge Edwin Jowitt postponed sentencing until he reviews social
and psychiatric reports on Coveley.
   Coveley's attorney, Peter Feinberg, told the judge that a
cucumber ``is not the choice of a man who is perhaps more
professionally geared for robbery.''
   Security cameras filmed the man as he held up a savings and loan
office in east London, Warren said. Police later arrested him at
his apartment.
   Warren said Coveley undertook the raids to finance his addiction
to cocaine and heroin. He said Coveley used a fresh cucumber for
each raid.
</TEXT>
