<FIRST>r a AM-ChildrenThrown 5thLd-Writethru a0852 10-06 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children Thrown, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0852,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Throws Children Out 10th Floor Window</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Zainab died ..., to UPDATE with boy's condition
deteriorated.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saying ``God is waiting for you,'' a naked woman
pushed two of her children out a 10th-floor window Thursday,
killing her 6-year-old daughter and critically injuring her
3-year-old son, officials said.
   Rescuers stormed the apartment in time to save a third child, a
1-year-old girl, as she was being shoved through the window's
safety bars, officials said.
   The mother, Meenhah Abdussalaam, 32, her daughter, Zainab, and
son Husein were taken to St. John's Episcopal Hospital in Queens, a
borough of New York, authorities said.
   Zainab died of her injuries, said Nancy Uzo, a spokeswoman for
St. John's. Husein was transferred from St. John's to North Shore
University Hospital on Long Island, where he was in extremely
critical condition on a respirator after surgery, said Carol
Hauptman, spokeswoman for North Shore.
   Both suffered massive internal injuries, fractures and cardiac
arrest, said Charles De Gaetano of the Emergency Medical Services.
The mother, who was not physically injured, was being evaluated at
the hospital.
   Mrs. Abdussalaam was taken into custody at 2:20 p.m., five
minutes after the children fell from the Queens apartment, said
police spokesman Detective Joseph McConville. She was not
immediately charged.
   ``She was mumbling `Mohammed, Elijah.' She was trying to move
the children along to the window to jump and she was going to jump
also,'' said Fire Lt. John Lane, who was one of the first rescuers
on the scene.
   ``She told the children, `God is waiting for you,'' said Lane,
who added that they were all naked.
   ``The only thing that saved them was there was a window guard,''
which made it difficult to push the children out the window, he
said.
   Neighbors described Mrs. Abdussalaam as quiet and polite, a good
mother and a devout Moslem, whose husband had recently moved out.
   ``Her husband left her last week and she went crazy,'' said one
neighbor, Zulfar Sahar.
   Firefighters passing the 20-story building on the way back to
their station ``saw one child, a girl, hanging by her hands from
the window ledge of the apartment,'' said Fire Department spokesman
Efrain Parilla.
   ``They started shouting `don't jump' and as they did so, they
saw the child trying to get back on the ledge. ... She lifted a leg
and tried to get back on the ledge, then the firefighters saw an
arm come out of the window and push the child away,'' Parilla said.
   The firefighters reached the scene as the girl fell on dirt in
front of the building. ``We looked up and saw the arms and legs of
another young child hanging out the same window,'' Lane said.
   ``We said `Oh God, don't jump, we're here, we want to help
you,'' the 28-year-veteran firefighter said, his voice shaking with
emotion during a telephone interview.
   The rescuers then broke down the apartment door, and the door to
a bedroom, where the mother had barricaded herself in with the
children, McConville said.
   The officers managed to grab the mother as she was sliding her
1-year-old daughter, Amna, out between the window bars.
   ``She was mumbling `Mohammed, Elijah,' she was trying to move
the children along to the window to jump and she was going to jump
also,'' said Fire Lt. John Lane, who was one of the first rescuers
on the scene.
   ``She told the children, `God is waiting for you,'' Lane said.
   ``The only thing that saved them was there was a window guard,''
which made it difficult to push the children out the window, he
added.
   Two other children, identified as an 8-year-old boy, Askia, and
a 4-year-old girl, Fatima, were in the apartment but were not
harmed. It was not known if they saw their siblings being pushed
out the window, police said.
   The children's father, Sultan Abdussalaam, 35, is separated from
the mother and was at work at the time of the incident, police said.
   The woman recently had received notice that she was going to be
evicted from her five-room apartment, but police did not know
whether the notice had had any effect on her behavior.
   Ann Sessa, president of the building's tenant association, said
the couple had lived without incident in the building for 12 years,
and said Mrs. Abdussalaam was ``very careful with the children.''
   The children were always clean and polite. ``It was always,
`Yes, M'am,' `No, M'am.' They're really nice children. They're not
wild.''
</TEXT>
