<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MTVBanned     10-06 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MTV Banned,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church-Affiliated University Cuts Off Music Video Channel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A church-affiliated university that
requires students to attend chapel daily says it doesn't want its
MTV because some students were watching nothing but the music video
channel.
   ``A minority of students were monopolizing it,'' David England,
spokesman for David Lipscomb University, said Thursday. ``They were
turning it up and keeping others from using the TV as intended.
This was eliminating the other students' right of choice.
   ``They were playing it so loudly that other students and
professors couldn't carry on conversations.''
   Complaints about the content of some MTV videos also led the
school to block the cable channel from sets in dormitory lounges
and the student center last month, England said.
   ``There is a morality issue and we won't back off what we
perceive to be immoral kinds of things,'' he said. ``We have a lot
of students who don't like what they see on it. We've had far more
complaints about it being on than it being off.''
   The school has an enrollment of 2,500 and is affiliated with the
Churches of Christ, a non-denominational group that preaches basic
Bible teachings.
   Barry Kluger, MTV vice president for corporate communications,
said by telephone from New York City that he regretted the decision.
   ``We feel the programming, after going through our stringent
standards, is appropriate for TV viewers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
