<FIRST>r a AM-FultonSheriff     10-06 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fulton Sheriff,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts Fulton County Sheriff on Extortion Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury Thursday indicted the
sheriff of Georgia's largest county on 27 counts of extortion
involving payments allegedly received from the company providing
food services to the county jail.
   U.S. Attorney Robert L. Barr said the indictment charged Fulton
County Sheriff Richard Lankford with taking more than 20 payments
totaling more than $20,000 from L&amp;G Catering Services between the
fall of 1985 and August 1988.
   It also charged Lankford with attempting to extort additional
payments of $2,000 and $5,000 from L&amp;G Catering as recently as May
of this year, he said.
   The indictment said the payments were made by L&amp;G's managing
owner, Jack LeCroy, at various locations, including the Fulton
County Sheriff's Office. Most of the payments allegedly occurred at
area restaurants.
   Barr said the payments were induced ``by exploiting the
corporation's fear of losing its valuable contract, and by
exploiting (Lankford's) official position.''
   The grand jury also charged Lankford, who has been sheriff since
1985, with filing false federal income tax returns for 1984 through
1987 by omitting the alleged payments.
   Lankford's said he was at Crawford Long Hospital being treated
for kidney stones.
   Barr said Lankford, if convicted, could be sentenced to 20 years
in prison and fined $250,000 on each extortion count. The income
tax charges could carry penalties of three years in prison and
another $250,000 fine.
   The investigation leading up to the indictments was conducted by
the FBI and the Internal Revenue Service, Barr said.
   Lankford was charged under the Hobbs Act, a federal statute that
prohibits elected officials from using their offices for personal
gain.
</TEXT>
