<HEAD>Ad Agency Says It Expects To Be Indicted for Jamaican Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young &amp; Rubicam, one of the country's largest
advertising agencies, said Thursday it would soon be indicted on
charges that it participated in bribing Jamaican officals to obtain
the Jamaican Tourist Board's ad account in 1981.
   The New York-based agency, which developed the ``Come back to
Jamaica'' ad campaign, also said several of its employees might be
indicted by a federal grand jury as well.
   The grand jury in New Haven, Conn., has been investigating the
relationship between the agency and the Caribbean nation's tourism
authority since 1986, The New York Times reported in Friday
editions.
   A report about the possibility of indictments appeared Wednesday
in The Hartford Courant. That newspaper said two or more Jamaican
officials also might be indicted.
   In a statement Thursday, Young &amp; Rubicam denied any impropriety
in its business dealings.
   ``Y&amp;R has a 66-year record of achievement conducted to the
highest ethical standards,'' the agency said.
   Marty Steinberg, a lawyer for the Jamaican Tourist Board, told
the Times that board officials had been called as witnesses before
the grand jury. He also said the board had been told it was not the
subject of the inquiry.
   Y&amp;R said it, too, cooperated with the grand jury.
   Ruder Finn Inc., a New York public relations agency that once
worked for the tourist board, also said it was under investigation
for that relationship.
