<DOCNO> AP891006-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     10-06 0827</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soil, Water Conservation Spending at Record Level</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says spending on
soil and water conservation is at a record level because of 1985
legislation that established a long-term retirement program for
fragile cropland.
   Under the massive Conservation Reserve Program, or CRP, a goal
of up to 45 million acres of highly erodible cropland could be
taken from production by the end of next year.
   By midyear, more than 30 million acres had been contracted and
more are on the way.
   According to analysts in the department's Economic Research
Service, total spending by USDA and state agencies for conservation
this year could exceed $3.2 billion, up from $2.5 billion in 1988
and $1.2 billion in 1987.
   Estimates show that total USDA spending this year on soil and
water conservation could reach $2.8 billion, up from $2.1 billion
in 1988 and $1.7 billion in 1987.
   Costs of the long-range CRP are expected to account for nearly
$1.75 billion, or roughly 62 percent of the $2.8 billion total,
says economist Merritt Padgitt.
   Other big USDA cost items are $176 million for carrying out
cost-sharing practices under the traditional Agricultural
Conservation Program, which dates back to the 1930s, and $366
million for technical assistance and extension services. A number
of other lesser programs make up the remainder.
   ``Yes, conservation expenditures are at an all-time high,
basically because of the CRP. Otherwise they have been trending
down,'' Padgitt said Thursday. ``The CRP is what has pushed them up
in the past three years.''
   Under the CRP, farmers whose contract offers are accepted can
idle land for 10 years and get annual rental payments from the
government. Those average around $50 per acre per year.
   In return, they must plant grass or trees to protect the land
from erosion. Federal payments also are made to help with the cost
of the initial plantings.
   For 1989, CRP spending is expected to include about $1.2 billion
for rental payments on retired land.
   Besides the total 1989 spending of more than $3.2 billion by
federal, state and local governments on soil and water
conservation, spending by farmers could be approximately $323
million.
   However, Padgitt said that was a tentative figure based on
survey information and could be revised.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department is giving Spain
more than 600 plants native to North America to help celebrate the
500th anniversary of the landing of Columbus in the New World.
   Horticulturist Sylvester March of the National Arboretum said
Thursday that the plants will join similar contributions from South
and Central America as part of the 1992 World's Fair in Seville.
The plants will be used in the landscaping and park areas around
the exposition's grounds on La Cartuja Island near Seville.
   March said the 600 specimens are representative of many parts of
North America and were shipped this year to give them time to reach
full development by the exposition's opening in 1992.
   The arboretum's selection ranged from the agave, a hardy
succulent, to the palmetto, he said. All of the plants are suited
to Seville's Mediterranean climate.
   Overall, at least 50,000 trees of more than 200 different
varieties and more than 150,000 bushes and shrubs have been
received for the gardens, according to Spanish officials.
   The island was said to be ``a particularly appropriate site''
for the New World garden because of its historic relationship to
Columbus, who often visited the Carthusian monastery on La Cartuja
to consult its extensive library. The Chapel of Santa Ana at the
monastery was built to house his remains.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporting companies have reported to
the Agriculture Department an additional sale of 400,000 metric
tons of U.S. corn to the Soviet Union for delivery in 1989-90 under
a long-term supply agreement.
   The corn sale announced Thursday was the third this week to the
Soviet Union, with orders totaling 2.6 million tons of corn and
100,000 tons of soybean meal. The seventh year of the long-term
agreement between the two countries began Oct. 1.
   U.S. grain sales to Moscow in 1988-89 were a record of more than
21.7 million tons, including more than 16.3 million tons of corn
and nearly 5.4 million tons of wheat.
   In addition, 1988-89 sales included 442,500 tons of soybeans,
1.35 million tons of soybean meal and 1.02 million tons of grain
sorghums.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 400,000 tons of
corn would be almost 15.8 million bushels.
   The new sales were made by unidentified private exporting
companies, which are required to report large sales to the
department. No selling prices or further details were released.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.26 per bushel at the
farm level, according to USDA's five-day average, meaning that the
latest sale could have a farm value of about $36 million.
</TEXT>
