<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0051EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru   10-06 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0407,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Bombs Explode in Bogota, Wound Two</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with bombings. Pickup 7th graf,
`One suspect...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs exploded late Thursday in
Bogota, injuring two people and damaging a supermarket and a bank,
police said. The attacks were believed to be the latest in a series
by drug traffickers.
   Also Thursday, President Virgilio Barco named new ministers of
justice, interior and communications. His government also announced
plans for referendum to let voters decide whether suspected drug
traffickers wanted in the United States should be extradited.
   A U.S. official in Bogota said that despite the goverment's
unprecedented crackdown on drugs, hundreds of tons of cocaine
continue to be smuggled into the United States.
   Police said citizens captured one man fleeing from the bombings
and turned him over to the authorites. The blasts damaged a
supermarket and bank about 1,200 feet apart, wounding two people,
police said.
   Since Aug. 23, when cocaine chieftains responded to the
government's crackdown by declaring a ``total war'' against it,
traffickers have been blamed for 148 bombings that have killed 10
people and wounded 165.
   The traffickers are trying to get the government to reverse its
stand on extradition.
   The government revived Colombia's extradition treaty with the
United States as part of the emergency measures imposed in a
crackdown on drug lords seven weeks ago.
   Barco's plan for a referendum was announced in a communique
issued by the minister of government, Orlando Vasquez, as one of
his last acts before resigning. Vasquez appeared to be a casualty
of political fighting in Barco's Liberal Party.
   The vote on whether suspected traffickers should be sent to the
United States for trial could come as early as January.
   One suspect has been extradited so far. Proceedings are under
way against another, and two more are being held pending the
arrival of U.S. documents asking for their extradition.
   Barco named Carlos Lemos Simmonds minister of interior, who is
in charge of the nation's police. He replaces Orlando Vasquez
Velasquez, who held the office since July 16. Simmonds was
communications minister and acting minister of justice since Monica
de Greiff resigned last month after death threats by drug
traffickers.
   Barco chose as his new justice minister Roberto Salazar
Manrique, a former treasury official and deputy director of the
national bank.
   The new minister of communications is Enrique Danies Rincones,
ex-governor of Guajira.
   The Cabinet announcements came in a statement by the
presidential press secretary.
   Colombia, with help from the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration, has tried destroying plantations of coca bushes
that are the source for cocaine and destroying laboratories and
chemicals.
   The DEA is now helping Colombian authorities set up a program
aimed at preventing chemicals from reaching traffickers, a U.S.
official said Thursday.
   The program will try to identify companies set up solely for
buying chemicals for cocaine labs, the official said at a briefing
for U.S. reporters. He spoke on condition he not be identified.
   Colombia's cocaine cartels are sending an estimated 3,300 to
4,400 tons of cocaine to the United States each year, the official
said.
   Chemicals used by the drug traffickers are coming mainly from
the United Sates, China, West Germany and the Netherlands, he said,
adding that the DEA will assure that chemicals from the United
States are headed for legitimate companies.
   The official said Colombian companies that import chemicals
often end up unknowingly selling the chemicals to fake companies
set up by cocaine lords.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
