<FIRST>r w PM-AIDSResearch     10-06 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Research,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Awards $9 Million for Expanded AIDS Drug Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government is ``reaching out'' to
women, minorities and drug users infected with AIDS by giving $9
million to community-based research programs in 14 cities,
officials say.
   The money will go to 18 programs that serve about 30,000 people
with AIDS. About a third of that number are black or Hispanic, 21
percent are intravenous drug users and 8 percent are women.
   ``The message is we're reaching out,'' said Dr. Anthony Fauci,
director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious
Diseases, which is distributing the funds.
   ``We're attempting to make available and accessible to the
community kinds of topnotch clinical research that has been
classically limited to the major medical centers.''
   Researchers say women, minorities and intravenous drug users are
under-represented in AIDS drug trials, largely because the research
is conducted at academic medical centers while most AIDS patients
get care from doctors in their own communities.
   Thursday's announcement of the programs selected for funding was
criticized by a losing applicant _ the Community Research
Initiative in New York, a pioneer of community-based AIDS research.
   CRI was the model for many of the more than two dozen
community-based research programs conducting clinical trials on
AIDS drugs. Most of the testing is sponsored by drug manufacturers.
   Those programs have helped move AIDS drug testing from the large
academic research centers into communities, where local physicians
and their AIDS patients can participate.
   CRI officials said they had not been told why they had been
excluded, but said it may have been a punishment for past
criticisms of federal research efforts.
   Fauci said the awards were decided by a panel of community
doctors, nurses, social workers, researchers and people infected
with the virus.
   The reviewers evaluated and ranked the proposals. The institute
then funded each in the order they appeared until the $9 million
was exhausted, Fauci said.
   He said that he could not, by law, discuss the merits of any
applicants, but that institute officials would discuss CRI's
application with CRI officials privately.
   However, Fauci did reject CRI's contention that past criticism
of federal research may have been a factor.
   ``I'm sorry CRI wasn't funded. I would have liked for them to
have been,'' Fauci said, adding there were more qualified programs
than there was available funding.
   ``The process I saw was rigorous and equitable,'' said reviewer
Jean McGuire of the AIDS Action Council.
   The programs selected include 11 with limited clinical
experience and seven that are capable of or have been conducting
clinical trials. They will receive from $278,000 to $800,000 for
the first year of a five-year contract.
   The programs with limited clinical experience are:
   Addiction Research and Treatment Corp. in Brooklyn, N.Y.;
Atlanta AIDS Research Consortium; Chicago Community Program for
Clinical Research on AIDS; Clinical Directors Network of Region II
in the Bronx and Brooklyn, N.Y., and Newark, N.J.; Comprehensive
AIDS Alliance of Detroit;
   Delaware Community Programs for Clinical Research on AIDS,
Dover, Del.; Harlem AIDS Treatment Group in New York; Hill Health
Center in New Haven, Conn.; Louisiana Community Program for
Clinical Research on AIDS in New Orleans and Baton Rouge, La.;
North Jersey AIDS Alliance in Newark, N.J.; and Phoenix Shanti
Group of Phoenix, Ariz.
   The programs with some clinical experience are:
   Bronx Lebanon Hospital in the Bronx, N.Y.; Denver Community
Program for Clinical Research on AIDS; Henry Ford Hospital in
Detroit; Research and Education Group, the Oregon AIDS Task Force
in Portland, Ore.; Richmond AIDS Consortium in Richmond, Va.; San
Francisco County Community Consortium; and the Veterans
Administration Center in Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
