<FIRST>r w PM-Children'sTV     10-06 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children's TV,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showdown Likely Over Children TV Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress may be heading for another showdown
with the White House on restricting advertising on children's
television shows.
   The Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee on
Thursday approved on a voice vote a bill that would limit ads on
shows aimed at children to 10{ minutes per hour on weekends and 12
minutes per hour weekdays.
   The bill also would condition a broadcaster's license renewal on
whether the station provided programs aimed at educating youngsters.
   President Bush hasn't said what he'll do if such legislation
reaches his desk, but the Justice Department is recommending he
veto it on grounds it unconstitutionally intrudes on TV program
content.
   The bill was a compromise between a television
industry-supported measure by Sens. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, and
Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., that passed Congress last year but was
vetoed by President Reagan, and a tougher measure proposed this
year by Sen. Tim Wirth, D-Colo.
   Introducing his bill, Metzenbaum cited a dramatic increase in
the amount of advertising on children's shows since the Federal
Communications Commission repealed ad limits in 1984. He said some
programs urge young viewers to dial 900 telephone numbers to hear
taped messages from cartoon characters.
   The House has passed the Metzenbaum version.
   After the bill was approved Thursday, Sen. Daniel Inouye,
D-Hawaii, persuaded the committee not to send it to the Senate for
30 days.
   Inouye, who has bitterly attacked what he calls ``rubbish'' on
television, said he wanted to consult broadcasters and consider
further changes in the bill.
   Committee Chairman Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., agreed to a request
by Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., that the committee consider extending
the bill's restrictions to cable television.
   Inouye said studies have shown that youngsters, on average,
watch between three hours and five hours of TV a day, while
spending less than an hour on homework. Young children lack the
ability to distinguish between commercials and programs, and
working parents often can't supervise what their children watch,
Inouye said.
   The Senate bill also would require the FCC to be more responsive
to complaints about so-called program-length commercials that
feature toys.
   This bill, Inouye said, ``is the least we owe our children.''
   Until 1984, the FCC had limited commercials on children's
programs to 9{ minutes per hour weekends and 12 minutes weekdays.
Wirth's bill would have reimposed those standards.
   Wirth's bill also would have reclassified program-length
commercials as advertisements, thereby effectively eliminating them.
   In other action Thursday, the committee, on voice votes:
   _Approved a bill to require broadcasters to provide the lowest
possible rates to political candidates and make the ads
non-pre-emptible.
   _Authorized FCC spending of $109.8 million for fiscal 1990 and
$117.8 million for fiscal 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
