<HEAD>White House Aide is New SEC Commissioner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House aide Richard C. Breeden, President
Bush's choice to head the Securities and Exchange Commission, is
clearing his calendar and planning when he would take office
following his Senate confirmation.
   The Senate in a late-night session Wednesday approved Breeden's
nomination on a voice vote, several hours after he had been
unanimously recommended by the Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs
Committee.
   Although Breeden is the numerical replacement for departing SEC
member Charles C. Cox, he is expected to be named by Bush to head
the agency that oversees securities markets, regulates the sale of
stocks, bonds and stock options and enforces securities laws.
   David Ruder, the previous chairman, returned to teaching law at
Northwestern University on Sept. 30. In the interim, Bush has
appointed SEC member Edward H. Fleischman as acting chairman.
   Breeden, 39, a 1975 graduate of Harvard Law School who was
deputy counsel from 1982-85 for then-Vice President Bush, has
served the president in a variety of capacities, most recently as
an architect of the legislation that helped bail out the nation's
ailing savings and loan industry.
   Breeden sailed through confirmation hearings before the Banking
Committee last month.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Making Social Security Independent Would Be `Devastating,' HHS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Chief Says
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan, reiterating the Bush administration's position, says a
move in Congress to make the Social Security Administration an
independent agency would be ``devastating'' to the elderly.
   ``This would be devastating for senior Americans'' because it
would disrupt services to them, Sullivan told a National Press Club
luncheon audience Thursday.
   He also said it would mean the ``serious and legitimate concerns
regarding care and support of our senior citizens will lose Cabinet
level advocacy.''
   Social Security is now part of the Department of Health and
Human Services.
   Supporters of the proposals in Congress say that making Social
Security an independent federal agency would give it increased
visibility and would protect its trust funds from being tapped for
other uses.
   Measures to make Social Security independent of HHS are in the
budget reconciliation bill passed by the House on Thursday and in
the Senate's reconciliation bill that will be acted on soon.
   ``If the system ain't broke, don't fix it,'' Sullivan said,
``and we maintain that the system (Social Security) is working
better than ever.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Toy Maker Recalling Rattles</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A toy maker is voluntarily recalling a rattle
because it could present a choking, breathing or eating hazard to
small children, the manufacturer and a safety commission say.
   The rattles may be broken in use and expose small parts that
could be eaten or swallowed by small children and cause them to
choke, said a statement released Thursday by the Consumer Product
Safety Commission.
   Some 60,000 of the rattles, which have a center section shaped
as a bear's face, butterfly, ball or train engine, were sold
nationwide through J.C. Penney stores.
   The toy maker, Louisiana-based Mini-Togs, Inc., said the rattles
were distributed with two baby bibs, but the recall involves only
``Baby Bib'' model 200.
   No choking incidents have been reported, but consumers should
immediately return the rattles for $1.00 refunds from the stores
where they were purchased, the safety commission said.
</TEXT>
