<FIRST>u a AM-NursingHomeFire 3rdLd-Writethru a0452 10-06 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Home Fire, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0452,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nine Dead In Nursing Home Blaze</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with authorities correcting death
total to nine. Picks up 6th graf, `Daze and ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine people were killed and scores
hospitalized Thursday night when a fire broke out in a 160-bed
nursing home, authorities said.
   The fire was reported shortly after 10:30 p.m. on the second
floor of the Hillhaven Rehabilitation and Convalescent Center, a
four-story brick structure, said Norfolk Fire Chief Thomas E.
Gardner.
   ``We've avoided a really major disaster,'' Gardner said.
   The cause and extent of the fire, which was extinguished after
midnight, were not immediately known.
   Authorities said seven bodies had been accounted for at the
scene, and two more people were dead on arrival at Sentara Norfolk
General Hospital.
   Dazed and confused, Hillhaven residents were taken to nearby
yards where firefighters, paramedics and neighbors tried to calm
them and keep them warm against the night air.
   Inside the structure, firefighters found scores of bedridden
patients whom they gingerly guided down ladders and smoke-filled
hallways. Some patients were in their bedclothes; others were
naked. All seemed frightened.
   Many of those overcome by smoke were taken to Sentara Norfolk
General Hospital.
   Among them was Robert J. Bell, 82, who said he was in his room
on the second floor when the fire broke out.
   ``I woke up in a roomful of smoke,'' he said. ``The whole room
was saturated with smoke. You couldn't see and you couldn't hardly
breathe.''
   Another second-floor resident, who was treated in the hospital's
emergency room, 76-year-old Harriett Waddill, said:
   ``Everything was quiet. We were going to bed. All of a sudden we
heard this commotion in the hall. They were running up and down the
hall and they were yelling, `Get him out of the room.' It was
getting so black I couldn't even identify where my bed was.''
   Hillhaven staff members knelt at the sides of many patients who
were not immediately taken to hospitals.
   One man, who knelt between two patients, patted their heads and
rubbed their shoulders, all the while telling them: ``You're safe.
It will be all right.''
</TEXT>
