<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia     10-06 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Justice Minister Named; Two Injured in Explosions in Bogota</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Virgilio Barco named a new
justice minister to lead Colombia's crackdown on drug traffickers
after they sent death threats to the previous official and
reportedly warned other candidates for the job.
   His government also announced plans Thursday for a referendum on
whether suspected drug traffickers should be extradited to the
United States.
   Late Thursday, two bombs exploded at a supermarket and a bank in
Bogota, injuring two people, police said.The explosions were
believed part of the traffickers' violent response to the
government's unprecedented 7-week-old crackdown on drugs.
   Since Aug. 23, when cocaine chieftains declared a ``total war''
against the government, traffickers have been blamed for 148
bombings that have killed 10 people and wounded 165.
   A government spokesman said Roberto Salazar Manrique, former
treasury official and deputy director of the national bank,
accepted the job as justice minister.
   But five people, including three government officials, turned
down the post after receiving death threats from drug traffickers,
according to Colombian news reports.
   Traffickers from the powerful Medellin cartel are blamed in the
1984 slaying of Justice Minister Rodrigo Lara Bonilla. Since 1981,
about 50 judges and 170 judicial employees have been killed.
   Traffickers also threatened Salazar's predecessor, Monica de
Greiff, who quit on Sept. 21 after disagreements with President
Virgilio Barco on the country's anti-drug policy. Salazar becomes
Barcos' ninth justice minister.
   As justice minister, Salazar heads the government's war against
trafficking. He processes extraditions of Colombian drug
traffickers to the United States.
   As part of emergency measures declared during the crackdown, the
government revived Colombia's extradition treaty with the United
States.
   Cocaine bosses have enjoyed relative impunity from Colombian
courts through payoffs or intimidation of judges and they want the
government to reverse its stand on extradition.
   So far just one suspect has been extradited, but proceedings are
under way against another. Two more are being held pending the
arrival of U.S. documents asking for their extradition.
   Barco's plan for a referendum on the extradition issue was
announced in a communique late Thursday. The vote could come as
early as January.
   The naming of a new Justice Minister came as part of Barco's
second Cabinet change in three months. Communications Minister
Carlos Lemos Simmonds was named interior minister.
   Replacing him at the Communications Ministry will be Enrique
Danies Rincones, the former governor of Guajira state.
   The army late Thursday caught three alleged hired assassins just
before they were to meet with leaders of the Medellin cartel,
according to national television news.
   The army reportedly caught the two men and one woman on a farm
in Versalles, in the state of Antioquia, which includes the city of
Medellin.
   The three were reportedly waiting for Pablo Escobar and Gonzalo
Rodriguez Gacha, who together with Jorge Luis Ochoa, are thought to
control the Medellin cartel.
   The Barco administration has offered a $250,000 reward for
information leading to the capture of Rodriguez and Escobar, both
on the list of 12 Colombian drug figures most wanted for
extradition.
   The Barco government declared war on the traffickers following
the Aug. 18 assassination of leading presidential candidate Luis
Carlos Galan, an anti-drug crusader.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
