<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-06 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Share Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened against the Japanese yen
Friday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined.
   The dollar closed at 142.45 yen, up 1.40 yen from Thursday's
close of 141.05 yen. It opened at 141.95 yen and ranged between
141.80 yen and 142.75 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 140.19-point
gainer Thursday, shed 313.64 points, or 0.88 percent, closing at
35,209.35.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's strength followed a
surprising upswing in overseas markets Thursday despite interest
rate hikes by central banks of West Germany and several other
European countries.
   The Bundesbank, West Germany's central bank, raised its key
lending rates by 1 percentage point, including the official
discount rate to 6 percent, to help curb the dollar's strength and
stem inflationary pressures in that country.
   Central banks in Britain, France and other European nations made
similar moves.
   The discount rate, the rate a nation's central bank charges on
loans to commercial banks, has a strong impact on other domestic
interest rates. Higher interest rates tend to support a currency.
   Masaaki Tanahashi, a dealer with Mitsui Bank, said Japan's
central bank stepped into the market intermittently during early
trading to sell dollars, but said ``The intervention helped
little'' to stop the dollar's upward pressure.
   The Bank of Japan does not comment on its monetary activities,
but traders estimated the size of the intervention at about $100
million.
   Tanahashi said the market was awaiting U.S. unemployment figures
for September, due out later Friday in Washington, as a factor in
finding the dollar's direction.
   Meanwhile, Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto told a news
conference Friday morning that Japan will watch carefully for any
impact from the West Germany's interest rate raise, but said Japan
``isn't thinking of changing its monetary policy'' for now.
   On the stock market, the market's main barometer held back for
the first time in three days, due to the West German interest hikes
and the yen's easing against the dollar, stock dealers said.
   They said concern over the upcoming U.S. jobless rate was
another factor keeping many investors on the sidelines.
</TEXT>
