<FIRST>r a PM-WafieAwards     10-06 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wafie Awards,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Cuisine Honors Its Gustatory Heroes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The creators of California cuisine dined on
salmon-stuffed grape leaves and other delicacies as they dished out
awards to the top contributors to the state's gustatory scene.
   Besides honoring its best and brightest at the awards ceremony
Wednesday night, the American Institute of Wine and Food celebrated
what members said was California's contribution to changing
American tastes.
   ``Northern California has been in the forefront of new ideas and
developments in cuisine,'' said master of ceremonies Narsai David,
who received the top citation, for education.
   ``What was called `California cuisine' has become American
cuisine _ freshly prepared superb ingredients, frequently served
with the very simplest of sauces,'' said David, food authority,
wine expert, shopkeeper, three-star restaurateur and commentator in
the San Francisco Bay area for 25 years.
   Some 240 epicures paid $60 a plate to dine on an impressive
variety of delicacies at the Californian Culinary Academy and to
salute the winners of the 10 Wine and Food Achievement, or
``Wafie'' awards.
   Guests enjoyed hors d'oeuvres that included smoked chicken with
honey mustard; grape leaves stuffed with salmon, fried artichokes,
goat cheese with sun-dried tomatoes, and sauteed Texas venison
marinated in cabernet.
   Those who weren't already full then sat down to crayfish with
caviar dressing, quail and lentils, and rack of lamb with elephant
garlic. The courses were accompanied by select chardonnay, pinot
noir and cabernet sauvignon. All the foods and wines were donated.
   Other ``Wafie'' winners included Jerry DiVeccchio of Sunset
Magazine, for literature and journalism; winemaker Zelma Long of
Simi Winery; chef Alice Waters of Chez Panisse; pioneer California
oyster farmers Michael Watchorn and John Finger; and Chuck Williams
of Williams-Sonoma, the kitchen accessory chain whose glossy
catalog is mailed to 77 million people.
</TEXT>
