<FIRST>r a PM-RapeAcquittal     10-06 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rape Acquittal,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women's Groups Outraged at Jury's Decision Blaming Woman for Rape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The acquittal of a rape suspect on
grounds that the woman wore a lace miniskirt with no underwear was
a ``horrendous'' verdict that could deter victims from prosecuting
rapists, counselors said.
   ``No woman asks to be raped,'' Dorothea Gallagher of the
National Organization for Women's Broward County chapter said
Thursday. ``I can't think of any other crime in which people would
say that the victim asked for it.''
   A jury of three men and three women said just that in explaining
their acquittal of Steven Lord, 26, on kidnapping and rape charges
Wednesday.
   ``She asked for it,'' foreman Roy Diamond said. ``The way she
was dressed with that skirt, you could see everything she had. She
was advertising for sex.''
   ``She was obviously dressed for a good time, but we felt she may
have bit off more than she could chew,'' juror Mary Bradshaw said.
   According to testimony, the 22-year-old woman wore a tank top
and a short, white lace skirt without underwear last Nov. 6, the
night she said she was raped.
   Alexander Siegel, the woman's attorney, said his client was
``bewildered, shocked, angry, astounded'' by the verdict.
   Detective Tom White of the Indian River County Sheriff's
Department, who worked on the case, termed the acquittal ``very
disappointing.''
   ``I honestly believe as a police officer that he raped her, that
he forcibly had sex with her,'' White said. ``I took her to the
emergency room. We took her clothing and her car into evidence, we
caught him the following day.''
   White said the woman told him that Lord took off her underwear
when he allegedly raped her the first time.
   Joanne Richter, director of the Sexual Assault Treatment Center
in Fort Lauderdale, said the verdict could discourage rape victims
from prosecuting their attackers.
   ``No matter who you are or what you are wearing, it doesn't mean
you should be a victim of sexual assault,'' Richter said. ``I am
having a hard time believing that people think that if you're not
dressed appropriately that you should be a victim of sexual
assault.''
   ``It's a fairly horrendous verdict,'' said Ellen Vargyas at the
National Women's Law Center in Washington, D.C.
   At the trial, the woman said Lord pulled a knife on her in a
Fort Lauderdale restaurant parking lot, forced her into her car,
drove north on Interstate 95, and pulled over twice to rape her at
knife-point.
   Defense attorney Tim Day told jurors the woman agreed to have
sex with Lord in exchange for $100 and cocaine, but later changed
her mind.
   ``How could anyone think that someone would want to be cut up
with a knife, hit with a rock and raped?'' Siegel said. ``They put
her on trial.''
   That's common, though, said Sally Goldfarb, staff attorney at
the NOW Legal Defense and Education Fund in New York.
   ``In most rape trials it's the victim, not the suspect, that's
on trial,'' she said.
   Barbara Mitchell, who heads the sexual crimes and child abuse
section of the Broward State Attorney's Office, said the attitudes
reflected in the jurors' comments die hard.
   ``I thought we had done a better job educating the public,'' she
said. ``We'll have to try it again.''
</TEXT>
