<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--HugoName     10-06 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Hugo Name,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>It's All In a Name, Hugo Residents Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUGO, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some folks in this small southeastern
Oklahoma town think the worst hurricane of the decade has given
their home a bad name.
   ``We want people in Charleston, South Carolina, to know that the
name Hugo doesn't always hurt,'' said William Rogers, president of
the local Lions Club.
   To prove it, Mayor Charles Sims proclaimed this week ``Help
Charleston Week,'' and Lions Club members organized a food drive
that netted nearly $7,000 in goods.
   A rented trailer will leave Monday to deliver the provisions to
Lions Club members in Charleston, Rogers said.
   Hurricane Hugo slammed into South Carolina Sept. 21 with winds
topping 135 mph, killing at least 18 and leaving 50,000 homeless.
   ``We just want them to know that the folks here in Hugo are a
lot friendlier than that hurricane was,'' Rogers said.
</TEXT>
