<FIRST>r a PM-SchoolEvacuation     10-06 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Evacuation,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nearly 300 Sickened as Furnace Leaks Fumes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TILTONSVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carbon monoxide fumes that sickened
nearly 300 people at a high school seeped from a cracked furnace
just after it was turned on for the first time this fall, the
district superintendent said.
   Dozens of students suffered headaches and nausea and a handful
briefly passed out Thursday morning at Buckeye Southwest High
School when the fumes wafted through ventilating systems into all
three floors of the school.
   Twenty-nine people were listed in fair or satisfactory condition
at two hospitals today. Three of the patients were in intensive
care for closer observation, including one with an asthmatic
condition, a hospital spokesman said.
   Another 256 people were sent home from the hospitals on
Thursday, officials said.
   An inspection uncovered a crack in one of the four furnaces in
the school's basement, said Ann Stephens, Buckeye Local Schools
Superintendent.
   Inspectors who conducted an annual examination in August didn't
find the crack.
   ``It was inside the furnace _ you can't see it without totally
tearing the furnace apart,'' Ms. Stephens said.
   Carbon monoxide fumes began escaping about 6 a.m. when
custodians turned on the gas heating system for the first time this
fall, Assistant Fire Chief Gary McHugh said. Firefighters were
called about 10:30 a.m. after students began complaining of nausea,
headaches, light-headedness and shortness of breath, he said.
   ``If they'd been in there for at least two more hours, it could
have been worse,'' McHugh said. ``A few of them could have died.''
   Authorities evacuted about 450 students and at least 25 teachers
from the school, which is about 5 miles up the Ohio River from
Wheeling, W.Va.
   Some 181 people were taken to Ohio Valley Medical Center in
Wheeling, where 21 were admitted and listed in fair condition,
hospital spokesman Chap Holbert said.
   Another 104 people were taken to East Ohio Regional Hospital in
Martins Ferry, where seven were listed in satisfactory condition
this morning and one was fair, Holbert said.
   All those admitted had low to moderate levels of carbon monoxide
in their blood, said Dr. Bruce Walmsley, coordinator emergency
services at both hospitals.
   The school probably will remain closed until Monday, and carbon
monoxide tests will be conducted daily to make sure the gas has
dissipated, Ms. Stephens said.
</TEXT>
