<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Japan-US     10-06 0109</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Japan-US,0111</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Vice Foreign Minister New U.S. Ambassador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese government today named Ryohei Murata,
former administrative vice-minister for foreign affairs, as its new
ambassador to the United States, the Foreign Ministry said.
   Murata will be officially appointed to the post Monday,
replacing Nobuo Matsunaga, who is retiring from foreign service.
   Murata, 59, joined the Foreign Ministry in 1952 and served as
first secretary and counselor at the Japanese Embassy in Washington
from 1970 and 1972. In 1987, he became deputy vice-minister for
foreign affairs. He was promoted to administrative vice-minister
for foreign affairs later in 1987 and joined the foreign minister's
secretariat in August.
