<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0649EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     10-06 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Find Bodies of 21 Youths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 21 Sinhalese youths were shot
and killed, apparently by a vigilante group in retaliation for the
slaying of a volunteer solider, military officials said today.
   Authorities today found the bodies today 60 miles northeast of
Colombo, in central Kandy district. It brought to 39 the number of
slain youths found in the area in two days. Those found Thursday
had been beheaded or fatally shot, then dumped on a university
campus.
   Military officials blamed pro-government vigilante groups for
both massacres.
   The slayings on Wednesday and Thursday were to avenge the death
of a volunteer soldier gunned down by two unidentified men on a
bicycle, the officials said on condition of anonyity. Edward
Nagahawatta, an assistant registrar at the university, was killed
inside the campus Wednesday, officials said.
   The country's eight universities were closed more than two years
ago because of student unrest. The government contends the campuses
are a stronghold of the People's Liberation Front, an extremist
Sinhalese group that advocates overthrowing the govenrment.
   Military officials said on condition of anonymity that the 21
victims were found today around the town of Kandy.
   Two bodies were discovered in the main bus terminal in Kandy, 15
were found in Gelioya village and the remaining four, in Mahiyawa
village, officials said.
   Elsewhere, five people were killed in southern Sri Lanka, the
govnerment said without elaboration.
   Human rights groups say the military and vigilante groups
routinely kill sympathizers of the Sinhalese militants. The
government denies the charge.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa called a meeting with opposition
parties last month to try to resolve ethnic differences dividing
the Indian Ocean island.
   The front refused to attend the peace conference and spurned a
temporary truce called last week by government forces. At least 80
people were killed during the six-day truce, which expired Tuesday.
   The front has rejected all peace offers from the government,
saying it wants Premadasa to resign because he came to power in
what they called fraduulent elections in December 1988.
   When it began its campaign in 1987, the Sinhalese front opposed
the government's peace overtures to Tamil separatists demanding an
independent homeland in the northeast. It also objected to the
Indian peacekeeping soldiers deployed in Sri Lanka to help
implement a peace treaty with Tamil guerrillas.
   The soldiers will be pulled out by Dec. 31, the Indian
government has said.
   At least 11,000 people, including 1,000 Indian soldiers, have
died in the 6-year-old Tamil rebellion. Tamils say they are
discriminated against by the majority Sinhalese in jobs and
education.
   The predominantly-Buddhist Sinhalese make up 75 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people and control the government and military.
Tamils comprise 18 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
