<FIRST>r a PM-IllegalDrivers     10-06 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Illegal Drivers,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Estimates 150,000 Drive Illegally in Massachusetts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 300,000 Massachusetts motorists have had
their licenses suspended, and state officials estimate at least
half of those are continuing to drive illegally.
   The statistics have prompted the Registry of Motor Vehicles to
begin taking away the license plates of drivers caught behind the
wheel with suspended driving licenses, officials said.
   State Registrar Robert M. Hutchinson Jr. released the figures on
license suspensions during a news conference Thursday where he
defended the registry's decision to reinstate the driver's license
of a man charged with killing a 10-year-old girl while driving
drunk in New Hampshire on Sunday.
   Following the arrest of Peter Dushame of North Andover, the
registry said his license had been suspended and that he was
driving illegally when he allegedly hit Lacey Parker in Nashua.
   But Hutchinson said Thursday that Dushame had a valid license at
the time of the accident. He said either ``human or technical
error'' led authorities to believe initially that Dushame's license
was still under suspension.
   The registry suspended Dushame's license in March 1988 after
being notified by New Hampshire authorities that he had been
convicted of a serious motor vehicle offense there.
   Hutchinson declined to identify the offense, citing privacy laws.
   According to the New Hampshire Division of Motor Vehicles,
Dushame's record includes two drunken driving convictions there
since 1986, the year that state began notifying Massachusetts
authorities of vehicle offenses committed in New Hampshire by
Massachusetts drivers.
   Hutchinson said the registry was aware of only one offense by
Dushame in New Hampshire. Dushame would have received a longer
suspension if the registry known of the other conviction, he said.
   Dushame's sister, Beth Davis, said he got his license back about
two months ago.
   Asked whether the registry acted properly by returning his
license, Hutchinson said, ``Based upon the law at the time, we
acted correctly, yes.''
</TEXT>
