<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0740EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Norway     10-06 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Norway,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norway's Labor Government To Resign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIK A. WOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland's
government will step down next week rather than be ousted by a
right-wing coalition, a spokesman for the Labor Party leader
announced today.
   The announcement comes one month after her party suffered its
greatest postwar election defeat.
   Mrs. Brundtland's 3-year-old administration will be replaced by
the three-party right-wing coalition led by Jan P. Syse of the
Conservative Party.
   ``She will inform the Parliament on Oct. 12 and hand in the
government's resignation to King Olav on Friday the 13th,'' said
spokesman Arne Strand.
   The alliance said it was ready to call for a vote of
no-confidence on Oct. 24 if Mrs. Brundtland refused to resign.
   Labor will go ahead with plans to present its 1990 national
budget to the new 165-seat Parliament before resigning, Strand said.
   ``Mrs. Brundtland's Cabinet will serve as a caretaker government
over the weekend. On Monday, the way is open for a non-socialist
government,'' he said.
   Syse, 58, presented a basic platform for his non-socialist
minority coalition on Wednesday after two weeks of negotiations.
The three partners are working on distributing Cabinet posts.
   The vaguely worded platform papered over differences among the
new partners and increased doubts among analysts on whether the
alliance can last a full four-year term.
   The new government of the Conservative, Christian Democrat and
Center parties will have a precarious hold on power, controlling 62
of the 165 seats in parliament. It will have to rely on support
from the far-right 22-seat Party of Progress.
   Labor has 63 seats, and the Labor-allied Socialist Left party
has 17. There is one independent.
   On Wednesday Mrs. Brundtland called the non-socialist program
``unfit as government platform,'' and said it ignores difficult
questions.
   Progress Party chairman Carl I. Hagen, whose anti-socialist
party was shunned by the centrist partners, said he would vote
against Mrs. Brundtland, but would not pledge loyalty to the
coalition unless his party was a full partner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
