<FIRST>r a PM-ChildrenThrown     10-06 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children Thrown,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Mother Pushed Her Children Out Window</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother who told her children ``God is waiting
for you'' pushed her 6-year-old daughter and 3-year-old son out a
10th-floor window, killing the girl and critically injuring the
boy, authorities said.
   Firefighters broke down the apartment door Thursday afternoon
just in time to stop the naked woman from pushing a 1-year-old
daughter through the window's protective bars, saving that child
and two others, said fire Lt. John Lane.
   ``She was mumbling `Mohammed, Elijah,' she was trying to move
the children along to the window to jump and she was going to jump
also,'' said Lane, one of the first rescuers to reach the apartment.
   ``She told the children, `God is waiting for you,' '' he said.
   Meenah Abdussalaam, 32, her daughter, Zainab, and son, Husein,
were taken to St. John's Episcopal Hospital.
   Zainab died of her injuries, hospital spokeswoman Nancy Uzo said.
   Husein was transferred to North Shore University Hospital in
neighboring Nassau County, where he was in extremely critical
condition late Thursday after surgery, hospital spokeswoman Carol
Hauptman said.
   The mother, who was unhurt, was being evaluated at St. John's.
Dr. Russell Beavers told reporters she ``seemed distant ... not
cognizant of what was going on.''
   Mrs. Abdussalaam was charged early today with murder, attempted
murder and endangering the welfare of children, said Sgt. Pete
Berry, a police spokesman.
   Firefighters who happened to be passing by and saw the first
child fall forced their way into a barricaded bedroom and found the
mother and three children: 1-year-old Amna, her 8-year-old brother,
Askia, and 4-year-old sister, Fatima. All were naked.
   Police managed to grab the mother as she was sliding Amna out
between the window bars.
   Lane said Mrs. Abdussalaam punched the firefighter who broke
down the bedroom door.
   Neighbors described Mrs. Abdussalaam as quiet and polite, a good
mother and devout Moslem whose husband had recently moved out. Some
said her husband left her; others said she kicked him out.
   The husband, Sultan Abdussalaam, 35, was at work at the time of
the incident, police said.
   The three uninjured children were turned over to city welfare
workers.
   Police said Mrs. Abdussalaam had been notified she would be
evicted from her five-room apartment, which is in a federally
subsidized building in a middle-class neighborhood.
   Building superintendent Kevin Rafferty denied the eviction
report but said Mrs. Abdussalaam had been notified her rent was 10
days overdue. He said the family lived in the building for 12 years
without incident.
   Ann Sessa, president of the building's tenant association, said
Mrs. Abdussalaam was ``very careful with the children,'' who were
always clean and polite.
   ``It was always, `Yes, Ma'am,' `No, Ma'am,''' Mrs. Sessa said.
   Firefighters were passing the building when they saw the girl
pushed from the window, department spokeswoman Efrain Parilla said.
   ``(They) saw one child, a girl, hanging by her hands from the
window ledge of the apartment. They started shouting, `Don't jump,'
and as they did so, they saw the child trying to get back on the
ledge,'' Parilla said. ``She lifted a leg and tried to get back on
the ledge, then the firefighters saw an arm come out of the window
and push the child away.''
   As the firefighters rushed up, they saw the boy hanging out the
same window, Lane recalled.
   ``We said `Oh God, don't jump, we're here, we want to help
you,'' said the 28-year veteran firefighter, his voice shaking with
emotion.
   Firefighters stretched out their hands and partially broke the
boy's fall, said Lucy Bartholomew, who lives directly beneath the
Abdussalaams' apartment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
