<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Politics     10-06 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kaifu Assured Of Two More Years As Ruling Party President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister and governing party president
Toshiki Kaifu, in office less than two months, was assured of two
more years as the Liberal Democratic chief when he registered as
the only candidate for the post.
   No other Liberal Democrats filed papers to oppose Kaifu's
candidacy by today's 11 a.m. deadline, said Seisuke Okuno, head of
the party's election management committee.
   Kaifu, 58, will be formally declared party president without
balloting at a party convention on Oct. 31, he said.
   He will remain prime minister as long as the Liberal Democrats
retain their majority in Parliament, or until his term as party
president expires in October 1991.
   Kaifu, in a policy statement attached to his application,
pledged to restore public trust in the party and promote political
reform.
   ``The serious objective of the party now is to make politics
trustworty for the public and stabilize the political situation,''
Kaifu said in a statement released today.
   He also called for a dialogue with communist bloc nations,
preserving the global environment and combating drug abuse.
   On Aug. 9, Kaifu became the party head and prime minister
because of the party's overwhelming majority in Parliament. He
replaced Sousuke Uno, who stepped down to take responsibility for
the party's poor showing in an election for the upper house of
Parliament.
   It was the first time the party lost control of a house of
Parliament in its 34 years.
   Uno resigned after only two months in office. He followed Noboru
Takeshita, who resigned June 2 because of links to a widespread
influence-peddling scandal.
   Although Kaifu has been in office less than two months, party
rules require the president to face another election when his
predecessor's term expires. Kaifu is currently serving the term
originally given to Takeshita, who was elected in November 1987.
   Although Kaifu was elected party president with a wide margin
over two candidates, he was seen as a short-term prime minister
because he was seen as neither possessing premier credentials nor
the political support to stay in power.
   Kaifu belongs to a small faction of his party, and has not held
top Cabinet or party posts _ credeitials generally required for the
premiership.
   The Liberal Democrats have been thrown into crisis following
bribery and sex scandals, as well as strong public opposition to a
new consumption tax.
   The Liberal Democrats face a severe challenge from opposition
parties in general elections for the more powerful Lower House,
which could come as early as next spring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
