<FIRST>r a PM-Lites Sub a0417 10-06 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites, Sub, a0417,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf of LACONIA, N.H.-dated first item to restore dropped
word, `the.'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LACONIA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Episcopal priest says he'll be happy to
bless pets this weekend, but he's laid down some commandments for
owners.
   ``If you bring large animals, be prepared to clean up after
them,'' the Rev. Robert Chrisman said.
   Chrisman will bless animals at St. James Episcopal Church Sunday
for the feast of St. Francis. He said it's appropriate because St.
Francis is the patron saint of animals.
   ``God has given us these animals to care for,'' he said.
   According to a recent issue of the church bulletin, ``Father Bob
is experienced in blessing all sorts of animals,'' but asks that
dogs be on leashes and cats and smaller animals be in cages or
otherwise confined. He also specifies ``no poisonous reptiles,''
the bulletin said.
   The blessing will last about a half-hour, Chrisman said, and
will include a short scripture reading, prayers and ``a bit of
teaching, focusing on the care of animals.''
</TEXT>
