<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Trooper-Rape     10-06 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Trooper-Rape,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trooper Convicted for Raping Motorist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALLSTON SPA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state trooper convicted of raping a
motorist he stopped for a traffic violation faces up to 25 years in
prison.
   Robert O. Bennett Jr. was found guilty Thursday of first-degree
rape, two counts of first-degree sodomy, first-degree sexual abuse,
first-degree coercion, unlawful imprisonment and official
misconduct in the September 1988 incident.
   Saratoga County Judge Frank Williams scheduled sentencing for
Dec. 4. The eight-year veteran trooper could receive up to 25 years.
   Bennett, 36, of Halfmoon, was charged with attacking the woman,
a 30-year-old college professor, while patrolling I-87 in Saratoga
County.
   The woman testified that Bennett stopped her for an improper
lane change and erratic driving and took her to a wooded area and
raped her.
   She said she kept the incident secret until days later when she
called a Rape Crisis hotline. State police were eventually notified
and began an investigation.
</TEXT>
