<FIRST>r i PM-Belgium-Slaying     10-06 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Belgium-Slaying,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend Funeral of Jewish Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 people today attended the
funeral of a Jewish leader who was gunned down in Brussels, and an
unknown group claimed responsibility for the slaying in the name of
a ``free Palestine.''
   Foreign Minister Mark Eyskens and Justice Minister Melchior
Wathelet were among those paying their last respects to Dr. Joseph
Wybran, the head of Belgium's Jewish community.
   Wybran, 49, was shot Tuesday evening outside the Brussels
University Hospital, where he headed the immunology department. He
died early Wednesday of a gunshot wound to the head.
   In a letter to several newspapers, a group calling itself
``Young Palestine, Proud and Free,'' claimed responsibility for the
shooting and said more attacks would follow.
   ``Our demands are simple: a free Palestine for a free people.
The first victim was Wybran,'' the letter said. The group said it
was made up of ``young revolutionaries, trained and supported by
the PLO.''
   Shawqi Armali, a Palestine Liberation Organization
representative in Brussels, denied any knowledge of the group and
condemned the killing.
   It was the second claim of responsibility for Wybran's slaying.
   On Thursday, an underground group in Lebanon calling itself
Soldiers of Justice said it killed Wybran and claimed he was a spy
for Israel.
   Police have reported no progress in their search for the killer
of Wybran, who recently campaigned for the removal of an order of
Roman Catholic nuns from the grounds of the former Auschwitz
concentration camp in Poland.
</TEXT>
