<FIRST>r a PM-Colombians-Security     10-06 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombians-Security,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombians Take Security Classes at Training Center</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUNSWICK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly two dozen Colombian security
officials have received 14 days' specialized instruction in the
United States on survival training and court security to help their
country battle cocaine cartels.
   The training session at the Federal Law Enforcement Training
Center was held by the U.S. Marshals Service at the request of the
State Department. The Colombian government had requested help in
training employees who protect judges and others in the judicial
system.
   Twenty-three Colombians from several ``policing'' agencies
received instruction in court security, personal protection and
survival training at the center before returning to Colombia on
Saturday, said Frank Skroski, deputy chief of training for the
Marshals Service.
   ``We modified our program to accommodate their specific needs,''
Skroski said. ``They were a very serious group, and they worked
long and hard.''
   He said although there are similar training programs conducted
across the country by the State Department, this site was ideal for
the Colombians because it had Spanish-speaking instructors.
   Cocaine cartels have been blamed for the deaths of at least 220
Colombian judges, politicians and other officials who have tried to
crack down on the drug trade in recent years.
   When the Colombian goverment this summer began a renewed cocaine
crackdown in conjunction with the United States, drug barons
threatened to kill 10 judges for every suspected drug dealer
extradited to the United States for trial.
   President Bush supported the crackdown, which began in August
after a leading presidential candidate was assassinated, by issuing
a $65 million military emergency aid package for the country,
including bulletproof vests, combat helicopters and grenade
launchers.
   A $2 million program to aid Colombian judges and others
threatened by cartel hit men was also announced by Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh.
</TEXT>
