<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1108EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-States-Fiscal     10-06 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-States-Fiscal,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Declining Revenues in Some States Seen Posing National Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Declining tax revenues in Northeastern states
may spell economic trouble for the nation as a whole, state
officials said today.
   ``Growth of the national economy has helped the fiscal condition
of many states,'' said Raymond G. Scheppach, executive director of
the National Governors' Association.
   ``But at the same time, spending pressures on the states have
continued to build,'' he said, citing increased costs from
congressional action on catastrophic illness insurance, Medicaid
and other programs.
   Scheppach said many states closed out fiscal 1989 with ending
balances higher than the previous year's, because they anticipated
economic slowdowns that did not occur.
   Scheppach spoke at a news conference as the governors'
association and the National Association of State Budget Officers
released their annual fiscal survey of the states.
   The survey reported that total state ending balances in fiscal
1989 were higher than in 1988.
   It also showed, however, that many Northeastern states _ often
an index of trends in the national economy _ reported declining
ending balances in 1989 and revenues below estimates.
   ``The rapid decline in revenues in these states could portend
downturns in other states,'' the two groups said.
   Scheppach said early indications from several Northeastern
states is that they are ``seeing no revenue growth at all'' in the
first three months of fiscal 1990.
   The fiscal year ends on June 30 in 46 states. It ends on March
31 in New York, on Aug. 31 in Texas and on Sept. 30 in Michigan and
Alabama.
</TEXT>
