<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-Part 1stLd-Writethru a0516 10-06 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Part, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0516,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede STORM LAKE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Odd Harvest: Farmers Finding Clues to Sioux City Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with five sted one farmer collecting
rewards; but disk considered key piece of evidence still missing; other
details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. has paid $4,700 to five
farmers whose fall harvests turned up parts of a jetliner that
crashed at Sioux City, but a $50,000 bounty remains for the part
most sought by investigators.
   ``The harvest is in full swing right now, and they're getting
crops out, and they're able to see where they haven't been able to
see before,'' Buena Vista County Sheriff Chuck Eddy said.
   Officials of the National Transportation Safety Board and GE
hope missing parts will provide clues to why United Airlines Flight
232 crashed July 29. The crash killed 112 people, but 184 survived.
   Most of the parts turned in, including three this week, appear
to be engine fan blades or pieces of blades, said Stephen Gadd, a
lawyer representing GE. The company made the CF6-6 tail engine that
disintegrated before the crash.
   Many other pieces of engine were found immediately after the
July 19 crash.
   Still missing is the 300-pound titanium disk that held the
blades. The company is offering $278,000 in rewards for the parts,
ranging from a $500 minimum to $50,000 for the disk, and has paid
$4,700, Gadd said.
   Investigators suspect the disk failed, causing the engine to fly
apart over western Iowa. A bit of metal from the disintegrating
engine severed hydraulic lines, causing the pilots to lose control,
they believe.
   The Chicago-bound plane crashed during an attempted emergency
landing after turning back to Sioux City, about 50 miles from here.
   Farmer John Husman found what appeared to be part of a fan blade
while running a combine through his soybean field about six miles
north of Alta.
   ``It was pretty well mashed up,'' he said. ``It looked like it
must have gone through an awfully big force.''
   Husman said he found the part last Friday, but continued to
harvest his crop until rain idled him on Thursday. He said the
reward money is appreciated.
   ``That would make up for some of the repair bills on the
combine,'' he said.
</TEXT>
