<FIRST>r a PM-ThinBlueLine 1stLd-Writethru a0566 10-06 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thin Blue Line, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0566,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses to Remove Overturned Murder Conviction from Records</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to restore dropped time element.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has denied Randall Dale Adams' request to
clear state records of his 1977 capital murder conviction, which
was thrown out after the movie ``The Thin Blue Line'' cast doubt on
the evidence.
   Judge Larry Baraka said he denied the motion Thursday because
Adams' attorneys did not prove that he was wrongfully indicted.
   ``We don't know if he did or didn't do it,'' Baraka said.
   Adams spent 12 years in prison after being convicted of the 1976
fatal shooting of Dallas police officer Robert Wood. The jury had
recommended Adams be put to death, but the sentence later was
commuted to life.
   Earlier this year, the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals ordered a
new trial for Adams after reviewing evidence mostly obtained
through Errol Morris, producer of the documentary movie.
   Adams had maintained his innocence and said the real killer was
David Ray Harris, who had provided investigators with clues that he
said linked Adams to the slaying. Harris withdrew his accusation in
a court hearing last year and provided so many details about the
case that Baraka declared his statements a virtual admission of
guilt.
   After the appeals court ruling, Dallas County District Attorney
John Vance dismissed the capital murder charge against Adams,
saying his office lacked sufficient evidence to prosecute Adams,
who now lives in Ohio. But erasing any record of the conviction
required a separate ruling.
   Adams' attorney, George Preston, said he probably will file a
motion for a new trial asking Baraka to reconsider.
   ``Right now, if he were even stopped on a traffic violation, his
arrest, charge and conviction of capital murder would be accessible
by the officer,'' Preston said.

</TEXT>
