<FIRST>u w PM-Refugees-USEmbasssy     10-06 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees-US Embasssy,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Denying Fleeing East Germans Entry to US Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germans hoping to flee to the West are
``politely denied entry'' to the U.S. Embassy In East Berlin and
only those who have normal business there are permitted to enter,
the State Department says.
   A press notice issued Thursday night reinforced earlier U.S.
statements that the embassy is not equipped to grant waves of
would-be emigrants extended sanctuary.
   ``Our embassy is not in a position to accommodate large numbers
of people who want to sit there until other governments do
something,'' said Richard Boucher, a State Department spokesman.
   Eighteen East Germans _ 10 adults and eight children _
voluntarily left the U.S. Embassy Wednesday evening after a 31-hour
occupation that touched off an effort by dozens of others to try to
get past East German police and into the building.
   Boucher said the East German government had given assurances
that ``their desire to emigrate would be considered positively and
that no reprisals would be taken against them.'' Also, he said, a
woman pushed away by police from the entrance was given similar
assurances.
   ``We try to do what we can to express our humanitarian concerns
for individuals as well as whole groups of people,'' the U.S.
spokesman said.
   But while asserting again American support for the right to
travel, Boucher said it was ``worth remembering'' that the vast
majority of East Germans trying to emigrate wish to settle in West
Germany, and not the United States.
   ``The embassy that we have in Berlin is, of course, not set up
as a place where people can go,'' Boucher said. ``We do not have
the capability to handle even a limited number of people.''
   The U.S. official also cautioned would-be East German emigrants
that ``people potentially put themselves in a difficult situation
with respect to their own government.''
   Boucher said the advice was based on recent statements by the
East German government that flocking to Western embassies ``was no
longer acceptable.''
   The notice to the press Thursday night said visitors to the
embassy were asked by U.S. officials why they wanted to enter the
building.
   ``Those who have normal embassy business are allowed to enter,''
it said. ``Those who do not are informed that the U.S. is unable to
assist them on other types of matters. They are politely denied
entry. No one is forced from embassy premises.''
   When hundreds of East Germans tried to rush the five-story stone
building in downtown East Berlin on Wednesday the doors were
slammed shut and East German police called in reinforcements. About
100 formed a line in front of the embassy.
   Boucher said the fact that thousands of East Germans are trying
to flee ``relfects a deep sense of dissatisfaction'' with their
government.
   He said the police were not requested by U.S. embassy officials.
``We deplore the manhandling of the crowd,'' the spokesman said.
``And the embassy has protested the stopping of people trying to
visit it.''
</TEXT>
