<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia-Soviets     10-06 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Soviets,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Rebels Say Moscow Sending Huge Arms Shipments to Phnom
Penh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moscow has doubled the pace of its arms
shipments to Cambodia this year, sending 60 tanks and 20 MiG-21 jet
fighters in August alone, the resistance coalition and Asian
diplomats said today.
   The Soviet Union began shipping huge quantities of munitions to
Phnom Penh when it became clear that Vietnam's troops would be
withdrawn by the end of September, the officials said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Moscow sent 160 T-55 main battle tanks this year, more than
doubling Phnom Penh's inventory of tanks.
   The Soviets also sent at least 36 Mig-21 fighter jets, 76.2mm
heavy artillery, trucks, thousands of tons of land mines, small
arms and ammunition to the port at Kampong Saom, diplomats said.
   Soviet deliveries of munitions through the end of August are
running about twice as high as the pace of shipments in 1988, the
diplomats said.
   The information on shipments came from the Cambodian resistance
movement's sources, U.S. intelligence and independent media
reports, they said.
   An official at the Soviet Union's U.N. Mission, speaking
privately, said he did not think that the pace of Soviet arms
deliveries had increased this year.
   In Cambodia and Afghanistan, governments backed by Moscow have
lost the protection of armies from powerful neighbors and now face
determined, well-trained guerrilla movements.
   Moscow greatly increased the quantity and quality of munitions
it sent to Afghanistan after Soviet troops completed their
withdrawal earlier this year.
   Vietnam's deputy foreign minister, Nguyen Dy Nien, recently told
the General Assembly: ``From this rostrum, I solemnly declare that
from September 27 there does not remain a single Vietnamese
volunteer soldier in Cambodia, either army man, adviser or military
employee.'' Last week, a Cambodian resistance leader called
Vietnam's troop withdrawal a sham.
   Son Sann, the prime minister of the three-party resistance
coalition recognized by the United Nations as the legitimate
government of Cambodia, claimed Vietnam left behind at least 30,000
Vietnamese soldiers, 100,000 militiamen and a million settlers.
   China supplies weapons to the three members of the Cambodian
resistance coalition, including its strongest guerrilla army, the
Khmer Rouge, which ruled Cambodia from 1975 until ousted by Vietnam
in 1979.
   Led by Pol Pot, the Khmer Rouge traumatized the nation by
attempting to impose a peasant agricultural economy on everyone in
the country. More than a million people died of starvation or were
executed during its reign.
</TEXT>
