<SECOND>PM-Mobutu Protest,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zaire's President Delivers Harvard Remarks Amid Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zairian President Mobutu Sese Seko defended his
human rights record in a news conference today after about 500
people protested during his speech at Harvard University the night
before.
   In his brief remarks, Mobutu also predicted a cease-fire
agreement would be signed this month to halt the civil war in
Angola. The agreement would replace the faltering June accord
between rebels and the Soviet-backed government, who have been
fighting for 14 years.
   ``The text is ready,'' he said.
   Mobutu, asked about reported human rights violations in Zaire,
said that after Belgium gave the central African country its
independence in 1959, conflicts among 24 political parties and
seven unions left a half-million people dead in six years. But
since he took power in 1965, he said, tribal and ethnic conflict
has eased.
   ``The results are clear,'' he said. ``There are no more deaths.''
   About 500 African-American activists, academics and others
chanted outside a university auditorium Thursday night during
Mobutu's speech at the John F. Kennedy School of Government.
   For the past two weeks a coalition of activists tried to
persuade Harvard to rescind its invitation to the African leader,
who was asked to speak his part in the Angola peace effort.
   ``Harvard, like other universities, feels very strongly about
the right of free speech,'' Steven Singer, a spokesman for the
graduate school, said Thursday.
   Mobutu called for greater U.S. assistance in reducing Africa's
foreign debt. Zaire owes an estimated $7 billion to $8 billion to
overseas creditors.
   He defended his country's human rights record before a skeptical
audience of about 150 people, one of whom angered the African
leader during a question-and-answer session.
   The student, who said he was Zairian, accused Mobutu of
perpetuating a state of continued poverty and starvation in Zaire.
   Mobutu fired back: ``And you say in front of foreigners that
people starve to death in Zaire. What Zaire are you talking about?''
   Mobutu's opponents accuse him of taking power nearly 25 years
ago in a CIA-sponsored coup, trafficking in arms to rebels in
Angola and amassing a private fortune while impoverishing Zaire.
   On Wednesday, Mobutu met with President Bush and addressed the
United Nations in New York.
</TEXT>
