<FIRST>r a PM-LouisianaAbortions     10-06 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Louisiana Abortions,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judicial Panel Hears Arguments on Revival of Louisiana Abortion Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Abortion Consent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-abortion lawyers told a federal judicial
panel today that the U.S. Supreme Court cleared the way in July to
reinstate a Louisiana law making nearly all abortions illegal.
   John Baker, a Louisiana State University law professor, told the
three U.S. District Court judges that the July 3 decision upholding
Missouri abortion restrictions changed the way abortion cases can
be reviewed by the court.
   That means Louisiana may ban abortions if it proves it has a
compelling interest in protecting the unborn, he said.
   Such an interest is already evident in state laws giving fetuses
the right to such things as support payments, said Baker and
Jennifer Schaye, a lawyer for state Attorney General William Guste.
   Rachael Pine, an attorney for the pro-choice side, said there is
no basis for lifting the 1976 federal court order that keeps
Louisiana from sending doctors to jail for performing abortions.
   She said all nine Supreme Court justices agreed that the
Missouri case, Webster vs. Reproductive Health Services, does not
overturn Roe vs. Wade, the 1973 ruling establishing a woman's right
to abortion.
   Pine disagreed with Baker's contention that Webster changed the
judicial standard for review of abortion cases and said the courts
still must bar any law that unduly restricts a woman's access to
abortion.
   ``If this law is not an undue burden on a woman's right, I don't
know what is,'' Pine said.
   Baker countered that he wasn't asking the court to overturn Roe
vs. Wade but simply to set up a test case to see if Louisiana's
interest in protecting the unborn would indeed be upheld by the
U.S. Supreme Court.
   There was no indication when the judges will rule.
   Before the hearing, about 70 demonstrators on the courthouse
steps sang ``Keep abortion safe and legal'' to the tune of the
``Battle Hymn of the Republic.'' A dozen anti-abortion protesters
arrived later and walked quietly in a circle.
   New Orleans District Attorney Harry Connick spearheaded the
effort to revive the anti-abortion law shortly after the Supreme
Court ruled on the Missouri case. Guste joined the case later.
   The action brought immediate protest from the National
Organization for Women, the ACLU and other groups.
   ``Louisiana is a major battle ground,'' said Shirley Peddler,
director of Louisiana's ACLU chapter. ``It is the first state to
try to criminalize abortion, even without grounds to do so.''
</TEXT>
