<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1245EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     10-06 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Nationwide Ordered to Study Party Chief's Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just when many Chinese thought political study
classes were winding down, a new command has come down from the
Communist Party's top levels: ``Study Well Comrade Jiang Zemin's
Important Speech.''
   Jiang is the new party general secretary, and he delivered the
speech last week as the nation prepared to mark the 40th
anniversary of Communist rule.
   It was an 80-minute, hard-line lecture on the evils of Western
liberalism and the correctness of the June military attack in
Beijing on students and citizens protesting for greater freedom.
   ``Only socialism can save China,'' Jiang said. ``Replacement of
capitalism with socialism is the great historical trend.''
   Over the past week, the party and China's official media have
praised the speech to a degree unprecedented for the words of
anyone lower than senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   ``It is a programmatic document guiding the Communist Party of
China in all its tasks in the near future,'' the party's Propaganda
Department said in the order.
   The party newspaper, the People's Daily, said the speech
``crystalized the collective wisdom'' of people inside and outside
the party and should be used to ``conscientiously raise the
theoretical level and political acuteness of all party comrades.''
   Many see the intense campaign as an effort to convey on Ziang an
aura of leadership that he lacks.
   A party source said Jiang is not at ease in his post. The
source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Jiang has been
treading carefully since taking office in June in the aftermath of
the protests, trying to make peace with both the hard-line and
reformist camps of the fractured party and trusting few people.
   He appears to have Deng's full support, but a government
employee, also speaking on condition of anonymity, predicted that
will count for little after the death of the senior leader, who is
85 and reportedly suffering from cancer.
   ``Jiang is only an interim leader,'' the government worker said,
echoing a widespread opinion. ``He is like Hua Guofeng.''
   Hua took over as party and government leader after the death of
Mao Tse-tung in 1976 but lacked his own power base in Beijing and
had lost all his top posts by 1981.
   Jiang, too, has no Beijing power base, having spent most of his
career in Shanghai, where he was party leader before June.
   Until this week's calls to study his latest speech, the level of
official media coverage of Jiang was normal for a party leader.
   The new campaign goes beyond anything ordered under Jiang's
predecessor, the now-disgraced Zhao Ziyang, at least in part
reflecting the leadership's new concern with strengthening
ideological education.
   Government ministries, research institutes, provincial and city
governments, military units and factories all have issued their own
orders to employees to ``earnestly study'' the speech and build
socialism under its inspiration.
   Half of national television's 30-minute nightly news program has
been taken up showing groups hard at study, following a
time-honored ritual that starts with the group leader summarizing
the correct line.
   Each participant then makes his own statement, mostly using
phrases from Jiang's speech and newspaper editorials about it.
   Chinese who spent most of the summer studying a speech by Deng
condemning the pro-democracy protests are not heartened by the new
campaign.
   ``We are so tired of saying all this stuff,'' one intellectual
said with a groan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
