<FIRST>r a PM-BarbaraBush     10-06 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barbara Bush,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Says She's Optimistic About Health Care for Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush told a convocation at
Morehouse School of Medicine today that institutions like the
predominantly black Atlanta school have made her optimistic that
the nation's poor will see improved health care.
   Mrs. Bush, a former board member of the medical school, said
Morehouse's mission of providing doctors for the poor, mainly in
inner-city areas, was a major reason for her optimism.
   She said the school's student body is growing rapidly, it has a
95 percent passing rate on national board tests and it has never
experienced an operating budget deficit.
   ``I'm not naive enough to think the graduates of Morehouse will
solve all the health problems ... but I'm optimistic,'' she said.
   She urged students to keep the school's mission of serving the
poor in mind after they graduate. ``Our communities need your
skills and commitment,'' she said.
   Mrs. Bush said she wanted to dispel the widely held notion that
she was responsible for getting the medical school's founder, Dr.
Louis Sullivan, nominated as secretary of health and human services.
   She said it was her husband who first introduced her to Sullivan
and who came up with the idea of the Cabinet nomination.
   Mrs. Bush's appearance at the school today kicked off a
three-day series of events leading to Sunday's inauguration of Dr.
James A. Goodman, who will succeed Sullivan as the school's
president.
   Goodman presented the first lady with an honorary doctorate of
humane letters, citing her active support of the medical school and
her work toward erasing illiteracy.
   Mrs. Bush later visited the Basement, a non-profit recreation
center providing Atlanta teen-agers with a drug- and alcohol-free
environment.
</TEXT>
