<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     10-06 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>27 Killed in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials said Friday at least 27
people were killed in southern and central Sri Lanka in the
previous 24 hours, most of them by vigilantes fighting
anti-government Sinhalese radicals.
   Military officials, who cannot be identified under briefing
rules, said the bodies of 21 ethnic Sinhalese youths were found
Friday in and around Kandy, 60 miles northeast of Colombo.
   Two bodies were found in Kandy's main bus terminal, 15 in Geloya
village and four in Mahiyawa village, they said.
   A day earlier, the bodies of 18 young Sinhalese were discovered
on the Peradeniya University campus in Kandy. The victims were
either beheaded or shot.
   Residents and military officials blamed vigilantes for both
massacres, which they described as revenge for the murder Wednesday
of Edward Nagahawatta, the unversity's assistant registrar and a
volunteer soldier. He was killed by two gunmen on a bicycle, who
escaped.
   A government statement said gunmen killed Ranjit Perera, a
free-lance news photographer, on Thursday after dragging him from
his home in Kegalle, 45 miles northeast of Colombo. Officials said
privately they believed Perera, 29, was killed by pro-government
vigilantes for taking pictures of their victims.
   Human rights groups claim the government actively supports
vigilante groups in its conflict with the People's Liberation
Front, a radical guerrilla group from Sri Lanka's Sinahalese ethnic
minority. The government denies it.
   Officials blame the extremists for most of the 5,000 deaths
reported since 1987, when the ultranationalist group began its
campaign of violence. The government statement said the Sinhalese
extremists killed five people in southern Sri Lanka, the Sinhalese
heartland, during the previous 24 hours.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa called an interparty meeting last
month in an effort to end the violence by resolving ethnic
differences in this island nation off the tip of India.
   The extremist group refused to attend and spurned a unilateral
six-day truce the government declared. Military officials say 80
people were killed during the cease-fire period, which ended
Tuesday.
   Sinhalese radicals oppose the government's peace overtures to
ethnic Tamil guerrillas, who began fighting in 1983 for an
independent nation in northern and eastern Sri Lanka, and to the
presence of an Indian peacekeeping force.
   At least 11,000 people have been killed in the Tamil war,
including 1,000 Indian soldiers.
   Indian soldiers were deployed to supervise a surrender of arms
by Tamil guerrillas, but the main Tamil force continued fighting.
India became involved because it is the regional power and has a
Tamil population of 60 million.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people and accuse the Sinhalese majority,
predominantly Buddhist, of discrimination.
</TEXT>
