<FIRST>u w PM-ChildCare 1stLd-Writethru a0454 10-06 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Care, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0454,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Passes Child Care Plan, Budget-Reduction Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 3rd graf, The House, to CORRECT figure to $17.2 billion
sted $5 billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers, agreeing on a massive expansion of
child care aid through tax credits and subsidies, still must decide
between competing proposals on how to divide up the subsidies.
   ``It's a good day for America's children,'' Rep. Pat Schroeder,
D-Colo., said Thursday as the House approved the child care
measure, which is expected to cost $22.7 billion over the next five
years. ``The Congress is more enlightened than a lot of people
thought,'' she said.
   The House overwhelmingly rejected a smaller $17.2 billion
administration-endorsed child care plan that would have eliminated
requirements for state regulation of child care providers. The
substitute, offered by Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, was defeated
on a 230-195 vote.
   Also rejected by a 285-140 margin was an amendment by Rep.
Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., mirroring Bush's proposal last March to
expand child care aid solely through tax credits.
   Democratic leaders refused to allow a vote on competing
proposals on how to divide up some $1.75 billion in new direct
subsidies. Instead, they sent both to a conference with the Senate,
which approved its own child care package last June.
   The child care measure was included as part of a bill to reduce
spending by nearly $11 billion in fiscal 1990, which began last
Sunday. The overall bill, with a variety of unrelated proposals
such as a cut in capital gains tax rates and a repeal of the
year-old catastrophic care program for the elderly, was approved on
a 333-91 vote.
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich of Georgia predicted after
the House's action Thursday that Bush would veto the entire bill if
House-Senate negotiators retain language specifying regulatory
mandates and restricting aid for church-provided child care.
   Both the Senate version and one of the House versions target
much of the aid toward establishing child care facilities in the
public schools.
   However, the House also armed its negotiators with a version
written by its Ways and Means Committee to provide the $1.75
billion in new direct subsidies over the next five years through
existing entitlement block grants to the states.
   That plan, supported by governors as well as churches, would
allow the new aid to continue flowing to church-supported child
care centers through voucher programs.
   Stenholm's measure would have dropped requirements that states
inspect child care centers and provide 15 hours of annual training.
It also would have ended current child care tax deductions of up to
$2,400 for families with incomes above $90,000.
   ``We believe the family is the best determiner of how child care
should be provided, not the federal government,'' Stenholm said in
leading the attack on the proposed standards.
   Supporters of the proposed standards, however, argued that
increasing the quality of child care is just as important as
increasing its availability and reducing the cost of it to poor
families.
   ``The federal government has found it appropriate to regulate
the type of food we eat so that our health is protected,'' said
Rep. Thomas J. Downey, D-N.Y. ``Clearly our health is important and
so are our children. They deserve the finest and the best care we
can provide for them.''
   All the surviving proposals would double the size of the
preschool Head Start program for poor children and convert it into
a year-round, 10-hours-a-day operation.
   The bulk of the new aid _ $13.5 billion over the next five years
_ is in the form of increased Earned Income Tax Credits for poor
families with children under age 12.
   Basically the credits would expanded by a maximum of $200 to
$300 for each child in qualifying families plus another $430 per
family if one or more of the children is under age 6.
</TEXT>
