<FIRST>u i PM-EGermany-Anniversary 5thLd-Writethru   10-06 1016</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EGermany-Anniversary, 5th Ld-Writethru,a0597,1048</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Urges Patience As East Germany Marks 40th Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Gorbachev expressing confidence
in East Germany. Pickup 6th pvs, `Gorbachev joined...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev urged East
Germans today to be patient for change as he helped observe 40
years of a Communist system that thousands of East Germans have
rejected by fleeing West.
   The Kremlin chief said he had ``complete confidence'' in East
Germany's ability to solve its growing problems.
   Communist authorities closed three major border crossings
between East and West Berlin, and church sources said riot police
with clubs, tear gas and water cannons patrolled the streets of
major cities throughout East Germany.
   The sources also reported new clashes between police and
protesters, and West German television showed battles in Dresden
between police and protesters hoping to join the exodus of refugees.
   ``Be patient, don't panic and don't be sad. We are very close
partners and we will solve our problems and struggles together,''
Gorbachev told 1,000 East Germans at a monument for the victims of
facsism.
   ``Gorby! Gorby!'' East Germans shouted as Gorbachev arrived from
Moscow.
   Asked if he thought the situation in East Germany was dangerous,
he said: ``I don't think so.''
   ``Compared to our problems, there is no comparison,'' he said
with a chuckle. ``Nothing surprises us anymore.''
   ``We have complete confidence in'' East Germany's ability to
solve its problems, he said.
   Gorbachev joined other East bloc leaders for a two-day show of
unity, despite fractured relations over the refugee flight and East
Germany's reluctance to try the type of political reforms he has
championed.
   East German leader Erich Honecker welcomed Gorbachev at East
Berlin's Schoenefeld airport, the state news agency ADN said.
Gorbachev later planned to address Communist Party dignitaries.
   Also today, a train brought 633 East German refugees from Poland
to West Germany, the latest of more than 47,000 citizens who have
fled this tightly controlled society to the West since
mid-September.
   There were efforts to avoid further embarrassment to the East
Berlin government. Authorities closed three of the nine busiest
border crossings into the city, turning back hundreds of tourists
and West Germans since Thursday, said Werner Thronicker, a
spokesman for the West Berlin government.
   East Berlin, the site of anniversary events, was bedecked with
the fixtures of socialist celebration. Huge red banners were draped
from the Communist Party headquarters, reviewing stands were set
for parades and flags hung from public buildings and apartment
blocks.
   Kiosks were plastered with posters showing construction workers
and young mothers appreciating accomplishments of the postwar
republic, founded on Oct. 7, 1949.
   But the image of the East Germans who fled to the West through
Czechoslovakia, Hungary and Poland was broadcast nationwide by West
German television.
   The West German government said it saw ``no reason for
celebration'' since the date marks four decades of the division of
the German nation. It also criticized the latest developments in
East Germany.
   ``The blocking of borders, the sending back of tourists, the
violent supression of peaceful demonstrations and the officially
declared rejection of political and economic reforms takes away all
hope from the people,'' chief government spokesman Hans Klein said
in Bonn.
   And on Thursday, as the ailing 77-year-old Honecker prepared for
festivities meant to show the virtues of strict doctrine, thousands
of would-be emigrees clashed with police in Dresden. West Germany's
ZDF television network said young demonstrators threw stones at
security forces on Thursday and dozens of windows were broken at
Dresden's train station.
   Witnesses said police used water cannon and truncheons to
disperse those who hoped to jump aboard trains carrying East German
refugees westward from Prague.
   In Magdeburg, north of Leipzig, police clashed with 600 people
who joined a silent march through the city after a church prayer
service late Thursday, said Church sources in East Berlin. About
200 people were arrested.
   Riot police equipped with clubs, tear gas, shields and water
cannons patrolled the streets of many major cities throughout the
country, said the sources, who demanded anonymity.
   Those who left said 40 years had created a country ahead of its
East bloc neighbors in consumer goods but behind in the less
tangible measures of opportunity.
   They described a nation where Communist Party loyalty determined
education and employment, censorship concealed truth, and police
supervision was a part of daily life. Many hid from television
cameras, fearing relatives left behind would be harassed.
   ``I cannot say I was ever wanting for food or things, that's why
it was so hard,'' said a young East Berlin woman who reached the
West German Embassy in Warsaw with her 2-year-old daughter. ``But
there was nothing else, just limits.''
   Gorbachev's attendance at the celebration is viewed as a formal
show of support for East Germany, which has rebuffed the economic
and political reforms sweeping much of Eastern Europe.
   Although he did nothing to censure the Warsaw Pact allies who
served as springboards to freedom for the refugees, it was not
likely he would criticize Honecker, who some say is likely to be
replaced soon as Communist Party chief.
   But there were reports Gorbachev might privately pressure East
Germany's aging leader to ease his resistance to reforms.
   Unrest within East Germany, along the East Bloc's frontier with
the West, is unacceptable to the Soviets.
   It is equally unacceptable for disagreements between East
Germany and Hungary _ which allowed thousands pass to the West _ to
develop into an open split that might weaken the alliance.
   Gorbachev has stated that the Eastern European allies may follow
their own path to socialism. The Soviets have watched quietly as
Hungary reforms its economy and Poland experiments with the bloc's
first non-communist government.
   A West German newspaper, Bild, said today that Gorbachev would
try to persuade East Berlin to ease press censorship, permit
greater freedom of expression and loosen travel restrictions.
   Other Western reports said Gorbachev and his foreign minister,
Eduard Shevardnadze, quietly helped arrange the exodus of East
German refugees from Prague over the weekend.
</TEXT>
