<FIRST>r w AM-Hugo-Tides     10-06 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Tides,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Damaged Coastal Areas Face High Tides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal areas damaged by Hurricane Hugo may be
facing a new threat from slightly higher than normal tides next
weekend.
   The combination of a full moon and the moon's nearness to Earth
will conspire to raise the tide a couple of feet above average, the
National Ocean Service reported.
   Aiding in this is the fact that the moon will be at its closest
point of the year.
   But weather is a much bigger factor than the moon's alignment,
pointed out Milt Rutstein of the Ocean Service, a division of the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
   ``As long as there's no storm, it's just another high tide,''
said Rutstein.
   Average high tide at Charleston, S.C., is 5.3 feet, explained
Rutstein, while the prediction calls for high tides of between 7.0
feet and 7.3 feet on Oct. 14-16.
   However, strong northwest winds could drive the tides back out
to sea, while a strong southeast wind could pile up even more water
and increase the threat, he pointed out. The most important
consideration will be the weather on those days.
   Similar tidal circumstances are expected to occur in November
and again in April.
   Causing the high tide will be the fact that the moon is at
perigee at the same time it is full, Rutstein explained.
   The orbit of the moon is not perfectly round, but rather oval
shaped. Perigee is the time of the month when the moon is closest
to Earth, and that closeness allows it to exert greater pull on the
oceans.
   Perigee will occur shortly after midnight Oct. 15, Rutstein said.
   LeRoy Doggett of the U.S. Naval Observatory reported that at
that time the moon will just over 221,000 miles from Earth. That's
the closest the moon has come so far this year, although Doggett
said slightly closer passes are possible.
   ``It's enough, I think, to make a difference,'' compared to the
month before and after. The perigee in September, for example,
found the moon 1,500 miles farther away.
   And in November, when high tides are again expected with the
full moon and perigee occurring one day apart, the moon's perigee
will be about 300 miles farther away than this month.
   Besides the perigee, the fact that the full moon occurs late on
the 14th also encourages the high tide, said Rutstein.
   The highest tides, called spring tides, occur every 14 days,
when the moon is new and full. New moon occurs when the moon is on
the same side of Earth as the sun and the two pull together on the
oceans. Full moon means the moon is on the opposite side of earth
from the sun and the two pull against one another.
   Lower tides, called neap tides, occur when the sun and moon are
at right angles to one another.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891006-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1332EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-CatastrophicInsurance 2ndLd-Writethru a0581 10-06 0831</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Catastrophic Insurance, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0581,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Considers Whether to Scrap or Revamp Catastrophic Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 6 grafs new with Kennedy amendment; picks up pvs graf 3:
In addition.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate today defeated a plan that would
have killed catastrophic health coverage for physicians' fees and
repealed the unpopular surtax on retirees that finances most
benefits under the program.
   The amendment, by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., would have
retained insurance coverage for catastrophic hospital and
prescription expenses. It was defeated on a 64-35 vote.
   Other plans for significantly changing the catastrophic program
would drop coverage for prescriptions. Kennedy said 5.4 million
people had to bear catastrophic health costs because of
prescriptions last year, compared to 1.3 million because of
hospital bills and 2.3 million due to physicians' fees.
   ``Nobody has any information on how much this (drug) program
will cost,'' protested Sen. William Roth, R-Del. He noted estimates
that administration of drug benefits will cost $2 billion a year.
   Kennedy and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., sponsor of a plan that
would retain coverage for physicians' fees and hospital costs but
not drugs, agreed on one point: the surtax on retirees should be
eliminated.
   ``The surtax is the object of the anger and ire of senior
Americans,'' McCain said.
   In addition to repealing the surtax, which is paid by about 40
percent of retirees, McCain's amendment would wipe out coverage for
prescription drugs and expanded coverage for physicians's fees
while retaining full coverage of hospital bills.
   Senate leaders are rallying behind a plan by Sen. David
Durenberger, R-Minn., that would keep more benefits of the program,
wipe out drug coverage and significantly reduce _ but not repeal _
the surtax, which is paid by higher-income retirees.
   But there is considerable support for outright repeal.
   Durenberger's proposal was embraced Thursday by Health and Human
Services Secretary Louis Sullivan, who said ``the rush for repeal
... is shocking.'' But a short time later, Richard G. Darman,
director of the White House Office of Management and Budget, said
the administration has not endorsed any specific plan to salvage
the program.
   The Senate was expected to decide the program's fate today. The
House already has voted by a lopsided margin to repeal it.
   Sullivan, in a speech to the National Press Club and in a letter
to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said repeal would represent a major setback to national
health policy.
   ``To take back from tens of millions of elderly Americans the
comfort of knowing that serious illness will not cause them
financial ruin would not only be unwise health policy, but would
simply be an unforgivable act of political expedience,'' Sullivan
told the press club.
   Congress is considering repealing or scaling back the program
because of loud complaints from its intended beneficiaries: the 33
million retirees who are eligible for Medicare.
   The program is being attacked by some retirees who already have
other catastrophic coverage, and from some with higher incomes, who
must pay an income surtax of up to $800 a year to finance coverage
for themselves and low-income older Americans.
   Durenberger said his proposal ``would provide seniors with the
equivalent of $4,000 worth of private medigap insurance coverage at
a cost of between $48 and $300 per year.''
   His amendment had the support of Bentsen, Senate Majority Leader
George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, and Republican Leader Bob Dole of
Kansas.
   The catastrophic law expanded Medicare benefits to protect
retirees against being wiped out financially by a long illness.
   This protection includes full coverage of hospital bills, after
the beneficiary pays the first $560; full coverage of doctors'
bills after the first $1,370 a year, starting in 1990; half of
prescription drugs after a $600 deductible starting in 1991; 150
days a year of nursing home care plus other benefits for
mammography, home care, hospice care and special payments for the
poor.
   The program is financed chiefly by a surtax of up to $800 a year
on the wealthiest 40 percent of retirees who pay at least $150
federal income tax. The remaining cost is covered by a flat monthly
premium of $4 paid by all but the poorest retirees.
   Durenberger's proposal would retain full hospital coverage;
delay starting full coverage of doctors' bills until 1991 and then
require the patient to pay the first $1,780 a year; eliminate
coverage for most drugs; require a beneficiary to spend three days
in a hospital before qualifying for skilled nursing care, and
retain most of the lesser benefits, including mammographies,
respite care and home health care.
   The $800-a-year maximum surtax would be held to $200 this year
and next, then raised to $250 for the following three years. The
current surtax rate of 15 percent of income tax liability would be
cut to 10 percent for five years.
   The additional catastrophic drug premium of 90 cents a month,
rising to $3.02 by 1993, would be eliminated.
</TEXT>
