<FIRST>u w PM-Congress-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru a0586 10-06 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0586,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney, Powell Defend Response to Panama Coup Attempt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with hearing, plans for congressional report;
picks up at pvs 3rd graf, ``We're going''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's top military leaders told
senators today they would not have changed their advice to
President Bush based on what they now know about the circumstances
of Tuesday's failed coup in Panama, a lawmaker said.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and Gen. Colin Powell, chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, testified for three hours in closed
session with the Senate Intelligence and Armed Services committees.
   The two panels planned to issue later today a factual analysis
of issues that remain in dispute surrounding the events in Panama
and contacts between the rebel officers who organized the coup and
U.S. officials.
   ``There are a lot of things in dispute'' said Armed Services
Committee Chairman Sam Nunn, D-Ga., referring to media and other
accounts which he said are ``all over the lot.'' He declined
further comment.
   But Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said Cheney and Powell ``basically
... would not have changed their decision and recommendations to
the president, based on what they know today.''
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., the Intelligence Committee chairman
and a leading critic of administration handling of the crisis, said
he had not changed his mind following the briefing. He again
criticized what he called ``a flawed policy'' in Panama.
   ``We're going to get to the bottom of this,'' Boren said in
advance of the hearing. ``I am convinced the full facts have not
been laid out to us or the American people.''
   Among the mysteries surrounding the coup, Boren said in an
interview, is exactly what was said in a conversation Tuesday
afternoon between two mid-level rebel officers and an American
officer, Army Gen. Marc Cisneros, at a U.S. military base in Panama.
   It is clear, the senator said, that the rebels asked the United
States to provide logistical support by blocking roads and bridges
that might be used by troops loyal to Noriega to approach the
Panamanian Defense Forces headquarters where the dictator was then
being held by the dissidents.
   But whether they also offered to turn over Noriega to the United
States remains unclear, he said, adding it appears that differing
versions of the conversation were given to the National Security
Council, the CIA and the State Department.
   One version reports that the rebels said they were unable to
deliver Noriega to the U.S. base, but would cooperate if a U.S.
helicopter were sent to remove him. The other version portrayed the
rebels as refusing to turn the dictator over to the United States,
saying they wanted him to retire and remain in Panama.
   ``I want to see those cables and compare them,'' Boren said. ``I
think they've got a lot of explaining to do.'' He said he may
schedule hearings and ``put some people under oath.''
   Despite Cheney's efforts to explain administration actions and
detail the uncertainty that pervaded Tuesday's situation, members
of Congress in both parties continued to criticize.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., called the administration's story
a ``weak-kneed explanation for failure'' and said the United States
had ``botched'' the handling of the coup. ``It's an incredible
stain on us,'' he said.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said he doubted
administration assertions that Noriega was left weakened by the
coup attempt. ``It seems to me that he is emerging from this,
perhaps, unfortunately strengthened,'' Foley said.
   Cheney, in a round of media interviews and in meetings with
members of Congress, defended the administration's caution as the
only responsible course in the face of incomplete intelligence and
suspicions about the identities and motives of the rebels.
   He said the coup leaders had made only general requests for
support and called ``hogwash'' any suggestion that there was a
direct appeal for the United States to snatch Noriega away.
   But in a speech on the Senate floor, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
contended the requests for help had been more extensive and more
specific.
   ``They told the U.S. officers that they were holding Noriega
captive, and requested U.S. assistance to take custody of Noriega
and remove him to the United States,'' Helms alleged.
   Boren said Helms' information, which came from staff inquiries,
had ``some basis to it.''
   Helms made his comments during debate on an admittedly symbolic
amendment to a drug bill that underscored Bush's authority to use
military force to apprehend Noriega and bring him to justice on
drug charges.
   The amendment was later killed, 74-25, after Sen. Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., termed it ``the officially sanctioned snatching
provision.''
   The Senate then adopted, 99-1, an alternative proposed by Sen.
Sam Nunn, D-Ga., expressing support for Bush's efforts to
democratize Panama through a ``full range of economic, diplomatic
and military options.'' Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., was the lone
dissenter.
</TEXT>
