<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Soviet     10-06 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Soviet,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Wants to Go to Ukraine in 1992</HEAD>
<HEAD>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II told Ukrainian Catholic
bishops he hopes to travel to the Soviet Union to attend a
religious gathering in 1992, Ukrainian church officials said Friday.
   The pope expressed the desire to go to the Ukraine in a private
audience Thursday with a group of Ukrainian Catholic bishops living
in the West, according to two American bishops at the meeting.
   In his public remarks to the bishops Thursday, the pope urged
Soviet authorities to grant immediate legal status to the Ukrainian
Church, which has been suppressed 43 years.
   The pope is expected to raise the Ukrainian issue during Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's visit to Italy on Nov. 29-Dec. 1. It
would be the first meeting between supreme leaders of the Roman
Catholic Church and the Kremlin.
   Bishop Basil H. Losten of Stamford, Conn., and Bishop Robert M.
Moskal of Parma, Ohio, told a news conference the Ukrainian
Catholic Church hopes to hold a eucharistic congress in Lvov,
Ukraine, in 1992.
   A eucharistic congress is a gathering of the faithful to foster
devotion to the sacrament of the altar.
   The meeting is currently scheduled to be held in Winnipeg,
Canada, but the bishops said it would be moved to Lvov if the
church is legalized and if Soviet authorities grant visas to
Ukrainian Catholics living abroad.
   ``The Holy Father expressed his desire to be present at the
eucharistic congress should it be held in Ukraine,'' Losten said,
adding it would be up to the head of the Ukrainian church,
Vatican-based Cardinal Myroslav Lubachivsky, to invite him.
   The pope has often expressed his desire to travel to the Soviet
Union, but only on condition he could visit his flock throughout
the country, including Ukraine and Lithuania.
   Some church officials have expressed hope that a meeting with
Gorbachev could pave the way for the first papal visit to the
Soviet Union.
   The Ukrainian church was forcibly merged with the Russian
Orthodox Church in 1946, with bishops and priests arrested,
deported and killed. But the church has flourished underground and
the bishops estimated there are as many as 5 million Catholics in
the Ukraine today.
   Moskal said the bishops, who have been holding a special,
two-week synod in Rome, hope the pope's meeting with Gorbachev will
lead to the church's legalization.
   But he added, ``Here and there you hear of (Soviet authorities)
not bothering the people in one village or town. And then in
another place the people are continually harassed and persecuted.
So we still feel pessimistic about a lot of things.''
</TEXT>
