<FIRST>r a AM-Disney-Vultures     10-06 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disney-Vultures,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney Negotiating Settlement in Vulture Abuse Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney World is negotiating with
prosecutors to settle charges that the amusement park abused wild
birds, particularly vultures, that invaded its zoological park,
lawyers said.
   U.S. Magistrate Elizabeth Jenkins agreed Thursday to postpone
Disney's arraignment on federal charges for 30 days after both
sides said they thought they could reach a plea agreement.
   State and federal charges were filed against the central Florida
theme park last month after the deaths of vultures and the alleged
mistreatment of other birds at Discovery Island, an 11-acre
zoological site.
   Disney has said the wild birds were attacking animals, stealing
their food, defecating on park boardwalks and making too much noise.
   Disney and five employees were charged with 13 state
misdemeanors and three federal counts. Included were allegations
that workers beat vultures to death; held dozens of them in a
small, overheated shed with little food and water; shot hawks and
falcons; and knocked eggs from the nests of egrets and ibises.
   Disney officials have refused to comment on the charges.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Roberto Moreno said a fine and some
assurance that Disney won't abuse wild birds may be part of the
settlement.
   Disney attorney Robert Eagan would not comment after the
hearing. He told the magistrate it was likely an agreement could be
reached.
   State attorney's spokesman Randy Means confirmed negotiations
were continuing in the state cases, but refused to give specifics.
   Disney officials last week announced a series of changes at
Discovery Island, including a new manager and a new environmental
advisory committee.
   The head of investigations for the Florida Game and Fresh Water
Fish Commission said his office has agreed to meet with Disney
officials next week to discuss how to legally solve the company's
problem with vultures.
</TEXT>
