<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     10-06 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brite and Brief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: FireAnt, one word, is cq in first item.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARSHALL, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Throwing fire ants wouldn't have been
much of a spectator sport, admittedly, but why rubber chickens?
   ``You get the humane society on you if you use symbols of
lovable pets and tossing rubber frogs would be too much like Kermit
and would upset the kids,'' said Harris County District Judge
Bonnie Leggat. She is chairwoman of the chicken-throwing event,
expected to be a highlight of the seventh annual FireAnt Festival
Oct. 14.
   ``We haven't got any complaints,'' she said. ``Apparently,
chickens are not thought of too fondly by anybody. After all,
Chicken Little was a dingbat.''
   The sport originally was conceived as an exhibition between
local politicians two years ago.
   ``We found out they could throw bull, but not chicken,'' said
George Smith, publisher of the Marshall News-Messenger and one of
organizers of the festival, which has been growing every year and
is expected to have an attendance of 50,000 this year. That's
people, not ants.
   The chickens _ regulation rubber imports from Taiwan _ have been
made more aerodynamic by stuffing them with old pantyhose, thus
answering the age-old question of which came first _ the chicken or
the L'eggs.
   Rigid rules require contestants to throw the chickens like a
football.
   ``We won't let them fling them around like a discus, because
their necks pop off and pantyhose goes flying anywhere,'' Ms.
Leggat said.
   Mike Whitworth of Marshall holds the chicken toss record of 109
feet, 6 inches, set in 1987. He revealed his winning technique:
``If you get its little beak up in the wind, then that little
sucker can sail.''
   This year's festival also includes a fire ant calling contest, a
beverage coaster throw, a face-making contest and the Texas Open
Diaper Derby. A 26-foot-tall anteater balloon will make its debut
this year.
   Country singer Lee Greenwood will be grand marshal of the parade
that opens the event. He will perform a concert in the evening.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROSSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman said it was difficult for
judges to select the winning entries from the hundreds of beauties
submitted for a 1990 calendar, but 14 pinups were finally chosen.
   Dewey McIlrath's pride and joy, a bright orange 1935
Allis-Chalmers WC tractor, was one of the winners. It will be
featured in a 1990 Classic Farm Tractor Calendar, printed by the Du
Pont chemical company.
   ``My late father-in-law, Ed Spinn, bought this tractor new for
$635 and farmed with it for many years,'' said McIlrath, a farmer
and businessman. ``My brother, Bud, is also a collector, and he
rebuilt this engine and helped with the restoration.''
   The engine of McIlrath's general-purpose tractor has a magneto
ignition system that requires hand cranking to start.
   The tractor was displayed at the Farm Progress Show in
Rochester. It is one of two Indiana tractors in the calendar, which
features 14 tractors built in the 1920s and 1930s.
   Du Pont spokesman John Harvey said it was difficult to select
just 14 tractors from the hundreds of photos submitted.
   ``We easily could have produced several calendars with just
Indiana tractors,'' he said.
