<FIRST>r a AM-Atheists     10-06 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atheists,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atheists to Honor Man Who Instigated Lawsuit Over Prayers at Football
Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Jager, whose son's lawsuit led to a court
decision that has halted prayers at many high school football
games, will be honored at a convention of atheists and agnostics
this weekend.
   Jager, of Douglasville, is to be named Freethinker of the Year
by the Freedom From Religion Foundation, a 3,400-member group based
in Madison, Wis.
   Jager's son, Doug, sued the county school system in 1986 to halt
prayers before Douglas County High School football games. After he
won before the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals and the U.S.
Supreme Court refused to hear the case in May, many school systems
stopped pregame prayers.
   The elder Jager, 53, said he would never have forced the issue
if other students had not harassed his son, a band member, for not
reciting the prayers. When school officials did not address his
concerns, Jager suggested that his son sue.
   The elder Jager later became active in the Freedom From Religion
Foundation, founded in 1978 to work to keep church and state
separate and to teach the public about atheism.
   Tom Malone, the group's Southeast region vice president and a
social studies teacher at Clarkston High School, said members do
not try to persuade people to leave the church and do not support
governmental opposition to religion.
   Malone said the convention will feature several Georgia speakers.
   ``We anticipated that, since our organization is based in
Madison, Wis., some people would accuse the organization of being
outside agitators,'' he said. ``We wanted to show some of our
home-grown concerns.''
   Expected participants include:
   _Dr. Ken Saladin, a biology professor at Georgia College, who
was turned down for a Scout den leadership position because he
would not sign an oath acknowledging the importance of a belief in
God.
   _Columbus radio station manager J. Edward Wilson, who left the
Seventh-day Adventist Church after years as a minister.
   _Butterfly McQueen, a Georgia resident who played Prissy in the
film ``Gone With the Wind,'' who will receive a Heroine Award for
her advocacy of free thought.
</TEXT>
