<HEAD>Conflict on Peace Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the main proposals by Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak to advance Israel's plan for elections in
the occupied lands, which the Labor Party favors, and objections
expressed by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Likud bloc:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MUBARAK PLAN=
   _Include Palestinians from outside the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip in a delegation to hold preliminary talks in Cairo with
Israeli representatives.
   _Accept the U.S.-backed concept of trading land for peace.
   _Allow the 140,000 Palestinian residents of Arab east Jerusalem,
which Israel has annexed, to participate in the elections.
   _Freeze building of Jewish settlements in the territories.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LIKUD POSITION=
   _Accepting Palestinians from outside the territories would
amount to opening the process to the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which Israel defines as a terrorist organization.
   _No changes or additions can be made to the plan Israel adopted
in May, which calls for electing Palestinians to negotiate with
Israel on interim self-rule. The final status of the occupied lands
would be decided later.
   _Israel should not give up territory for peace.
   _East Jerusalem, captured from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East
war, should not be included in the elections because it has been
declared part of Israel.
   _Building of settlements should continue under the agreement
that created the Likud-Labor coalition government in December 1988.
</TEXT>
