<FIRST>r a AM-ChurchSlayings     10-06 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Slayings,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Shootings Suspect Jailed on $100,000 Bond</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man sought in the fatal shootings of two
fellow church deacons and the wounding of a third in Texas turned
himself in as authorities were getting closer to finding him, the
FBI said Friday.
   Gerald King, 30, was jailed under $100,000 cash bond after being
arrested Thursday on charges of unlawful flight to avoid
prosecution.
   Robert Siller, agent in charge of the Dayton FBI office, said
King's mother and stepfather live in Dayton.
   ``We attempted to locate him at various relatives' residences,''
Siller said. ``He was basically one place ahead of us. He really
wasn't running. It's just that we were getting closer and closer.''
   Siller said King's parents told the FBI their son originally
intended to surrender in Dallas.
   King, a deacon at the Living Testimony Baptist Church in Dallas,
was wanted in connection with the shooting of three fellow deacons
Sunday after an argument apparently erupted among the men in the
church's finance room. Investigators haven't disclosed what
prompted the argument, and the Rev. Robert Simmons, the church's
pastor, said he doesn't know.
   Siller said King would not talk to agents about the shootings.
   The funerals Saturday of Jack Earl Ray, 51, and Artis Weaver,
60, will be the first meeting at the church since the shootings.
Billy Weaver, 39, the wounded deacon, was released from a hospital
Monday.
</TEXT>
