<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1546EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Economy     10-06 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Economy,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Unveils Plans for Creating Market Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland's new government Friday announced
plans for a market economy, warning of tight money, bankruptcy and
unemployment along the way but promising to soften the pain with
unemployment benefits.
   ``What we must do is a quick transformation of the present
economic system into a market system ... that can spur human
initiative and bring a gradual improvement of living conditions,''
Deputy Prime Minister Leszek Balcerowicz said.
   ``We have a great and unrepeatable chance to pass to a ...
system whose effectiveness is proven all over the world. But we
have to do it in a very difficult economic situation.''
   Balcerowicz detailed the preliminary plan one day after it was
approved by the Council of Ministers chaired by Prime Minister
Tadeusz Mazowiecki. The non-communist government has been in power
only 25 days.
   Western countries stand ready to help Poland and if the measures
are put into effect, beneficial effects could be discernible within
a year, Balcerowicz said.
   Poland has been suffering from inflation that has reached 50
percent a month, as well as an alarming drop in production of meat,
coal and industrial goods.
   Officials of the International Monetary Fund will come to Poland
on Oct. 16 and a crucial standby loan agreement should be signed
with the lending group by the end of November, he said.
   The agreement, in which Poland would commit itself to the
detailed program of restructuring and internal stabilization, would
signal the start of new Western loans and restructuring of Poland's
$40 billion Western debt.
   The plan's presentation was the most detailed explanation yet to
the Polish public of the sacrifices to expect under the stringent
reforms advocated by the East bloc's first non-communist government.
   The plan's basic thesis is that only by quickly converting
Poland to a market economy can the country's economic crisis be
solved. Previous remedies such as price controls, ration coupons
and centralized distribution would only worsen the problems and
delay the cure, he said.
   The plan forsees a preliminary phase lasting until Dec. 31,
followed by decisive action beginning early next year, Balcerowicz
told reporters.
   The first phase involves loosening state ownership of property,
breaking up monopolies, reforming the state budget, changing the
banking system, creating unemployment benefits and other social
security measures and making state enterprises more efficient.
   The government will counter monopolistic ``abuse'' of prices
through administrative means and the excessive growth of wages with
legislation to reduce wage indexation, Balcerowicz said.
   ``We must introduce a wage-and-price policy that will stop the
inflationary process,'' he said. ``Without approval of this point,
I can see no chance for leading Poland out of its crisis.''
   In the ``decisive'' phase beginning next year, he said, the
government means to stifle inflation, privatize many state-owned
enterprises, create a bond and stock market as well as a a new
budget system and a new tax system.
   The government also will cut off credit and subsidies, which
will lead to bankruptcies and economic problems for some
enterprises, Balcerowicz said.
   ``Some enterprises will run out of money. And this is a
necessary element of all successful programs to get out of violent
inflation,'' he said.
   Balcerowicz was unable to estimate the unemployment rate but
said it could climb to between 10 percent to 20 percent in the
worst case.
   Once changes are in place and the agreement with the IMF is
signed, he said, prices gradually will stabilize and living
standards will begin to improve. ``The situation is not hopeless.
There is a chance for real improvement.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
