<FIRST>u w AM-US-Angola     10-06 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Angola,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Savimbi Proposes Plan For Truce Monitored By Other African States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi said Friday
he had proposed to the United States a cease-fire plan that would
involve other African states in the monitoring of the truce
compliance.
   Savimbi said the plan he presented earlier in the day to
Secretary of State James A. Baker III and to President Bush on
Thursday would now be passed to Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko,
who has been serving as the mediator between the Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) and the Soviet-backed Angolan
government.
   If the proposal is accepted by the Angolan government, a truce
accord can be signed before the end of the month, sources said.
   The sources, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said the
truce proposal also includes agreement that the troops would not
receive new weapons during the cease-fire, that all hostile
propaganda would stop and that political prisoners be released by
both sides to the international community.
   Savimbi, speaking at the National Press Club at the end of a
week of meetings with officials and lawmakers, said he had arranged
to meet ``very soon'' with Mobutu in order to iron out their
problems and get the negotiations with Angola back on track.
   Mobutu and Savimbi have been feuding over the interpretation of
the Zairean-mediated truce accord, which collapsed soon after it
was reached last June. Savimbi denies he agreed to go into exile,
while Mobutu appears to be backing Angola's claim that he did. The
United States is backing Savimbi's version.
   There were some problems with President Mobutu ``but those
problems _ we consider them on the way to being solved,'' Savimbi
said.
   ``We got a commitment that the United States government will be
more involved ... as a supporting force to help the mediator,'' he
added.
   Baker expressed his ``unswerving'' support for UNITA and ``our
strong desire that direct negotiations between UNITA and (Angola)
resume without preconditions,'' said a State Department statement.
   He also ``reiterated our support for national reconciliation and
UNITA's goal for free and fair elections,'' the statement said.
   Angola has rejected direct negotiations with Savimbi, as well as
free elections.
</TEXT>
