<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Unrest     10-06 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Unrest,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomats Barred From Palestinian Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers Friday
prevented seven European diplomats from visiting a Palestinian town
that has been the target of tax raids. An Arab teen-ager died of
wounds sustained in an army clash.
   Shops and offices were closed throughout the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip for a second consecutive day in a strike called to
show solidarity with residents of Beit Sahour, where Israeli tax
raids have been under way for two weeks.
   The underground leadership of the 22-month-old Palestinian
uprising called for three more days of strikes starting Monday, the
Jewish holy day of Yom Kippur.
   The diplomats, all consuls general from Jerusalem, were stopped
at a military checkpoint on the edge of Bethlehem and told that
Beit Sahour, a nearby town of about 10,000 people, was a ``closed
military zone.''
   The army frequently closes areas in the West Bank and Gaza Strip
to keep outsiders away, including reporters and residents of other
areas.
   British Consul General Ivan Callan said the diplomats were
invited by Beit Sahour's mayor, Hanna Atrash, to see the problems
created by the government's repeated tax raids.
   ``It is part of our duty to discover what is going on,'' Callan
said. ``I think it is a mistake to prevent us from entering.''
   The other diplomats represent Belgium, France, Greece, Spain,
Sweden and Italy.
   The incident was the latest in a test of wills between Israel
and the Palestinians of Beit Sahour.
   The Israeli military government launched the tax raids to try to
make an example of the town, where compliance with a tax boycott
has been almost universal. Non-payment of taxes has been a frequent
tactic of the uprising.
   On Tuesday, soldiers declared part of Arab east Jerusalem a
closed military zone to prevent the holding of a Palestinian press
conference on Beit Sahour's problems.
   The army said in a statement Friday the diplomats were blocked
because ``radical elements are trying to mobilize support from
outside the area, with the help of international bodies that
encourage their actions and the media, while they increase their
violent activities.''
   The statement said this interfered with ``the legitimate
activity of collecting taxes and the efforts of soldiers to restore
quiet.''
   Atrash said the consensus in the town was ``no taxation under
occupation.''
   He estimated that more than $500,000 worth of furniture and
machinery has been confiscated during the raids on the town, which
is prosperous from scores of family-owned shops.
   Atrash said in a telephone interview he appreciated the
diplomats' efforts.
   ``I think that the diplomats' acceptance of the invitation and
their effort to come shows the political support of our people, not
only in Beit Sahour but also in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,'' he
said. ``It is a victory.''
   In Jerusalem's Mukassed Hospital, Hamad Shami, 17, died of a
gunshot wound to the chest suffered Thursday when soldiers fired at
youths stoning trains, hospital officials said.
   Shami's death raised to 585 the number of Palestinians killed by
Israeli troops or civilians during the uprising against Israeli
occupation. Another 127 Palestinians have been killed by fellow
Arabs, most on suspicion of collaborating with Israel. Forty
Israelis have died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
