<FIRST>r a AM-HazelwoodCase     10-06 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hazelwood Case,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial For Exxon Skipper Likely to Move Out of Valdez</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors and defense attorneys agree
the trial of the skipper of the tanker Exxon Valdez should be moved
from the port city of Valdez but where the trial will be held has
not been decided.
   Former Exxon Capt. Joseph Hazelwood faces misdemeanor charges of
operating a vessel while intoxicated, reckless endangerment and
negligent discharge of pollutants as a result of the nation's worst
oil spill. A felony indictment charges him with three counts of
second-degree criminal mischief.
   Hazelwood, 42, of Huntington, N.Y., is scheduled for trial in
January. He is free on $50,000 bail.
   The tanker was under Hazelwood's command on March 24 when it ran
aground on Bligh Reef after he turned the controls over to the
vessel's third mate. More than 11 million gallons of thick crude
oil spilled into Prince William Sound.
   Defense lawyers Richard Friedman and Dick Madson want to move
the trial and Assistant District Attorney Brent Cole said the state
supported the move.
   Because of pretrial publicity and the economic impact of the
spill on Valdez, ``we just agreed in the interests of expeditious
proceedings to not go through the hassle of trying to get a jury in
Valdez,'' Cole said.
   Cole said he has asked that the trial be held 125 miles away in
Anchorage, but Friedman said he was unsure that would be a good
choice. ``I think we're moving in the right direction _ away from
Valdez,'' he said.
   Anchorage Superior Court Judge Karl Johnstone was assigned the
case this week after Palmer Superior Court Judge Beverly Cutler
disqualified herself. Cutler said litigation handled by her father
and her sister could create the appearance of a conflict of
interest.
   Johnstone is a commercial fisherman who owns a drift gillnet
permit for Bristol Bay. Friedman said Johnstone's fishing was known
when he was assigned the case, and the defense team does not
believe the activity poses a conflict. Fishermen were among those
affected by the spill.
</TEXT>
