<FIRST>r a AM-AirForce-Haye     10-06 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Force-Haye,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Officer Pondering Fate After Conviction Set Aside</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Air Force officer says she's
relieved that a military appeals court has set aside her conviction
for an alleged affair with a man who worked with her in Titan 2
missile silos.
   A military appeals court at Little Rock Air Force Base
overturned Naomi Haye's fraternization conviction last week. It
ordered her reinstated with full back pay of about $75,000, minus
what she has earned in civilian employment since her dismissal from
the service in 1986.
   The tribunal left open the possibility that the former
lieutenant could be retried, although her attorney said another
trial was unlikely. An Air Force spokesman said Wednesday that no
decision had been made.
   ``I don't know what plans they have for me,'' Mrs. Haye, 32,
said Thursday from her home in Guam, where she lives with her
husband, Air Force Sgt. Patrick Haye, and two children.
   A panel of military judges convicted Mrs. Haye at a November
1986 court-martial of two counts of adultery with a fellow officer
and an enlisted man. She was also convicted of fraternization with
the enlisted man.
   The adultery conviction involving the enlisted man was thrown
out after her trial because it duplicated the fraternization
charge. The Air Force Court of Military Review overturned the other
adultery conviction last year.
   Fraternization is defined as a friendly relationship between an
officer and an enlisted person, detrimental to military order and
discipline.
   Neither of the two men was court-martialed or denied promotion,
according to Mrs. Haye's attorney, Morgan Welch.
   Mrs. Haye has contended she was singled out for prosecution
because she was a white officer married to a black enlisted man.
   The appeals court decided Mrs. Haye hadn't received a fair trial.
   ``I'm very relieved,'' Mrs. Haye said Thursday. ``It was a phone
call I was looking forward to.''
   She had been deputy commander of a missile crew at the Little
Rock base.
</TEXT>
