<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 2004EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets     10-06 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy Additional 1.1 Million Tons of Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporting companies have sold the
Soviet Union an additional 1.1 million metric tons of U.S. corn _
with a potential value of nearly $100 million _ for delivery in
1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement, the Agriculture
Department said Friday.
   The corn sale was the fourth this week to the Soviet Union, with
orders now totaling 3.7 million tons of corn and 100,000 tons of
soybean meal. The seventh year of the agreement began Sunday.
   U.S. grain sales to Moscow in 1988-89 were a record of more than
21.7 million tons, including more than 16.3 million tons of corn
and nearly 5.4 million tons of wheat.
   In addition, 1988-89 sales included 442,500 tons of soybeans,
1.35 million tons of soybean meal and 1.02 million tons of grain
sorghums.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 1.1 million tons
of corn would be more than 43.3 million bushels.
   The new sales were made by unidentified private exporting
companies, which are required to report large sales to the
department. No selling prices or further details were released.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.28 per bushel at the
farm level, according to USDA's five-day average, meaning that the
latest sale could have a farm value of almost $99 million.
</TEXT>
