<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1606EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap 1stLd-Writethru a0654 10-06 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0654,0877</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kidnappers Seize Two Swiss Red Cross Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads thruout to UPDATE with Palestinian spokesman linking kidnappings
to Shiite Moslem hijacker, edits to trim. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GEV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked kidnappers pushed two Swiss Red
Cross workers into a car Friday and sped into a Palestinian refugee
camp outside this ancient port in south Lebanon, police reported.
   A Palestinian guerrilla spokesman linked the abductions to a
Lebanese Shiite Moslem hijacker imprisoned in Switzerland.
   The victims were identified as Emmanuel Christen, 32, and Elio
Erriquez, 23, orthopedic technicians at an artificial limb center
operated by the International Committee of the Red Cross in Sidon,
25 miles south of Beirut.
   None of Lebanon's armed factions claimed responsibility.
   Eighteen Westerners, including eight Americans, are missing in
Lebanon, most believed to be captives of Shiite Moslems loyal to
Iran. Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Friday's abductions were the latest of several involving
foreigners working for relief agencies in south Lebanon. Most are
blamed on Fatah-Revolutionary Council, a Palestinian group led by
terrorist Abu Nidal, who broke with PLO chairman Yassir Arafat in
1973.
   Zeid Wehbeh, spokesman for the Palestine Liberation
Organization, said the PLO would ``spare no effort'' to help rescue
the victims.
   Moein Shabaita, spokesman for Yasser Arafat's Fatah faction, the
PLO's main guerrilla component, linked the kidnappings to a
Lebanese Shiite Moslem hijacker, Mohammed Hariri.
   Hariri was jailed for life in February for hijacking an Air
Afrique jetliner July 24, 1987, and killing a French passenger
after the plane landed in Geneva.
   Shabaita said the group that kidnapped Christen and Erriquez was
the same that abducted Swiss Red Cross worker Peter Winkler last
year, ``apparently for the purpose of trying to win Hariri's
release.''
   Winkler was kidnapped Nov. 17 and freed Dec. 16.
   People in Sidon reported seeing a convoy of seven Red Cross cars
with Swiss officials inside heading for Beirut in late afternoon.
Red Cross officials would not say whether the International
Committee, which is based in Geneva, would pull out of Lebanon as
it did last year after another kidnapping.
   Sidon police said Christen and Erriquez were seized at 7:30 a.m.
after arriving at the artificial limb center, which occupies the
ground floor of a four-story building near Ein el-Hilweh, a
Palestinian refugee camp on the southeastern outskirts.
   The relief workers drove there from the International
Committee's downtown headquarters, half a mile away, in a white
sedan identified by the Red Cross insignia on each side and a Red
Cross flag, police reported.
   Armed kidnappers wearing black masks waited in two cars outside
the center, said a police spokesman, whose name was withheld under
standing regulations.
   ``Christen, who was driving, parked outside the center and
climbed out, holding an artificial limb. Erriquez got out the other
door, followed by a Lebanese ICRC employee,'' he said.
   Two kidnappers jumped from a car, one brandishing a pistol and
the other a submachine gun, the spokesman reported.
   ``Christen and Erriquez put their hands up, offering no
resistance,'' he said. They were bundled at gunpoint into the trunk
of the gunmen's Mercedes, which sped off, followed by the other car
packed with gunmen.
   He said several witnesses saw the two cars racing into Ein
el-Hilweh.
   International Committee spokesman Jeorg Bischof said in Geneva
the abduction ``hinders the very important work the Red Cross is
doing in Lebanon.''
   Police said the orthopedic center, which provides artificial
limbs for victims of Lebanon's 14-year-old sectarian civil war, was
closed indefinitely after the abduction.
   Christen, in Lebanon since October 1987, had told friends:
``I've been here so long because I love it. I don't intend to ask
for a transfer.''
   Erriquez, who arrived in April, told colleagues: ``The
experience of working here will be good for me.''
   At least nine relief agency workers _ West Germans,
Scandinavians, Belgians and Swiss _ have been kidnapped in south
Lebanon during the past two years.
   Police and other sources have blamed Abu Nidal, whose real name
is Sabry al-Banna. He has bases at Ein el-Hilweh and in the smaller
Mieh Mieh refugee camp nearby.
   Mustafa Saad, commander of the Nasserite militia, a Sunni Moslem
group that has controlled Sidon throughout the civil war, blamed
Palestinians for the latest abduction but was not more specific.
   ``This is an Ein el-Hilweh affair, not mine,'' he told reporters
after a 10-minute meeting with Roland Sidler, the International
Committee's director in south Lebanon.
   Sidler would not talk to reporters.
   Saad ordered his militiamen to search all cars leaving Sidon.
   The International Committee withdrew its 31 Swiss nationals from
Lebanon on Dec. 20 after death threats from factions that were not
identified.
   Press reports in Switzerland and Lebanon said Winkler's
kidnappers, not identified, had threatened more attacks on Swiss
workers, claiming Swiss authorities reneged on a pledge to pay
ransom for Winkler.
   A 29-member Swiss group returned Jan. 22 after all Lebanese
factions promised there would be no attacks on humanitarian
organizations.
</TEXT>
