<SECOND>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0644,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Feels `Just Fine' After Finger Operation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with surgery complete, makes editing
changes throughout. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush underwent minor surgery on
Friday to remove a troublesome cyst from his finger, and said
afterward he felt ``just fine.''
   ``It was real minor,'' Bush told reporters as he left Walter
Reed Army Medical Center holding his right hand with bandaged
middle finger aloft.
   ``All is well,'' he said with a laugh.
   Bush said he had not felt any pain during the 25-minute
operation because he had been administered a local anesthetic,
called digital nerve block anestheisa. It was expected to wear off
three or four hours after the operation, and Bush said the doctors
had told him to expect some pain then.
   The White House said pain medication would be prescribed ``as
necessary.'' Bush left the hospital by helicopter to fly to Camp
David, Md., for the weekend.
   In a statement, White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater
called the operation ``entirely successful.''
   He said Bush had eight stiches for the 1{-inch incision, and
would wear a splint on the finger for two to three weeks.
   ``No long-term impairmnet of movement in the finger is
expected,'' Fitzwater said.
   The cyst ``appeared benign'' according to White House physician
Dr. Burton Lee, who observed the operation. However, a pathological
examination of the tissue was still under way.
   The White House identified the surgeons as Col. Allen Smith,
chief of hand surgery at Walter Reed, and George Bogumill, who
holds a similar position at Gerogetown University Hospital.
   Smith was to make a follow-up exam of the finger at the White
House on Oct 10.
   Making light of the matter the day before the surgery, Bush had
laughed over it and told reporters not to ``make a federal case of
it.''
   Bush has had the cyst on the middle finger of his right hand for
several years, but it recently came to the point of being
bothersome, Fitzwater said.
   The spokesman told reporters the cyst was ``not really painful,
but it's a nuisance in the sense that it's large enough to cause
him some anxiety.''
   Doctors had drained the cyst on May 10 when Bush underwent a
routine physical examination. The doctors said it had been present
for several years and did not pose a medical problem for the
65-year-old president.
   In recent weeks, Bush, who is left-handed, has been playing
golf, tennis and horseshoes and baiting fishhooks, as well as
signing proclamations, with no apparent difficulty from the cyst.
   The cyst was described as a quarter-inch in diameter, rising
about an eighth of an inch above the surface of the finger, with a
root that extended under the skin back toward the finger joint.
   The president jokingly told reporters ``Don't tempt me'' when
asked to display the finger in question for cameras and
photographers during a photo session Thursday with Angolan rebel
leader Jonas Savimbi. He then explained to Savimbi that the finger
is sometimes used for an obscene gesture.
   Bush promised reporters, ``I will show you my scar afterward.''
   Bush's doctors say he is in very good health and exceptionally
good condition for his age, as evidenced by his propensity for
vigorous sports and his often tightly-packed work schedule.
   He had a basal cell skin cancer removed from his face and a
small, noncancerous polyp removed from his colon in 1986, when he
was vice president.
</TEXT>
