<FIRST>u w AM-ShuttleLawsuit 1stLd-Writethru a0662 10-06 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Lawsuit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Denies Dangers From Launch of Galileo</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: CORRECTS Pluto to Neptune in 4th graf pvs, bgng, To date ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space agency told a federal court Friday
there are no safety reasons for stopping next week's launch of a
nuclear-powered probe from the space shuttle and that opponents are
trying to spread ``a tale of horrors.''
   ``There is no evidence that these horrors will in fact or are
likely to occur,'' NASA told U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch in a
court filing.
   Gasch has scheduled oral arguments on Tuesday _ two days before
the shuttle Atlantis is to lift off from Kennedy Space Center
carrying into orbit a probe called Galileo, powered by two
24.7-pound nuclear generators.
   To date, NASA has spent $1.5 billion on the project, which will
culminate in six years when the craft begins orbiting the planet
Jupiter. The nuclear devices create electricity for the long
journey and are similar to the ones that powered the Voyager probe
as it swept past Neptune recently.
   A coalition of citizens' groups has sought a court order to stop
the launch, claiming that the danger of plutonium contamination
from a shuttle disaster is far greater than the government has
admitted.
   The groups, led by the Florida Coalition for Peace and Justice,
asked Gasch to issue a temporary restraining order and a
preliminary injunction and have threatened to disrupt the launch in
other ways.
   ``In essence, plaintiffs do not like the launch decision and are
trying to get the court to second-guess the executive branch of the
government with regard to the acceptability of risk,'' said the
brief filed by Justice Department lawyer Stuart B. Schoenburg.
   Opponents of the launch warned that the possibilities of an
accident and a deadly plutonium release from Galileo are 1-in-350.
   NASA countered, in Friday's filing, that exhaustive
environmental impact studies showed the most probable accident
statistically would be failure of the rocket that is to propel the
space probe after it is released from the shuttle cargo bay.
   Even if the two thermonuclear power plants reentered Earth's
atmosphere, broke apart on hard rock and released plutonium, NASA
said, there would be no additional cancer deaths over a 70-year
period.
   The space probe's journey to Jupiter will be a complicated one,
involving one slingshot orbit of Venus and two of Earth to gain
momentum, and NASA said the highest potential for human harm would
be if the craft crashed through the atmosphere when it makes its
closest approach to Earth. The chances of that happening are 5 in
10 million.
   ``Under this maximum case scenario, there is a 1 in 10 million
probability of 9.4 excess cancer fatalities worldwide over a
70-year period,'' NASA said and the average individual risk would
be one in 25 billion.
   ``Plaintiffs seem to confuse possibility with probability,'' the
government brief said. ``Instead of focusing upon what is likely to
happen, they dwell upon the worst case which is highly unlikely to
occur.''
   NASA said the protesters ``at best, represent the narrow
concerns of a small segment of the public,'' and come to the court
with ``unclean hands'' because they filed suit just days before the
launch.
   The space agency plans to begin the countdown on Monday as
scheduled, but will halt activities at the 11-hour mark to await
any court action. The shuttle does not get fuel until the final
hours of the countdown.
   The government said ``volumes of safety analyses'' had been
prepared and circulated among experts, that the public at large had
a chance to comment on environmental impact studies and that the
president's science adviser had approved after ``an elaborate
launch approval process.''
   It said the court action ``is an attack on the judgment and
integrity'' of scientists and public officials involved.
   While the action proceeded in court, another group _ Public
Citizen _ circulated a letter it plans to send to individual
members of Congress on Monday. It urges them to intercede in the
launch because ``an explosion similar to the Challenger disaster
could be catastrophic for Florida's heavily populated Atlantic
Coast.''
</TEXT>
