<FIRST>r a AM-SovietDefection     10-06 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Defection,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missing Russian Violinist Turns Up, Says He Hopes for Asylum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of three Soviet musicians who
disappeared while visiting the Baltimore area last month with a
string ensemble has turned up in Savannah, where he says he hopes
to win asylum.
   Violinist Yuri Alexov disappeared Sept. 28 while visiting Towson
State University with the Leningrad State Conservatory, university
spokeswoman Kathy Williams said Friday. Another member of the
group, Mikhail Istomin, disappeared the same day, and Pyotr Zaytsev
disappeared Sept. 22, she said.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service officials said it was not
their practice to comment on whether any application for asylum had
been made, but a Savannah resident who is assisting Alexov said the
violinist has been told he will be allowed to remain in this
country.
   Misha Gubenko, an engineer who emigrated to Savannah from the
Soviet Union 10 years ago, said Friday that Alexov had spoken with
INS officials in Baltimore and was told to expect papers allowing
him to stay.
   Alexov will be the guest of Savannah's small but close-knit
Russian community, Gubenko said.
   ``I consider it one family,'' he said.
   Gubenko's son Alex, who served as interpreter for Alexov during
a news conference in Savannah on Thursday, said Alexov had been
``thinking of ways to get out'' for years.
   He said Alexov, 28, hopes his wife and 5-year-old son will be
allowed to join him. ``He's not sure, but he's hoping.''
   Zaytsev, a 19-year-old who plays the balalaika, an instrument
similar to a guitar, disappeared Sept. 22 before a scheduled
performance of the ensemble.
   Alexov and Istomin, a cellist, failed to return from a period of
free time six days later, Ms. Williams said. The rest of the group,
which had spent 10 days at the university performing as part of a
cultural exchange, left for Moscow later that day, she said.
   School officials did not know the whereabouts of any of the men
until Alexov turned up in Savannah, Ms. Williams said.
   INS officials ``just said they're safe and they're not
missing,'' she said.
   Alexov said through the interpreter that he spent two days with
a priest and two days with a new friend in Baltimore before calling
a friend who plays with the Savannah Symphony.
   The friend, who identified himself only as Oleg, said he drove
to Baltimore to get Alexov.
   ``The only thing he had was his violin and the clothes on his
back,'' said Alex Gubenko. The interpreter said it was painful for
Alexov to leave his family, but he does not want to go back to the
Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
