<FIRST>u w AM-Yazov     10-06 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yazov,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Defense Minister Invites Cheney to Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Defense Minister Dimitri Yazov ended
his first U.S. visit Friday by inviting his counterpart to Moscow,
praising American soldiers and bragging about the impenetrability
of his country's air defense system.
   Yazov and Defense Secretary Dick Cheney appeared at a joint news
conference where they pledged a continuation of military exchanges,
but made no substantive announcements.
   ``It is important to build friendship, develop mutual
understanding,'' said Yazov, who met with President Bush on his
week-long trip.
   Cheney, who said he would visit the Soviet Union at a
yet-to-be-decided time, said the military-to-military contacts
between the two superpower defense chiefs were ``very productive.''
   In an aside, Cheney said later he had been with Yazov on a bus
touring the Civil War battlefield at Gettysburg, Pa., when he
received the first report by portable telephone Tuesday that a coup
was underway in Panama. The coup against Panamanian ruler Manuel
Antonio Noriega failed within hours.
   During the week, Yazov visited Camp Pendleton, a Marine training
base north of San Diego; Luke Air Force Base in Arizona and Fort
Bragg, home of the Army's 82nd Airborne in Fayetteville, N.C.
   What impressed him most, Yazov said, were the soldiers _
``dedicated young men'' with a ``high level of training.''
   In a question-and-answer session with reporters, Yazov said the
Soviets are not worried about the development of the B-2 bomber,
the radar-evading plane known as Stealth.
   ``We don't have to modify the Soviet air defense system,'' he
said, adding the Soviets ``can bring down any air threat.'' But he
said he hoped the United States would not use the B-2 ``so we would
not be forced to bring them down.''
   On other subjects, he said the Soviet armed forces have not been
increased in size, but obsolete weapons systems have been replaced.
   Asked whether the Soviet Union was concerned about the Strategic
Defense Initiative, Yazov challenged a reporter: ``Are you aware of
what SDI is? Could you explain it to me?''
   He called SDI ``hypothetical,'' and said the Soviet Union
opposed putting weapons in space. ``We don't intend to create any
similiar space-based weapons'' systems, he said.
   U.S. officials also said Cheney and Yazov discussed an incident
of a Soviet warship plying the Mediterranean opening fire on a U.S.
surveillance plane south of Crete Sept. 22.
   Naval officials said the Soviets apologized for the incident and
said the Soviets had no intention of endangering U.S. aircraft. The
incident was first reported in The Los Angeles Times.
</TEXT>
