<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Activists Agree To Release Embassy Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist activists ended their
28-hour takeover of the Costa Rican Embassy on Friday, releasing
the 12 hostages they held to protest against President Alfredo
Cristiani's rightist government.
   A total of 12 hostages and 20 members of the Federation of
Committees of Mothers and Relatives of Political Prisoners were
evacuated in six International Red Cross vehicles around 1:30 p.m.,
watched by journalists.
   The reporters were kept 30 yards away by police and not allowed
to talk to the evacuees. None of the activists nor the one Costa
Rican diplomat and 11 Salvadoran embassy employees appeared to be
hurt.
   Government spokesman Mauricio Sandoval told reporters some of
the activists left weapons ``inside the (embassy) offices or
hidden,'' because they carried none when they boarded the Red Cross
vehicles.
   The activists have insisted they were not armed, but Costa Rican
diplomats disputed that.
   Sandoval said the hostages were being taken to Red Cross
headquarters in San Salvador, where they would be undergo medical
checks before being sent home, and the activists returned to the
federation office.
   He said the Salvadoran government could eventually file charges
against some of those involved in the takeover.
   The federation has been protesting for the past eight years the
kidnapping and killing of suspected leftists by rightist death
squads. The decade-old civil war has killed more than 70,000
people, between death-squad victims and casualties of the fighting.
</TEXT>
