<FIRST>r w AM-ConsumerCredit     10-06 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Credit,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumers Resume Borrowing in August</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $3.48 billion more in
consumer debt than they retired in August, the government reported
Friday, resuming their borrowing practices as expected after
reducing their debt in July for the first time in 2{ years.
   Analysts had said the July debt liquidation was a one-time
thing, and forecast continued borrowing in the foreseeable future.
   ``We really haven't become a nation of big savers,'' said
economist Sandra Shaber of the Futures Group, a Washington
forecasting firm. ``People aren't tearing up their credit cards.''
   The Federal Reserve Board said consumer credit in August
increased at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 6 percent,
compared to July's revised decrease of 0.9 percent, which was even
steeper than the 0.5 percent originally reported.
   The decline in July was the first since January 1987, when
consumer debt fell $1.63 billion, or 3.4 percent.
   For all of 1988, consumer credit climbed 8.5 percent.
   The August debt rebound had been expected in part because of
robust automobile sales propelled by end-of-model-year sales
incentives and the threat of steep price increases for 1990 models.
   Auto loans, which fell 6.9 percent in July and 2.3 percent in
June, grew by $400 million in August, or 1.7 percent on an annual
rate. Auto loans had declined $1.67 billion in July.
   The category of debt that includes credit cards rose by $3.57
billion in August, resuming a sharp 22.5 percent annual rate of
increase. It had risen only 8.9 percent to $1.41 billion in July,
down from a 20.1 percent hike in June.
   ``People are shifting now from things like cars and other major
durables to soft goods'' such as clothing, Mrs. Shaber said. ``This
reflects a shift in household spending patterns that has been going
on for the past year.''
   Consumer spending, which represents two-thirds of all economic
activity, is watched closely as a sign of economic health,
particularly in light of Fed efforts to contain inflation by
slowing the economy _ but without driving it into a recession.
   The Federal Open Market Committee, the Fed's monetary
policy-making body, met earlier this week to determine credit
strategy for the coming weeks. Its decision will not be disclosed
publicly for six weeks.
   Nevertheless, analysts did not expect any major changes in
central bank policies and look for interest rates to continue at
their current level for much of the remainder of the year.
   Bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate rose by
$158 million, a 1 percent annual rate of growth. That compared with
a 1.1 percent decline in July.
   Mobile home debts continued to fall, down a whopping $656
million or a 33.3 percent annual rate of decline. This category has
fallen for seven consecutive months including a July drop of $56
million, or 2.8 percent.
   The various changes left total consumer debt in August at a
seasonally adjusted $703.8 billion.
</TEXT>
