<FIRST>r w AM-FedPolicy     10-06 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fed Policy,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Reserve Wants To Hold Interest Rates Steady</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Policy-makers at the Federal Reserve decided
to keep interest rates unchanged in late August, following a period
earlier in the summer when they were nudging rates lower, according
to minutes of the meeting released Friday.
   The Federal Open Market Committee voted 10-1 at its Aug. 22
meeting to make no changes in interest rates although it issued a
directive that leaned toward credit-easing if the economy weakened.
   ``For the period ahead, a steady course was desirable in light
of the latest evidence suggesting that price pressures were not
intesifying'' and the economy was continuing to grow at a moderate
pace, the committee said.
   The bellwether federal funds rate _ the interest rate most
closely watched for signals of Fed policy decisions _ fell from
9.75 percent in early June to 9 percent by late July as the central
bank eased its credit grip amid signs of widespread economic
weakness.
   However, since that time, various indicators show that the
economy was not as weak as previously feared and the Fed has made
no further moves to ease credit conditions. The funds rate, the
interest banks charge each other to make overnight loans, has been
unchanged at 9 percent for the past two months.
   The Open Market Committee, composed of Fed governors in
Washington and five of the 12 Fed regional bank presidents, met
again on Wednesday. The minutes of that meeting will not be
released until after the next Open Market Committee meeting on Nov.
14, but private economists said they believed that the central bank
decided again this week to make no moves to change credit policy.
   The Labor Department reported Friday that the unemployment rate
rose to 5.3 percent in September as manufacturing employment took
the biggest one-month nosedive since the end of the last recession.
   But Allen Sinai, chief economist of the Boston Co., said he
believed that it would take more signs of weakness than one month's
unemployment report to convince the Fed to loosen credit further.
   Fed policy-makers did leave room for further easing with a
directive that leaned in that direction.
   Roger Guffey, president of the Kansas City regional Fed bank,
cast the lone dissenting vote, arguing that in his view inflation
remained at unacceptably high levels and this did not permit any
bias toward easing.
</TEXT>
