<FIRST>u w AM-Victims-RedCross     10-06 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Victims-Red Cross,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Kidnapped As Red Cross Prepares Campaign to Aid Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Kidnap, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The kidnapping of two Red Cross workers in
Lebanon on Friday occurred even as the organization was planning
worldwide television concerts in a campaign to benefit war's
civilian victims.
   The campaign is planned to culminate with rock and classical
music concerts and other events May 8, 1991, attempting to persuade
combatants to stop killing civilians, Red Cross officials said.
   Kidnapped in Sidon by masked gunmen were Emmanuel Christen, 32,
and Elio Erriquez, 23, who had been distributing artificial limbs
to victims of Lebanon's civil war.
   ``Today the conflicts don't look like they did'' when the Red
Cross was founded in 1864, ``when there were two or three big
armies clashing on a big field and that was it,'' said Princess
Christina of Sweden.
   The princess, representing a seven-nation steering committee
planning the campaign, spoke in an interview Thursday.
   The organizers are enlisting rock stars and other popular
figures to head drives in many of the 148 countries that have Red
Cross or Red Crescent organizations, said Leon Davico, the
Geneva-based campaign director.
   Princess Christina said the Red Cross will base its campaign on
conventions agreed to by virtually all nations in which they
promised to respect rules regarding prisoners, soldiers and
combatants during wars.
   Davico added, ``We'll tell the armies, `You have the duty to
protect the civilians. If you want to fight, it's your business,
unfortunately, but you haven't got the right to kill defenseless
women and children and old people.'''
   Princess Christina said there were about 30 conflicts in the
world that cause concern, but they usually don't fit the
traditional pattern of one country at war with another.
   ``It's internal conflicts within a country or within a region,''
she said, noting the conflicts sometimes involve political or
religious groups.
   Princess Christina said the planners had yet to set a
fund-raising goal for the project.
   Davico said there would be a series of concerts, in a worldwide
television event, with a rock concert reminiscent of the Band Aid
gala to raise money for famine relief in Africa.
   But he said there would be other events such as a classical
concert from the United States or a brief program from the Bolshoi
ballet in Moscow or something form Tokyo.
   Interspersed in the entertainment, he said, would be 10 short
films, each lasting 5-7 minutes, about war victims. The films will
be produced by top film makers from different countries.
</TEXT>
