<DOCNO> AP891006-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1733EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AryanMarch     10-06 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aryan March,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pulaski Shutting Down For Aryan Nations March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PULASKI, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business and community leaders in this
southern Tennessee community are taking a simple approach to
Saturday's scheduled march by white supremacists: They plan to shut
the town down.
   ``I'm hoping it's pouring down rain. That'd put a damper on
them,'' Mayor Hal Stewart said Friday. The group has a
constitutional right to march, he said, but town residents aren't
happy about the gathering.
   ``I doubt there'll be over five places open in Pulaski, and
they'll probably be on the outlying sections of the city,'' Stewart
said.
   ``We're just going to shut the town down and let them have their
march. There won't be anything open around the square. All the
merchants downtown agreed to close.''
   The Aryan Nations, a white supremacist group based in Hayden
Lake, Idaho, plans the early afternoon march to commemorate the
Oct. 6 birthday of Civil War hero Sam Davis.
   Davis, a Confederate scout, was hanged in Pulaski after refusing
to tell Union leaders who revealed information about movements of
Northern troops.
   Pulaski, population 7,600, also has a footnote in history as the
1865 birthplace of the original Ku Klux Klan. The current Klan,
which traces its roots to 1915 Georgia, also has marched here.
   No one knows how many marchers to expect Saturday in this town
90 miles south of Nashville, but the Tennessee Highway Patrol will
help police from Pulaski and surrounding towns with security.
   ``All we've got to go on is what their leader says, and he says
they're going to bring in a thousand,'' the mayor said of the
group's chief, the Rev. Richard G. Butler. ``We don't have any
proof there'll be that many.''
   City officials are counting on Police Chief Stanley Newton's
experience with the Klan.
   ``He's had three years of experience with three other marches by
the Klan, so we feel he and his officers are well-seasoned,'' said
Alderman Dan Speer.
   Pulaski residents were quietly indignant about the Klan marches,
which began in 1986 to protest designation of Martin Luther King's
birthday as a national holiday. But this time they decided to take
a stronger stand.
   A group called Giles Countians United, after trying to
discourage the march with petitions and resolutions, is urging
Giles County residents to stay away from the downtown area to avoid
possible confrontations with the marchers.
   ``Our whole goal is to at least tell the rest of the world that
Pulaski does not share the views of that group,'' said organizer
Mike Curry, president of Pulaski's First National Bank.
   Many residents have made a point of leaving town Saturday, and
two high school football games were moved up to Thursday night to
avoid incoming Aryan Nations members.
   More than 130 businesses agreed to close their doors Saturday,
no small decision, according to Speer, an insurance agent and
former restaurant owner.
   ``This is going to be the first Saturday of the month, which
traditionally is the most profitable Saturday and the busiest of
the month,'' Speer said. ``This is going to cost each business
several thousand dollars. The sacrifice the owners and employees
are making needs to be recognized.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
