<DOCNO> AP891006-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 2053EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-APME-PublicService     10-06 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-APME-Public Service,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Tribune, Albuquerque Tribune Cited for Public Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Associated Press Managing Editors
association presented its 1989 Public Service Awards on Friday to
the Chicago Tribune and The Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune.
   The Chicago Tribune, in the 50,000-and-over category, was
selected for its investigation into the mismanagement, greed and
corruption that created the savings and loan crisis.
   The Albuquerque Tribune led those in the under-50,000
circulation class with a report on the effects of alcoholism on the
Indian residents of Gallup, N.M.
   Robert H. Giles, editor and publisher of The Detroit News and
chairman of the judging panel, presented the plaques today at the
APME convention here.
   The other judges, all former presidents of APME, were Larry
Allison, senior vice president and editor, Long Beach (Calif.)
Press-Telegram; James Daubel, editor and publisher, Fremont (Ohio)
News-Messenger; Michael J. Davies, editor and publisher, Hartford
(Conn.) Courant; Robert J. Haiman, chairman, The Poynter Institute
for Media Studies, St. Petersburg, Fla.; Ted M. Natt, editor and
publisher, Longview (Wash.) Daily News, and Joseph W. Shoquist,
dean of the College of Journalism and Mass Communications at the
University of South Carolina.
   The other finalists in the 50,000-and-over circulation category
were: Anchorage (Alaska) Daily News; Colorado Springs (Colo.)
Gazette Telegraph; The Detroit News; The Greenville (S.C.) News;
The Hartford (Conn.) Courant; The Orlando (Fla.) Sentinel; Roanoke
(Va.) Times &amp; World-News; San Francisco Examiner, and USA Today.
   Under-50,000-circulation finalists were: The State-Times of
Baton Rouge, La.; The Beverly (Mass.) Times and The Peabody (Mass.)
Times; Gwinnett Daily News of Lawrenceville, Ga.; Herald-Dispatch
of Huntington, W.Va.; The Journal of Commerce (New York City);
Naples (Fla.) Daily News; Poughkeepsie (N.Y.) Journal; Scottsdale
(Ariz.) Progress, and The Wilkes-Barre (Pa.) Times Leader.
