<FIRST>r w AM-FirePrevention     10-06 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fire Prevention,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elderly Are High Risk For Fire Deaths</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nursing Home Fire, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fires that strike nursing homes are especially
dangerous because the elderly are a high risk group for fire
deaths, a spokeswoman for a national fire safety group said Friday.
   In fact, Americans over the age of 65 accounted for nearly
one-fourth of the fire fatalities in the ountry during a recent
four-year period, said Julie Reynolds, a spokeswoman for the
National Fire Prevention Association.
   ``They have the highest fire fatality rates involving smoking
materials, heating and cooking equipment and electrical fires,''
Reynolds said in a telephone interview.
   Careless smoking was blamed for the fire that killed nine people
and injured nearly 100 others when it struck a 172-bed nursing home
in Norfolk, Va., Thursday night. The nine residents who died ranged
in age from 65 to 97.
   An association study from 1982-1986 showed the elderly have a
fire death rate of 57.8 per 1 million population, about three times
the national average of 19.6 per million, Reynolds said.
   During the same period, the study showed that Americans over 65
accounted for 24.1 percent of the nation's fire deaths.
   ``There are certainly some factors that contribute to the higher
fire fatality rates,'' Reynolds said, noting some senior citizens
may be confined to living situations like nursing homes where they
may be bedridden or have physical problems which make their rescue
or escape difficult.
   For both private homes and nursing homes, the group recommends
smoke detectors in each sleeping room. Institutions should also
place smoke detectors in corridors and common spaces, the group
recommends.
   In addition, the fire association said portable fire
extinguishers should be provided near hazardous areas. It also
recommends automatic sprinkler systems for new high rise buildings.
   Fire officials said the Norfolk nursing home did not have any
sprinklers, but added they were not required when the home was
built in 1969.
   Reynolds noted the Virginia nursing home tragedy came right
before the group's National Fire Prevention Week, which is Oct.
8-14.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891006-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1732EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Refugees-USEmbassy     10-06 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-US Embassy,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Says East Germans Seized Outside US Embassy Can Leave For West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several East Germans detained by police
outside the U.S. Embassy in East Berlin will be permitted to leave
the country, the State Department said Friday.
   Spokesman Richard Boucher said the assurances were given by the
East German government and that he did not know how many people
were involved.
   All of those detained were released from custody with the
exception of two who were arrested for reasons unrelated to
emigration, Boucher said.
   In a related development, the State Department press office said
it had erroneously distributed a notice to reporters that East
Germans hoping to flee to the West were ``politely denied entry''
to the U.S. Embassy.
   A statement issued in its place said the embassy staff asks
those who seek to enter the chancery what their purpose is in
entering the building.
   ``Those who have normal embassy business are allowed to enter,''
the statement said. ``No embassy employees force people off the
premises.''
   The initial press notice, which was issued Thursday night,
reinforced earlier U.S. statements that the embassy was not
equipped to grant waves of would-be emigrants extended sanctuary.
   ``Our embassy is not in a position to accommodate large numbers
of people who want to sit there until other governments do
something,'' Boucher said Thursday.
   Eighteen East Germans _ 10 adults and eight children _
voluntarily left the U.S. Embassy Wednesday evening after a 31-hour
occupation that touched off an effort by dozens of others to try to
get past East German police and into the building.
   Boucher said the East German government had given assurances
that ``their desire to emigrate would be considered positively and
that no reprisals would be taken against them.'' Also, he said, a
woman pushed away by police from the entrance was given similar
assurances.
   ``We try to do what we can to express our humanitarian concerns
for individuals as well as whole groups of people,'' the U.S.
spokesman said.
   But while asserting again American support for the right to
travel, Boucher said it was ``worth remembering'' that the vast
majority of East Germans trying to emigrate wish to settle in West
Germany, and not the United States.
   ``The embassy that we have in Berlin is, of course, not set up
as a place where people can go,'' Boucher said. ``We do not have
the capability to handle even a limited number of people.''
   The U.S. official also cautioned the would-be East German
emigrants that ``people potentially put themselves in a difficult
situation with respect to their own government.''
   Boucher said the advice was based on recent statements by the
East German government that flocking to Western embassies ``was no
longer acceptable.''
   The notice to the press Thursday night said visitors to the
embassy were asked by U.S. officials why they wanted to enter the
building.
   ``Those who have normal embassy business are allowed to enter,''
it said. ``Those who do not are informed that the U.S. is unable to
assist them on other types of matters. They are politely denied
entry. No one is forced from embassy premises.''
   When hundreds of East Germans tried to rush the five-story stone
building in downtown East Berlin on Wednesday, the doors were
slammed shut and East German police called in reinforcements. About
100 formed a line in front of the embassy.
   Boucher said the fact that thousands of East Germans are trying
to flee ``reflects a deep sense of dissatisfaction'' with their
government.
   He said the police were not requested by U.S. Embassy officials.
``We deplore the manhandling of the crowd,'' the spokesman said.
``And the embassy has protested the stopping of people trying to
visit it.''
</TEXT>
