<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 2106EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Soviets     10-06 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviets,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Cabinet Minister Invited To Soviet Union Since 1967</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has invited Vice Prime
Minister Shimon Peres for a visit, officials said Friday. He would
be the first Israeli Cabinet minister to travel there since Moscow
broke relations over the 1967 Middle East War.
   The invitation to Peres, head of the Labor Party, was offered by
the non-governmental Soviet Peace Committee during Peres' meeting
in New York last month with a five-member Soviet trade delegation,
officials said.
   No date has been set, said spokesman Elie Yosef of the Finance
Ministry, which Peres also heads.
   Arye Levin, the head of Israel's consular mission in Moscow,
said the visit could include ``very senior-level contacts.''
Israeli newpapers said Peres might meet with President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   The trip would be another step in renewing ties between the two
countries, a process that started with the exchange of consular
delegations in 1986 and 1987. Moscow and most of the Soviet bloc
had broken relations after Israel captured land from Arab countries
in the 1967 war.
   Levin noted in an Israel army radio interview that Peres was
invited ``not as an Israeli minister but as a public figure, head
of the Labor party. It's an invitation from an official body but
not in the name of the Soviet government.''
   ``We should not see such visits as foretelling an immediate
renewal of ties,'' he said. ``The issue is to create a contact .. .
in order to tighten relations between leaders of the two
countries.''
   The Soviets have said the renewal of diplomatic ties with Israel
depends on progress on Middle East peace. The Soviet Union supports
a U.N.-sponsored international peace conference and talks between
Israel and the Palestine Liberation Organizaion.
   Some Israelis view the invitation to Peres as encouragement to
the left-center Labor Party, which has not opposed the plan for an
international peace conference. Prime Minister Yitzak Shamir, head
of the right-wing Likud bloc, is against such a conference and any
contact with the PLO.
</TEXT>
