<FIRST>u w AM-ToxicFine     10-06 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toxic Fine,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Issues Largest-Ever Toxic Waste Fine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency ordered a
$6.2 million fine Friday against a California company for allegedly
storing more toxic wastes than it was authorized to handle.
   The civil penalty, the largest fine ever under federal toxic
waste disposal laws, was levied against Casmalia Resources of
Casmalia, Calif., operator of a hazardous waste treatment, storage
and disposal facility.
   The EPA accused Casmalia Resources of ``accepting more hazardous
waste materials than its existing landfills were authorized to
handle.''
   The company also was charged with violating federal toxic waste
regulations because it improperly expanded its existing landfills
to accommodate additional wastes.
   EPA spokeswoman Robin Woods said the company must pay the fine
within 30 days or appeal.
   The penalty was based on an estimate on how much additional
profits were earned because the company received the unauthorized
waste shipments. Ms. Woods said the penalty amount could be changed
as more information on the amount of profit becomes available to
the agency.
   Prior to Friday's action, the largest penalty obtained by the
EPA for violation of the federal law governing toxic waste disposal
was $2.78 million last March against the Four County Landfill in
Rochester, Ind. That penalty came as a result of a federal judge's
ruling in a civil suit.
   The fines were issued under the Resource Conservation and
Recovery Act, which established disposal and storage requirements
for hazardous wastes.
   Meanwhile, the EPA announced Friday it was establishing a new
policy in the way it selects contractors for the so-called
Superfund program to avoid a potential conflict of interest that
has been the subject of controversy.
   The Superfund program deals with the cleanup of nearly 1,200 of
the most dangerous hazardous waste sites in the country. Critics
have charged that too often contractors who deal with actual
cleanup activities also work for the EPA on policy matters that
determine how cleanup activities are to be conducted.
   In some cases, critics have charged, a single contracting
company may be in a position to virtually create a job for itself.
   The EPA said the new policy would prohibit contractors actually
involved in cleaning up toxic waste sites or with providing
technical assistance in enforcement actions from competing for
contracts that deal with Superfund policy and regulatory issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
