<SECOND>AM-Children Thrown,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Who Pushed Children From Window Arraigned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother charged with pushing two of her
children from a window of their 10th-floor apartment pleaded
innocent Friday to murdering one child and attempting to murder the
other.
   A court-appointed lawyer for Ameenah Abdus-Salaam, 32, entered
the plea during an arraignment at Queens Criminal Court Friday
afternoon, said Dick Piperno, a spokesman for the Queens District
Attorney.
   Criminal Court Judge William Ehrlbaum granted her lawyer's
request that Mrs. Abdus-Salaam not appear.
   She is charged with murder, attempted murder, first- and
second-degree assault, reckless endangerment and endangering the
welfare of a child.
   The judge ordered her remanded to a city hospital prison for
psychiatric examination.
   Her 6-year-old daughter Zainab was killed and her 3-year-old son
Husein was critically injured Thursday when Mrs. Abdus-Salaam
pushed them from the window, saying ``God is waiting for you,''
officials said.
   Husein remained in very critical condition on a respirator at
North Shore University Hospital on Long Island Friday, said Carol
Hauptman, a spokeswoman for the hospital.
   The toddler suffered massive internal injuries, fractures and
cardiac arrest as a result of his plunge, said Charles De Gaetano
of the Emergency Medical Service.
   Three other siblings were not hurt, including a 1-year-old girl
saved by rescuers who stormed the apartment in time to stop her
being pushed through the window's child-safety bars, officials said.
   Those three children, 1-year-old Amna, her 8-year-old brother
Askia and 4-year-old sister Fatima, remained hospitalized while
social service officials decided which relative to release them to,
according to a hospital spokeswoman.
   Neighbors said the mother had been distraught over the recent
breakup of her marriage.
