<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Panama 1stLd-Writethru   10-06 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0724,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Question U.S. Preparedness for Coup</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 6th graf: ``Boren also'' with Boren saying CIA wasn't
present at meetings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lack of clear policy guidance from President
Bush was largely responsible for U.S. confusion in dealing with
Tuesday's Panamanian coup attempt, Senate Armed Services Committee
Chairman Sam Nunn said Friday.
   Meanwhile, Sen. David Boren, chairman of the Intelligence
Committee, questioned whether Bush was given enough information, in
the right context, to make a crucial decision as the uprising took
place.
   U.S. forces had information indicating troops loyal to Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega were being flown into Tocumen airport
several miles east of Panama City Tuesday morning, but had no
authorization to share that information with the rebels.
   However, said Boren, D-Okla., the rebels believed the
reinforcements were coming from another direction, and had asked
U.S. forces to block two other roads they believed would be used by
the loyalists, leaving the airport road clear.
   ``I just don't believe the information was distilled and
presented to (Bush) in a way that gave him an understanding of the
yes-or-no decision he had to make'' on whether to authorize
blocking of the airport road, Boren said.
   Boren also said no senior personnel from the Central
Intelligence Agency were present during White House meetings to
deal with the coup on Monday and Tuesday.
   Nunn said there should have been definite arrangements for how
U.S. troops were to react in the event of a coup.
   ``We have had a definite, longstanding policy in this country of
encouraging a coup'' in Panama, Nunn, D-Ga., told reporters. ``We
should anticipate that our policy ... might succeed. Then we have
to know what we're going to do next.''
   Nunn, who was among senators who met Friday with Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney and Gen. Colin Powell, chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, said many of the specific facts of the coup
remained murky and were under continuing congressional
investigation.
   A report from the Armed Services and Intelligence Committees was
being prepared, but was expected to be delayed by declassification
procedures at least until next week.
   Nunn complained, ``There were no real plans as to how the people
on the ground (in Panama) were to react'' if a coup took place. ``I
do think there were implicit kinds of commitments made when we
called for the overthrow.''
   Had U.S. officials known what questions to ask of the coup
leaders and under what circumstances they were free to intervene,
the outcome might have been far different, he said.
   Nunn said officials of the U.S. Southern Command, based in
Panama City, should have been under standing instructions to
determine the intent of any leaders of a coup: Did they intend to
recognize and support the duly elected government which was thrown
out by Noriega? Did they want U.S. intelligence data? Would they
turn Noriega over to U.S. authorities?
   On all of those questions, American personnel groped throughout
the morning Tuesday until any opportunity for the United States to
become involved evaporated, Nunn said.
   If there had been clear answers, ``The whole flow of events
might have changed. It would have put us in a totally different
legal and moral position,'' he said.
   Nunn said the United States failed to make proper use of its own
intelligence by bringing appropriate officials together and pooling
information flowing in from all sources. The situation was further
complicated by the simultaneous visit of President Salinas of
Mexico and a senior Soviet military official, he said.
   ``All of those entered into this'' and further underlined the
need for advance policy setting and contingency planning, said Nunn.
   On one disputed point _ whether the rebels asked for help in
getting Noriega out of the headquarters building where they held
him _ Nunn said he tended to accept Cheney's version that no such
request was made.
   During a visit to Capitol Hill Friday, Bush visited Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell to explain what he had known on
Tuesday when he decided not to commit U.S. force to the coup
attempt.
   Mitchell, D-Maine, said he related to Bush the concern many
senators have about whether the United States passed up an
opportunity to apprehend Noriega, but said Bush and chief of staff
John Sununu ``emphatically and categorically'' denied such an
opportunity existed.
</TEXT>
