<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Transit     10-06 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Transit,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Averted Before Baseball Playoff Series</HEAD>
<NOTE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ontario provincial government has averted a
transit strike that could have disrupted traffic to Sunday's
scheduled American League baseball playoff at the downtown SkyDome.
   After an announcement from the Ontario provincial government
that back-to-work legislation would be introduced Tuesday, union
and management of the Toronto Transit Commission announced that
normal schedules would resume Sunday.
   Gerry Phillips, the Ontario Labor Minister, said Thursday the
legislation would send the part-time employment issue to an
independent fact finder who would report back in eight or nine
months.
   The normally efficient transit system has operated erratically
for five weeks because of a ``work to rule'' slowdown by Local 113
of the Amalgamated Transit Union.
   A strike or management lockout Sunday had appeared likely. The
union opposes management plans to hire 450 part-time workers to
ease scheduling and take care of service at peak hours.
   Sunday's game would be the fifth in the best-of-seven playoff
series between the Toronto Blue Jays and Oakland Athletics, who won
the first two games at Oakland.
   ``This bill will get the parties back to work and give them the
tools to solve the one remaining issue,'' Phillips said in a
statement.
   Toronto residents have been allowing as much as 45 minutes'
extra travel time on the transit system, which operates subways,
buses and streetcars.
   The union had been planned to ignore new work schedules the
transit commission was introducing Sunday. Management threatened to
shut down the system in response.
</TEXT>
