<FIRST>u w AM-US-Israel     10-06 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Israel,1st Lead-Writethru,a0676,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Asks Baker To Set Up Talks On Palestinian Delegation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Desk: Tops With 8 grafs new material, picks up with 2nd graf: ``After
the,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir asked
the Bush administration on Friday to set up talks to break a
deadlock on which Palestinian Arabs would participate in
negotiations for self-rule on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Shamir made the request after the Israeli Cabinet turned down,
by tie vote, a Labor Party proposal for a meeting with Egypt on the
difficult issue. He also offered assurances that Israel ``had not
closed the door on the peace process.''
   Shamir's request for U.S. intervention was aired in an interview
with Israel television and elaborated in discussions between U.S.
and Israeli officials.
   It represents an attempt to keep the process alive by having
Secretary of State James A. Baker III set up three-way talks with
Egypt and Israel on a principal sticking point.
   That is, whether two Palestinians who were deported during the
22-month rebellion in the territories should be included in the
Palestinian delegation.
   ``We await these proposals and when they arrive we will give
them serious consideration,'' Shamir said, according to Israeli
embassy spokeswoman Ruth Yaron.
   Meanwhile, a U.S. official, who demanded anonymity, said Baker
was considering the idea as well as other ways to set up
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations. The official insisted the peace
process was not at a dead end.
   ``We are working hard, and we are hopeful,'' he said.
   After the Cabinet's tie vote, Baker talked by telephone with
Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens and Egyptian Foreign Minister
Esmet Abdel-Meguid.
   A State Department spokesman, Richard Boucher, insisted Israel
had not rejected Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's 10-point
proposal. ``Our view is that the Israeli Cabinet has held a full
discussion and neither accepted nor rejected the Egyptian ideas,''
he said.
   Mubarak had proposed negotiations in Cairo between an Israeli
delegation and Palestinians, including two who were deported from
the West Bank during the rebellion against Israeli control.
   Mubarak's approach also would require Israel to concede in
advance that it should relinquish territory on the West Bank and in
Gaza as a basis for gaining peace with the Arabs.
   The Egyptian leader put his proposal forward after the Palestine
Liberation Organization had declined to endorse a plan by Shamir to
hold elections among the 1.4 million Palestinian Arabs who live in
the territories.
   The elected Palestinians then would negotiate with Israel an
interim, five-year arrangement for local self-rule to be followed
by wider negotiations on an overall Middle East settlement.
   After Baker met last week in New York with Arens and
Abdel-Meguid he called on the Israeli Cabinet to decide how to
``move forward'' on the Shamir proposal. Otherwise, Baker said at a
news conference Friday: ``We will have to go back to the drawing
board.''
   But after the Israeli Cabinet deadlocked, U.S. officials said
there was no reason to start afresh. Instead, the officials said,
Baker intended to keep the discussions going while also seeking an
accommodation between the Shamir and Mubarak approaches.
   ``Any conclusion that it's over because it didn't happen today
is just not right,'' Boucher said. ``I don't think the secretary
put any time limit on this.''
   The spokesman said Baker was not planning to go to the Middle
East to continue the discussions.
   Baker endorsed the Shamir plan after it was adopted by the
Israeli Cabinet last May. He has also praised the 10 points
unveiled by Mubarak last month, but said they were no substitute
for Shamir's proposal.
   On a related subject, Boucher confirmed reports that Robert
Pelletreau Jr., the U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, recently held two
additional meetings with an official of the Palestine Liberation
Organzation.
   The spokesman declined to disclose what they talked about.
   The PLO news agency, WAFA, said the meetings concerned ``the
efforts under way and the positions of the different concerned
parties to realize a net gain in the peace process.''
   Pelletreau has been meeting in Carthage with PLO officials since
December. The State Department has given only skimpy reports of the
sessions.
</TEXT>
