<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1956EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Labor 1stLd-Writethru a0611 10-06 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Labor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0611,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Transformed by Move to Center</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to note conference ended; picks up 6th `But
for'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discarding its once-sacrosanct policy of
unilateral nuclear disarmament, Britain's opposition Labor Party
completed a transformation at its annual convention this week.
   From rambunctious, radical and noisily left-wing, the socialist
movement has shifted to the center, spruced up its image, dumped
its old working-class rallying cries and borrowed some of
Conservative Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's clothes.
   The reward has been Labor's most commanding and consistent lead
in polls since the party lost power to Mrs. Thatcher a decade ago.
   The price, dismayed Labor leftists complain, has been the
party's soul.
   ``They (the Labor leaders) aim to win by detaching the Labor
Party as a whole,'' former energy secretary Tony Benn, doyen of the
Labor left, complained during the weeklong party conference that
ended Friday in Brighton.
   But for the socialist anthem, ``The Red Flag,'' this year's
convention was scarcely recognizable as a British socialist
gathering. Even the red flags were gone.
   There were hardly any Marxists shoving tracts at delegates; no
howling down of party leaders by left-wingers; fewer jeans,
T-shirts and ban-the-bomb symbols; more collars and ties, more
coiffured hairdos.
   The turnaround on Britain's nuclear arsenal _ an issue that has
bedeviled the Labor Party more than 30 years _ was endorsed with
almost studied calm as part of a wholesale revamping of the party
platform.
   There was no hint of the uproar of 1981, when the convention,
moving left, adopted the no-nuclear-weapons doctrine, which played
a key role in Labor's electoral defeats in 1983 and 1987.
   There was none of the drama with which Aneurin Bevan, an
architect of the welfare state, headed off unilateralism in 1957,
when he pleaded to the convention not to be sent ``naked into the
conference chamber.''
   This year, the 3-2 vote to ditch unilateralism was greeted with
scattered applause, a few scarcely audible boos, and then silence.
   It was a triumph for party leader Neil Kinnock, the one time
left-winger and ardent anti-nuclear campaigner, who has shifted
markedly in the six years since he took over. But it is only since
1987, and Labor's third successive trouncing by Mrs. Thatcher, that
he has succeeded in clamping down.
   ``Ours is the winning way,'' declared 47-year-old Kinnock, who
aims to become prime minister by mid-1992, the deadline for the
next general election.
   Other key changes adopted by the convention included dropping
commitments to re-nationalize most of the state-owned industries
sold off by Mrs. Thatcher, and abolishing some _ but not all _ of
the curbs she has imposed on trade union freedom.
   The new policy calls for abandoning Britain's submarine-launched
nuclear missiles only as part of an international disarmament
accord. U.S. bases will be allowed to remain in Britain, and a
Labor government would buy the U.S. Trident nuclear missiles
ordered by the Thatcher government.
   It envisages a top income tax bracket of 50 percent, compared
with 83 percent when Labor was last in government.
   The Conservatives, who hold their convention next week, dismiss
the changes as public relations touches by an avowedly socialist
party. But they are clearly on the defensive.
   Inflation is above 7 percent, the pound is weak, and on
Thursday, interest rates were hiked to 15 percent, the 11th
increase since June 1988. Labor is 5 to 12 points ahead in polls.
   Denis Kavanagh, professor of politics at Nottingham University,
noted that Labor's big problem was being associated with ``union
power, high taxation, old-fashioned nationalism and weakness on
defense.''
   ``These findings are not new,'' Kavanagh wrote in London's
Sunday Times. ``What has changed since 1987 is the leadership's
determination to dump unpopular baggage.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
