<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-06 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Falls in Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms developed along a cold front from
central Texas through the middle Mississippi Valley to West
Virginia on Friday.
   There were also a few showers in the Northeast, over the
northern Rockies and the northern high Plains region and in the
central Gulf Coast region.
   Fair to partly sunny skies prevailed across the rest of the
nation.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six hour period ending at 2 p.m.
EDT included four-tenths of an inch at Parkersburg, W.Va. and a
third of an inch at Fort Leonard Wood, Mo.
   Thunderstorms developing along the cold front produced severe
weather in Texas and Oklahoma on Thursday evening. One person was
killed in central Oklahoma when strong thunderstorm winds hit the
town of Pocasset, downing power lines and damaging a mobile home.
   Thunderstorms over the Texas Panhandle produced wind gusts to 80
mph at White Deer, which damaged roofs and blew over a pickup. A
thunderstorm at Shamrock, Texas, produced wind gusts to 60 mph.
   Strong northwesterly winds continued Friday to bring cold air
into the north-central states, with winds to 30 mph in the upper
Mississippi Valley.
   Temperatures warmed into the 80s on Friday afternoon from
south-central Texas to the southern Atlantic Coast states. Readings
soared into the 90s in south-central Texas.
   Corpus Christi, Texas, set a new record high for the date with a
reading of 96, breaking a 94-degree mark set in 1962.
   The cold spot in the Lower 48 states Friday morning was 16
degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
</TEXT>
