<DOCNO> AP891006-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 2113EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0661 10-06 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Votes Down Proposal to Meet Palestinians in Cairo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with U.S. efforts to continue talks, Shamir
speaking of U.S. proposal.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Israel's coalition government cast a
tie vote Friday, in effect a rejection, on an Egyptian plan to hold
Israeli-Palestinian talks in Cairo as a step toward reviving Middle
East peace efforts.
   Some ministers in the Labor Party, which backed Egypt's
proposal, said the left-center party should leave the coalition
with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc. Labor
Party leader Shimon Peres said it will be considered.
   In Washington, U.S. officials said Secretary of State James A.
Baker III was seeking to keep negotiations alive. They said that
after the Israeli Cabinet vote Baker talked by telephone with
Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens and Egyptian Foreign Minister
Esmet Abdel-Meguid.
   Israel's policy-making inner Cabinet of 12 members voted 6-6
along party lines on a Labor motion to accept the proposal by
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt. Egypt is the only Arab country to
sign a peace treaty with Israel. A tie vote amounted to rejection.
   Mubarak's plan was to hold talks about the Israeli proposal that
Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip elect delegates for
negotiations with Israel.
   Likud objects to the Mubarak suggestion that former residents of
the occupied lands be included in the Palestinian delegation to
Cairo talks.
   Shamir told members of the inner Cabinet that acceptance of
exile delegates ``would bring the PLO into the peace process, and
Israel would have entered into the peace process which could lead
to a Palestinian state.''
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin of Labor said of the vote:
``Israel today suffered a severe setback. ... I am very
disappointed.''
   Palestine Liberation Organization representative Nabil Shaath
said in Cairo the rejection brought peace efforts ``back again to
stagnation.''
   Abdel-Meguid was less pessimistic, saying without elaboration
that ``consultations are under way with the United States and
Israel.'' He spoke with reporters in Cairo.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher insisted Israel had
not rejected Mubarak's proposal. ``Our view is that the Israeli
Cabinet has held a full discussion and neither accepted nor
rejected the Egyptian ideas,'' he said in Washington.
   Baker met last week in New York with Arens and Abdel-Meguid. He
urged the Israeli Cabinet to ``move forward'' on the Shamir
proposal and at a news conference Friday he said if the Cabinet did
not, ``We will have to go back to the drawing board.''
   But after the tie vote U.S. officials said there was no reason
to start afresh. Instead Baker intends to keep the discussions
going while seeking an accommodation between the Shamir and Mubarak
approaches, they said.
   Boucher said, ``Any conclusion that it's over because it didn't
happen today is just not right. I don't think the secretary put any
time limit on this.''
   After the Cabinet meeting Shamir said Baker's efforts could
restart the peace process.
   ``There is an American idea, maybe even a proposal for some kind
of a meeting with the Arabs of Judea, Samaria and Gaza in better
circumstances for us,'' Shamir said on Israel televsion, using the
biblical names of Judea and Samaria for the occupied West Bank.
   After the inner Cabinet vote, Police Minister Chaim Bar-Lev of
Labor said he believed time had run out for the 10-month-old
``national unity'' coalition. Labor has threatened previously to
leave the goverment over the peace stalemate.
   Peres told reporters Friday: ``I don't know if I will recommend
leaving the government or other steps, but it's clear that this
requires us to draw conclusions.''
   Mubarak also urged three other steps that Likud opposed and
Labor favored: endorsement of the U.S.-backed concept of trading
land for peace; a freeze on building Jewish settlements in the
occupied territories; and participation in the elections by Arabs
in east Jerusalem, which the government has declared part of Israel.
   The Israeli initiative, which the government endorsed in May,
calls for the election of Palestinians to negotiate an interim
autonomy agreement with Israel. The final status of the occupied
lands would be determined later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
