<DOCNO> AP891006-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 2119EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Spending-Taxes 3rdLd-Writethru a0749 10-06 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending-Taxes, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0749,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Democrats Exchange Offers on Tax Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with agreement neared; SUBS 12th graf, bgng:
``They're putting xxx to edit for second reference to Bentsen; picks up
13th graf pvs, bgng: Bentsen said...; should stand.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House and Senate Democrats neared a
deal Friday to speed work on a deficit-reduction bill by keeping it
free of controversial special-interest provisions, including
President Bush's proposed capital gains tax cut.
   Late in a day of publicly made offers and counteroffers, private
meetings and news conferences, Senate leaders of both parties had
come close to agreeing to a Democratic proposal for a stripped-down
budget bill.
   In exchange, Democrats would agree to guarantee a separate vote
on capital gains in the next few weeks. Republican supporters of a
capital gains tax cut believe they would win such a vote.
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said
Republicans still wanted Democratic leaders in the House, which has
already passed its own version of a capital gains reduction, to
promise to work out a compromise bill with the Senate. A meeting
among House and Senate leaders was scheduled for Saturday.
   ``I think we're pretty close to an agreement,'' Bentsen said.
   Friday morning, Bush traveled to Capitol Hill to discuss the
situation with Senate Republicans.
   ``Capital gains is vital,'' he said before the meeting. ``It's
not an extraneous matter with me.''
   The Senate's majority Democrats, who first offered to pare down
the bill Thursday night, said debate on the measure would begin
with an unusual Saturday session.
   In a late-night session this week, the Senate Finance Committee
approved a package of revenue increases raising $37 billion over
the next five years. The panel then voted to help dozens of
interest groups by granting them $28 billion in tax cuts or other
benefits.
   Democrats argued that stripping down the bill to its $13.8
billion in revenues and spending cuts for next year is the only way
to quickly pass it. Unless the measure is approved by Oct. 16 _
which until now has been considered unlikely _ the Gramm-Rudman
deficit-reduction law will automatically impose across-the-board
cuts on defense and many domestic programs.
   The Democratic proposal positioned them to blame the GOP for
forcing lengthy debate on a needlessly complex bill, thus
triggering the automatic cuts.
   ``They're putting the issue of capital gains ahead of meeting
the targets of Gramm-Rudman and delaying'' the law's spending cuts,
said Bentsen.
   Bentsen said he has offered to drop his own proposal to restore
Individual Retirement Account benefits from the bill if the capital
gains effort is also abandoned.
   Republicans, however, were unwilling to consent to the
Democratic plan unless the Democrats agreed to a Senate vote on
cutting the capital gains rate, which was a major plank in Bush's
election campaign last year.
   ``It's been part of the process from the very beginning,'' said
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater. ``It's already passed the
House, and we believe now is the time to include it in the bill.''
   For their part, Democrats seemed reluctant to promise such a
vote. Both Bentsen and Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, declined to predict whether the Senate would adopt a
capital gains cut if it came to a vote.
   The House approved its own version of the deficit-reduction bill
Thursday on a 333-91 vote, a measure that included a temporary
reduction in capital gains tax rates.
   GOP lawmakers who attended the Capitol meeting with Bush gave
differing accounts afterward of whether Bush would agree to forgo a
vote on capital gains until some other time.
   Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said Bush ``wants capital gains in
this package.'' But Sen. John Chafee, D-R.I., said if Bush was
promised a future vote, ``That's obviously something he'll have to
consider.''
   For procedural reasons, capital gains supporters would
apparently need 60 votes to prevail if the provision is part of the
deficit-reduction bill. Only 51 votes would be necessary if it was
free-standing legislation.
   Capital gains, which are profits from the sale of investments,
now are fully taxed at the same rates as other income. Under the
House-passed bill, the top rate of 33 percent would be cut to 19.6
percent until 1992, when it would be raised to 28 percent and
``indexed'' to avoid taxing gains arising solely from inflation.
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., has proposed a capital gains plan
under which the longer an investment was held, the less of its
profits would be taxed when sold. He wants to substitute his
proposal for the Democratic IRA restoration.
   Packwood's plan, which failed in the Senate Finance Committee on
a 10-10 vote earlier this week, is expected to be the starting
point for whatever plan the Senate considers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
