<FIRST>r a AM-CocaineSeizure 1stLd-Writethru a0753 10-06 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Seizure, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0753,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agents Told Of 60 Tons Cocaine, $80 Million Cash At LA Warehouse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with state charges dropped in Calif. so federal
charges can be brought.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The alleged manager of a Los Angeles warehouse
where raiders seized the largest cocaine haul ever told drug agents
that 60 tons of the drug passed through in the last year alone, a
prosecutor said Friday.
   James McTague also identified the leader of the drug ring as
Rafael Munoz, a Mexican who lives in Juarez, according to an
affidavit filed in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles and unsealed
here.
   The disclosures came during an identity and bail hearing for
Carlos Tapia Ponce and his son, Hector Tapia Anchondo, who
authorities claim ran the U.S. leg of the smuggling operation.
   U.S. Magistrate Lawrence Leavitt, citing a ``serious risk of
flight,'' ordered the Tapias held without bail pending their return
to Los Angeles to face narcotics charges. Leavitt set a preliminary
hearing Wednesday.
   McTague, married to Tapia Anchondo's sister, was identified in
the affidavit as the manager of the warehouse in Sylmar, where
authorities last week found 19 tons of cocaine and $12.2 million in
cash.
   ``He indicated that since he had been in charge they had moved
60 tons of cocaine through the warehouse,'' said Tom Green, an
assistant U.S. Attorney. ``The ledgers showed that $80 million cash
had gone through his hands since he'd been involved.''
   Green said McTague, arrested along with three others in the Los
Angeles raid, told Drug Enforcement Administration agents he was
hired a year ago to run the warehouse. The building was rented by
Tapia Ponce beginning in December 1987 for $1,700 a month.
   He said McTague told agents after his arrest they could find the
Tapias at a Las Vegas hotel, where they were vacationing with
family members.
   ``These two individuals were identified as the operators of the
organization,'' by McTague, Green said.
   An informant alerted authorities to activities at the warehouse
and surveillance began only two days before the raid, DEA special
agent James L. Capra said in the affidavit.
   Authorities initially said they found 20 tons of cocaine
estimated to have a street value of between $2 billion and $20
billion, but Green said Friday that after weighing the drugs the
final figure was about 19 tons.
   The 66-year-old Tapia Ponce, a Mexican national, admitted to
agents when arrested that he was involved in narcotics trafficking
and that he had been paid $5,000 a trip to bring 100 kilos of
cocaine over the border near El Paso several times a week, Green
said.
   Defense attorney David Chesnoff didn't ask bail for Tapia Ponce,
but argued that his son should be granted bail because he was
linked to the drug activity only by McTague's statements. A picture
of Tapia Ponce was found in the warehouse.
   Chesnoff said the 38-year-old Tapia Anchondo, a resident alien,
lives in El Paso with his wife and 2-year-old child and makes his
living on a ranch in Mexico. He described him as a college graduate
working on a masters degree in psychology.
   ``There is no record he's ever been in California or had
proprietary interest in cocaine,'' Chesnoff said.
   But Green described both men as ``the top hierarchy'' of a ring
that transported several thousand pounds of cocaine a week from El
Paso to Los Angeles in semi-trailers, then sold it at 100 to 500
pounds a deal from the warehouse.
   Green said both men probably will be charged with running a
continuing criminal enterprise, and under federal guidelines, face
a minimum of nearly 20 years in prison without possibility of
parole if convicted.
   ``They're virtually facing the rest of their lives in prison and
they have every reason to flee,'' Green said in support of bail
denial.
   In Los Angeles, meanwhile, a prosecutor dismissed drug charges
against McTague and three others to turn the four over to federal
authorities for prosecution.
   They would be jailed under a federal hold order until they could
be arraigned, probably Tuesday, said Grace Denton, a spokeswoman in
the U.S. Attorney's Office.
   Deputy District Attorney Curt Hazell, who dismissed the state
charges, said the maximum punishment under state law is 20 years in
prison, of which offenders usually serve 10. In federal court, the
four, if convicted, would face a maximum of life in prison without
the possibility of parole, he said.
   ``The federal case is as secure and as solid as ours,'' he said.
</TEXT>
