<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolHostages     10-06 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Hostages,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Hostage Suspect Was Troubled Teen Affected by Movie and Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When 15-year-old Anthony Lopez dared his
captor to shoot him, he didn't think he would be taken seriously or
that the gun was real. Moments later he felt pressure in his face.
   ``I chuckled and he shot me right there,'' Lopez said from his
hospital room. ``I heard the fire and saw the sparks. It didn't
hurt.''
   Lopez wasn't the only Loara High School student held hostage
during drama class Thursday who thought the armed student was just
kidding and trying to get attention when he took over the class.
   The armed youth, identified as Cordell ``Cory'' Robb, joked
during the siege, at one point referring to himself as ``the Dirty
Harry with acne'' and offering classmates sips of his Coca-Cola.
   Then they saw Lopez get shot in the face.
   ``When he shot, blood went all over the place _ all over the
tiles and carpet,'' said Diana Rankin, 14. ``Everyone was crying
and screaming.''
   Lopez, 15, was in fair condition Friday, said Fran Tardiff,
spokeswoman at the University of California, Irvine, Medical Center.
   Friends and acquaintances said Robb, 15, was a frequent reader
of Stephen King horror novels and wasn't taken seriously because he
made threats before. He had threatened to commit suicide and take a
class hostage, they said.
   ``He said he was going to hold hostage a drama class second
period,'' said friend Faye Peterson. ``He said there were people in
the class he didn't like. I guess they bugged him.''
   Last month, a 17-year-old high school student in Kentucky held
11 of his classmates hostage in what police said was a plot
directly from King's novel, ``Rage.'' No one was injured during the
daylong standoff.
   Classmates said Robb was also fascinated with the movie
``Heathers,'' in which a troubled teen-ager named J.D. kills the
popular kids at school. The sarcastic antihero dies when he tries
to blow up his school.
   Mike Berault, 14, who described himself as Robb's best friend,
said the youth thought J.D. was ``cool.''
   Robb himself was described as anything but cool, and most
classmates saw him as an outsider.
   ``A lot of kids teased him. They made fun of him and called him
names. I guess they thought he was strange,'' said Miss Peterson.
``People called him psychopath.''
   Friends said Robb was haunted by memories of his father, Ronald
Eugene Robb. The teen said his father committed suicide.
   He also had a strained relationship with his stepfather.
   ``It was a conflict all the time,'' said Carol Sharkey, who
babysat for Robb until he was 14. ``Cory said his dad was real
strict.''
   Hostages said Robb asked a police negotiator to bring his
stepfather to the school auditorium.
   Officer Steve Stempniak was the negotiator who calmly talked the
boy into giving up. ``When I was putting the cuffs on him, I guess
it finally hit me just what could have happened,'' the 11-year
police veteran said.
   Robb was being held Friday in a juvenile facility awaiting
charges.
   Nina Sartore, 16, said she has known Robb since grammar school
and wasn't really surprised when she heard what happened.
   ``Truthfully, he's got a lot of problems. I kind of expected
something like this ... for him to flip out.'' she said. ``I tried
to help him. He didn't want the help.''
</TEXT>
