<HEAD>Koch Named Visiting Lecturer at NYU</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch will become a visiting
fellow at New York University's Urban Research Center after he
leaves office in January, the university announced Friday.
   Koch will give six lectures on the economic and social
challenges facing cities and the roles of state and federal
governments in urban policy, the university said.
   He also will meet informally with students and faculty.
   The appointment was announced by N.Y.U. President John Brademas
and L. Jay Oliva, the university's chancellor and executive vice
president for academic affairs.
   ``With 25 years experience in public service as a New York City
councilman, United States congressman and as mayor, Mr. Koch is
uniquely qualified to address the challenges facing the nation's
metropolitan centers,'' Brademas said.
   Koch said he would fit right in as a visiting fellow because he
thought of himself as a ``pretty good teacher,'' and urban affairs
``is an area I am familiar with.''
   Koch, a three-term mayor, lost the Democratic primary last month
to Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins, who faces Republican
challenger Rudolph Giuliani in November.
