<HEAD>Commission Raps Chairman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-7: ``The coalition,'' with information on location.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Commission on Civil Rights on Friday
branded the title of a speech planned by its chairman as
``thoughtless, disgusting and unnecessarily inflammatory''
   The chairman, William B. Allen, planned to give the speech on
Saturday at a symposium ``Homosexuality and Public Policy
Implications'' sponsored by the California Coalition for
Traditional Values.
   The commission said in a statement its members had not seeen the
speech and did not know what Allen planned to say, but ``based on
the commissioners' understanding that the chairman entitled his
speech, `Blacks, Animals and Homosexuals: What is a Minority,' the
commissioners distance themselves from the speech's title as
thoughtless, disgusting and unnecessarily inflammatory.''
   The statement said the members ``distance themselves from the
chairman's participation in the symposium because the commission
does not possess jurisdiction to discuss issues involving
homosexuality, except in the context of the administration of
justice. Accordingly, the commission has no position on the issue.''
   The statement was approved by a 6-1 vote, with Allen the
dissenter. Blandina Cardenas Ramirez did not take part, the
commission said.
   The coalition opposes extension of civil rights protection to
homosexuals, and believes homosexuality is learned behavior that
can be changed. The session at which Allen is to speak is entitled
``Homosexuality and Public Policy Implications.''
   The first day's sessions of the symposium were held Friday at a
hotel in Anaheim, Calif. Allen's plans to speak there attracted
criticism from homosexual groups earlier this week.
   In an interview with The Washington Post published Wednesday.
Allen said: ``It's always appropriate to talk about civil rights
and to help people understand the promise of this nation. I can't
imagine why there would be any question about it.''
   There was no answer at a telephone listed in his name Friday
evening in Claremont, Calif., where he is a professor at Harvey
Mudd College.
