<HEAD>Trooper Convicted of Raping Motorist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALLSTON SPA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state trooper was convicted Thursday
of rape and sodomy in an attack on a motorist he pulled over for a
traffic ticket.
   Robert O. Bennett Jr., a state police officer for eight years,
was found guilty of rape, two counts of sodomy, sexual abuse,
first-degree coercion, unlawful imprisonment and official
misconduct.
   Bennett, 36, who is from Halfmoon, was charged with attacking
the woman after he pulled her over on Interstate 87 in upstate New
York.
   The woman testified last week that Bennett stopped her on Sept.
10, 1988, for an improper lane change and erratic driving and later
took her to a wooded area and raped her.
   The woman said she kept the attack secret until days later when
she called a Rape Crisis hotline in her hometown of Ithaca.
   Bennett was arrested and suspended in January after the woman
identified him from his name tag and the photographs of his cruiser.
   During his closing statement, Assistant District Attorney Thomas
McNamara said the victim, a 29-year-old college professor,
``entered a `Twilight Zone' of fear and trauma and intimidation''
at the hands of Bennett.
   Stephen Coffey, Bennett's attorney, said he would seek to have
Bennett released on bail pending an appeal.
   Judge Frank Williams scheduled sentencing for Dec. 4. Bennett
faces 8 1-3 to 25 years imprisonment.
