<FIRST>r a AM-Christo'sUmbrellas     10-06 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Christo's Umbrellas,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artist Gets Needed Permits for California Umbrellas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The artist Christo's plan to erect 1,700
giant yellow umbrellas in the hills of Southern California is on
schedule, with all the needed permits obtained, a spokesman said
Thursday.
   The outdoor artwork Christo proposes to erect near the mountain
community of Gorman, about 60 miles north of Los Angeles, is half
of a trans-Pacific project envisioned by the 54-year-old Bulgarian
artist.
   ``Everything is still on line, the schedule date is there,''
said Thomas M. Golden, U.S. project director for the undertaking
Christo has described as ``a symphony in two parts.''
   Christo creates transitory landscapes of unexpected colors and
materials to achieve what he calls ``a gentle disturbance'' of the
mind.
   He previously has wrapped the oldest bridge in Paris in
champagne-colored fabric, surrounded 11 islands in Florida's
Biscayne Bay with shocking pink polypropylene and erected a
transluscent ``Running Fence'' across Northern California.
   The two movements of Christo's umbrella symphony are to begin
simultaneously in October 1991 in California and Japan _ places
Christo selected for their geographical and cultural contrasts.
   As autumn burns the rumpled hills of Southern California to
golden hues, some 1,700 yellow umbrellas _ each 28 feet in diameter
_ will blossom like California poppies along the Tejon Pass.
   At the same time, about 1,300 identical blue umbrellas will open
in the lush bamboo forest, rice paddies, crowded villages and farms
of Japan's Ibaraki province, about 70 miles north of Tokyo.
   In both countries, the umbrellas will stay up only for about
three weeks.
   Although all the permits for the California project have been
gathered, many details remain to be worked out with the Japanese,
Golden said in a telephone interview from his office in Freestone,
Calif.
   ``We keep going back so they know you are sincere in pursuing
this,'' Golden said. ``It's entirely different. They don't have
public hearings and they don't have agencies that issue
encroachment permits, for example.''
   In Japan, there are about 435 landowners, and Golden said in at
least one instance the umbrella's 28-foot diameter is wider than
the parcel of land where it will be erected.
   In contrast, Christo has obtained permission to erect his
umbrellas from a total of 23 landowners in California, including
two governmental agencies, Golden said.
   The California Highway Patrol expects a bit more than gentle
disturbance from the project.
   ``I can imagine freeway commuter traffic, almost
bumper-to-bumper on weekends,'' said Capt. Patrick Harrington, head
of the California Highway Patrol's legislative unit in Sacramento.
   ``I told that to Christo at one of our meetings, and and he was
quite taken aback, and he said, `No! Not really?' ... But I just
know it's going to be really heavy traffic.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891006-0203 </DOCNO>
