<SECOND>PM-Religion Rdp, Adv 06,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, Oct. 6, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten farm and church organizations have joined
together to help educate Americans about the importance of farm and
trade policy to the Third World.
   ``We all need to make these vital connections between our food,
farmers and trade policy,'' says program chairman Walter Grazer of
the U.S. Catholic Conference. ``Education of our citizens is
critical, so they can make informed decisions and join in the
policy process.''
   The non-profit, Washington-based Trade and Development Program
is funded by a grant from the W.K. Kellogg Foundation.
   The goals of the program include ``maintaining U.S. family
farmers and vital rural communities,'' which organizers said are
important resources throughout the world.
   The sponsors are: Bread for the World Institute on Hunger and
Development, the Center for Rural Affairs, the Evangelical Lutheran
Church in America, the Friends Committee on National Legislation
Educational Fund, the National Catholic Rural Life Conference, the
National Farmers Organization, the National Farmers Union, the
National Grange, the Presbyterian Church (USA) and the U.S.
Catholic Conference.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint commission of Lutheran and Roman
Catholic theologians will focus on Scripture and tradition in the
next round of ecumenical dialogues.
   The teams of 10 Catholic and 10 Lutheran theologians decided on
the next topic while wrapping up six years of work on ``The One
Mediator, the Saints and Mary.''
   The eighth statement of the dialogue, scheduled to be voted on
in February, deals with the two traditions' differences regarding
the practice of involving saints in prayer and the doctrine that
Mary was conceived free of original sin and taken bodily to heaven.
   Catholic Archbishop Francis Stafford of Denver, co-chairman of
the dialogue, said the new topic is ``a natural development from
this round, in which there are many explicit references to the
relation between Scripture and tradition.''
   The ecumenical commission will celebrate the 25th anniversary of
the dialogues next September in Erlanger, Ky.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal tax collector praised high ethical
standards set by the Evangelical Council for Financial
Accountability but warned that violations by some fund-raisers may
prompt legislation affecting all charities.
   ``Know the rules, educate your donors, make necessary changes in
your practices, and view the requirements as an ethical
obligation,'' Robert I. Brauer, an assistant commissioner of the
Internal Revenue Service, told a recent conference marking the
council's 10th anniversary. ``Don't force us at the IRS to have to
report to Congress that there is a problem and remedial legislation
may be needed.''
   Brauer said the IRS is scrutinizing tour activities designed to
benefit profit-making travel companies and promoters.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Methodist policy makers may be
slightly more liberal than the average clergy and the lay members
in the nation's second largest Protestant denomination, according
to a new study.
   United Methodist leaders were defined as ministers and
laypersons who were elected as delegates to the United Methodist
General Conference in 1988. The General Conference, which meets
every four years, has final authority in all matters in the 9
million-member denomination.
   On a scale of one to five, with one being the most liberal and
five the most conservative, the average clergy delegate rated
himself 2.7 on social issues, while the lay delegates rated
themselves at about 3. The clergy at large had a 3 rating, while
the laity at large was rated at 3.3.
   A total of 616 clergy and lay delegates to the General
Conference responded to the mail poll. In the same period, 6,048
randomly selected clergy who were not delegates responded to a
similar mail poll, and 526 randomly selected lay people answered
telephone interviews.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, Oct. 6</NOTE>
