<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1125EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Kravitz Adv11   10-06 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Kravitz, Adv 11,0854</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, Oct 11 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lenny Kravitz Is Not Mr. Bonet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Name-dropping is a favorite pastime in the
entertainment business, and musician Lenny Kravitz has a few at his
disposal.
   There's his wife, actress Lisa Bonet of NBC's ``A Different
World''; his mother, Roxie Roker, who pla in the
long-running TV sit-com ``The Jeffersons''; and his father, Sy
Kravitz, a former NBC executive.
   But the younger Kravitz, who also goes by the name Romeo Blue,
prefers discussing a few well-placed strangers, such as John
Lenyed Helen Willisnon, Jimi Hendrix, Bob Marley and Lou Reed, all influences
for
his debut album, ``Let Love Rule.''
   ``I'm not hip on the way records sound today,'' the 25-year-old
Kravitz said, ``all this digital and sampling everywhere.
   ``My record sounds like the kind you just drop a needle on and
play. I grew up on records that sound like this. I don't think
records sound any better than in the late '50s or early '60s.''
   He makes his point on the record's opening track, ``Sitting on
Top of the World,'' proudly performed a little off-key, his voice
cracking early in the song.
   ``I dreamed the whole song,'' he said, ``and I hummed it into
the tape recorder. I did that one live, in one take, with just
guitar and mike.until now, I think
I turned down about eight record deals.'' he said. ``They wanted
trendy black music, which I hate. `This is too white. You have to
get your black base first, then you can cross over. Everybody has
to. Go get yourself a drum machine and make yourself a funk record.'
   ``That was a big issue. But what I'm doing is black music
anyway, rhythm and blues, rock 'n' roll. People think if you don't
sound like Bobby Brown, it's not black music.''
   He spent time in the studio, recording songs meant for his ears
only, when a friend heard a tape and passed the word around that a
promising new star was waiting to be discovered. After meeting and
falling in love with Bonet, Kravitz was an even hotter property.
   ``Being that I was married to her, people were interested in
what I was doing. I was on the cover of all these magazines, just
because I was married to her. `Who is this guy?'''
   Bonet not only brought him much-needed publicity, but helped
Kravitz find himself as a musician.
   ``When I first met Lisa, I was a studio musician, but I still
didn't know what to do, because I played funk, rock, jazz, whatever
and could play all sorts of instruments,'' said Kravitz, who plays
all the instruments on ``Let Love Rule.''
   ``We're so similar. I saw myself in her, a reflection of myself.
All of a sudden I knew what I had to. After she was finished with
her show, I started writing and cutting. I came to New York and
booked myself in a studio. My writing come back and I started
building up these tunes.''
   Kravitz's nasal vocals on ``Let Love Rule'' and ``Be'' recall
Lennon and Elvis Costello, and ``Mr. Cab Driver,'' an angry talking
blues, has the man-on-the-street feel of Reed's best known songs.
   ``I got `The Best of Lou Reed.' and `Walk on the Wild Side' just
blew my mind. I fell in love with that Lower East Side, New York
sound, getting that message over. But I don't think about doing a
Lou Reed-sounding record, certain sounds just come out of me.''
   He vows to include other musicians on his next record and is
touring with a 10-piece band. Kravitz hopes to win over fans who
know him only for the names he can drop.
   ``What if I came out to see you because your wife is so-and-so?
If that's what brings people out, fine,'' he said. ``But I've got
something to say, I'm not interested in being Mr. Bonet.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Wed Oct. 11</NOTE>
