<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1453EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv09   10-06 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 09,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Monday, Oct. 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>Firm Seeks Control of Personal Computer's Life-Cycle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imagine one company owning a rental car
business, a fleet of taxis, a chain of used car dealerships and an
auto parts company. The firms all supply each other, working
together to control a car's life cycle.
   That is what the ambitious Dan Bayha, 45-year-old president of
BATA Group in Morristown, N.J., wants to do in the world of
microcomputers.
   BATA controls a group of subsidiaries that concentrate on a
computer's afterlife:
   PSX Inc. buys from retail chains computers that have been traded
in, and refurbishes them for resale, mostly to rental companies.
For units too outdated or damaged, PSX scavenges parts.
   Personal Computer Rentals, in which BATA acquired a controlling
interest in May, is a rental franchise with 43 stores nationwide.
The franchise group is PSX's largest customer.
   BATA Capital finances equipment leased by corporations directly,
or provided via lease by Personal Computer Rentals.
   BATA is focusing its attention on what Bayha and others in the
industry see as a new growth front in the personal computer world:
rentals. Bayha said he hopes to more than double Personal Computer
Rentals' stores in two years.
   BATA, a name formed by Bayha and the last name of his partner,
Steve Tafaro, started 10 years ago as an IBM mainframe leasing
firm. A change in the tax laws in 1986 made it less advantageous
for companies to lease mainframes, Bayha said, so the firm turned
to microcomputers 2{ years ago.
   Each step of the business took them further. It was natural to
look at maintaining microcomputers as a leasing company, which led
to the idea of refurbishing and selling them used. They found that
rental firms were buying many of the retooled computers, so BATA
bought a controlling interest in Personal Computer Rentals.
   ``We kept bumping into things and said, `Gee, look at that,'''
Bayha said.
   With revenues of $15 million in 1988, not including the leasing
and rental business, BATA Group has not turned a profit, but that
should change this year, he said.
   ``It's not going to be unreasonable to believe that every home
will have two or three microcomputers just as they have two to
three televisions,'' he said.
   The personal computer market next year is expected to approach
$40 billion, with up to 15 million computers sold, said analyst Kim
Brown, at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. Hundreds of small
companies either broker or rent computers.
   Brown was skeptical about the chances that a company like BATA
could make it.
   Computer technology advances so quickly, and prices drop so
dramatically that purchasers may prefer to keep on buying new
equipment, said Brown.
   For instance, an IBM PC with a color screen and 640 kilobytes of
memory cost from $4,000 to $5,000 when introduced in 1982, and is
now worth in the $200 range. IBM and Apple are expected to
introduce low-end PCs for under $1,000 within a year, he said.
   The costs of refurbishment and handling might also make the
endeavor less profitable, said Brown. ``I'm not saying it can't be
done,'' he added.
   ``There's an awful lot of companies out there that don't have to
have the latest technology,'' countered Bayha. Potential users in
homes, small businesses and lower education don't necessarily need
``high horsepower'' computers, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday PMs, Oct. 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891006-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1416EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:RussianMusical Adv09   10-06 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Russian Musical, Adv 09,0848</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Oct. 9, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pierre Cardin and Russian Rock</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Pierre Cardin brings the first Russian rock
musical to New York in January, he expects sparks to fly.
   ``Sparks of love, that is,'' says the French
couturier-entrepreneur-theater producer.
   Cardin feels like something between Cupid and a diplomat for
having arranged a month-long engagement of the rock show ``Juno and
Avos'' at New York's City Center.
   In an interview at Maxim's, the Belle Epoque gastronomic
monument Cardin bought nine years ago, he bubbled like champagne
over his plans.
   ``Avos roughly means `a kind of hope,''' he said. And hope is
what he exudes for his ``mission'' to put on the unique musical
love story for the Americans.
   Cardin first brought the play to his Espace Cardin theater in
Paris in 1983. It might not be another ``Les Miserables,'' but the
French loved it. And the romantic scenario is particularly fitting
for today's burgeoning Soviet-American flirtation.
   The rock opera was written in 1980 by dissident Soviet poet
Andrei Vosnesensky. It is based on the true tale of a Russian sea
captain's love affair with the daughter of the Spanish governor of
San Francisco, circa 1800. It has a kind of Romeo-Juliet twist: The
couple can't marry because of religious differences; she is Roman
Catholic, he is Orthodox.
   ``It was kind of an allegorical cry for more mutual U.S.-Soviet
understanding,'' said Cardin, who is a good friend of the poet.
``Fortunately, things are going just that way.''
   Despite Vosnesensky's fears, Cardin insisted he could succeed in
getting the rock opera to Paris and even the United States. Thanks
to glasnost _ the new Soviet policy of openness _ and pulling some
strings with officials in both countries, he's making his dream
come true.
   ``Problems were not really political or cultural,'' Cardin said.
   ``The American unions are very sticky about all-foreign
productions. But I did it. The whole Russian cast and crew of 86
will be there. This is a great moment. Americans have seen Russian
ballet, folklore and the circus. But they've never seen anything
like this.''
   Long a fan of the Russian people and culture, Cardin has
manufactured and sold ready-to-wear clothing at luxury shops there
since 1986. He first heard about Vosnesensky's musical during an
earlier business visit.
   ``But it was only playing in repertory, and not the night I was
there. So they took the entire company out to a provincial town and
put it on for me and the townspeople.''
   He decided nothing would get in the way of his producing the
show at his Paris theater, known since it opened in 1970 for
everything from ballets starring Maia Plissetskaya to the American
avant-garde group Pilobus.
   Red tape of getting the big show to Paris was a mere trifle
compared to his worst moment _ opening night.
   ``Just as my show was opening in November 1983, the Soviets blew
up that KAL civilian plane over Kamchatka,'' Cardin said, and the
show itself almost bombed. ``Everyone told me I was out of my mind.
In fact, the first night the theater was almost empty. After all,
it wasn't the artists' fault. I went ahead.''
   Finally, the show was a hit, even though the new rock sound,
synthesizers and all, was astonishing for an old-fashioned love
story. Critics were flabbergasted to see the Virgin of Kazan _ a
prime chorus figure played by a bearded counter-tenor _ changing
his voice from baritone to the seraphic notes of the virgin.
   Difficulties have never bothered Cardin, who regularly flies
around the world to visit his factories and sell his goods, whether
couture, underwear or Maxim's champagne.
   ``My whole career is based on the impossible,'' he said. ``My
ready-to-wear wouldn't work, they told me more than 30 years ago.
Then all the other couturiers started copying that idea. I was told
I was quite mad to start factories in Russia and China.'' But they
flourished.
   ``Critics made the same comments about taking Maxim's all over
the world,'' he said. The Peking Maxim's was a big hit from the
time it opened six years ago, though it had to close after the
Tiananmen Square events last summer. It will open again within
weeks.
   Russophile Cardin will see his newest Maxim's open in the Soviet
Union next year, in spite of a few headaches.
   Meanwhile, Cardin is off to some of his worldwide enterprises in
China and Australia, ending up in New York on Friday to promote the
Russian musical, a production that's intially costing him ``the
eyes right out of my head,'' as the French expression goes.
   ``But money is never any concern of mine,'' he said. ``I just
want to see more mutual Russian-American understanding. It's
already miraculous, and I don't think Americans know enough about
the Russians. I think this should help.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Oct. 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891006-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1535EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Manny's Adv12   10-06 0918</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Manny's, Adv 12,0938</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Oct. 12, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Holly, Hendrix, Harrison: The Customers at Manny's</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henry Goldrich is the guy who told Harry Chapin
that ``Taxi'' ran too long to be a hit. He's also the guy who
kicked George Benson out of his store because of that annoying
guitar.
   ``Back in the '60s, I told Paul (Simon) that Simon and Garfunkel
was a lousy name. And I still think it is,'' says Goldrich.
   Fortunately, musicians want instruments and not advice from
Goldrich _ which is why his music store, Manny's on West 48th
Street, has served everyone from Dizzy Gillespie to Guns N' Roses
in the past five decades.
   The Beatles invaded Manny's before they did the rest of country;
these days, Sean Lennon buys his guitars there. Mick Jagger was
looking for the right ax for this year's Stones' tour when he ran
into Bo Diddley. David Johansen has been a customer since he was a
New York Doll; he visits now as Buster Poindexter.
   ``The Who _ when they were in town, doing the show _ they were
in here. Except Daltrey. He bought a guitar once and never played
it,'' says Goldrich, dropping names as fast as Clapton works a fret
board. ``They came to my son's bar mitzvah; flew over. They're
friends.''
   Goldrich, a gray-haired, bearded man with a slight pot belly, is
the son of the original Manny and current keeper of the family
business. His dad established the store in Harlem 54 years ago, and
they became a 48th Street fixture in the late 1940s. The musicians
followed and never left.
   ``It's word of mouth. We have a very long and great
reputation,'' says Goldrich, whose earliest recollections of the
store involve a nodding John Coltrane asleep on an upstairs couch.
   Manny's customer list reads like a history of American music:
Charlie Parker in the '40s; Buddy Holly in the '50s; Jimi Hendrix
in the '60s; Paul Simon in the '70s; David Byrne in the '80s. Most
have provided autographed pictures, an invaluable collection that
covers the walls of the stores.
   ``Elvis Presley is the only big rock star who never walked in
the store. ... We delivered stuff to his hotel,'' says Goldrich.
   Manny's and Rudy's Music Stop across the street still cater to
the big names, but most of their old neighbors are gone. There were
once 25 music stores along the strip that comprised the Big Apple's
bandstand. Today, a half-dozen remain, the rest replaced by the
westward creep of Rockefeller Center and the eastern move of
grocery stores and fast-food joints.
   Such intrusions don't mean the area has lost its magnetism for
musicians, who still pass through midtown construction and the
surrounding porno shops to check out what's what.
   ``Go to West 48th Street to look at all the guitars and amps. Go
to Manny's and Rudy's. Look at all the great new equipment. That's
my idea of a good time,'' Lou Reed told Rolling Stone. Most
musicians heed his advice.
   Guns N' Roses featured the store in their video for ``Paradise
City.'' Soviet rock star Boris Grebenshikov hit the 48th Street
shops shortly after arriving in the United States to examine the
merger of music and capitalism. And then there's the time Mark
Knopfler turned a salesman into a sideman at Rudy's Music Stop.
   Part-time Rudy's worker Jack Sonni met Knopfler through the
shop, which the Dire Straits leader began frequenting in 1979. Five
years later, Sonni signed on with Dire Straits for the ``Brothers
in Arms'' LP after getting a surprise invite from Knopfler.
   At least Sonni knew who Knopfler was. When Guns N' Roses
guitarists Izzy Stradlin and Slash showed up at Manny's, Goldrich
didn't have a clue as to their identities.
   ``The music now is very heavy metal, which is not my favorite.
You can't whistle it,'' said Goldrich _ Itzhak Perlman is his kind
of musician. ``But the kids _ they're probably just as nice.''
   When Goldrich started in the business, the musicians were as
hard up for cash as the struggling Manny. A day's receipts could
total $18; many of the musicians bought on credit and took a long
time to pay, he says.
   ``Charlie Parker used to come in and play tenor sax, and
Gillespie played piano, and we used to have the greatest jam
sessions in the world,'' Goldrich recalled. ``Coltrane (tenor and
soprano saxophone) was there. Coltrane _ there's guy that owed me a
lot of money.''
   Goldrich is understandably proud of the autographed pictures
that line his store. On a small portion of one wall, The Who, the
Rolling Stones, Janis Joplin, Hendrix, Buddy Holly and Bob Dylan
sit side by side.
   ``Keep one eye closed at all cost,'' advised Dylan on his
picture.
   Goldrich himself is a one-man rock 'n' roll repository. He sold
guitars for Hendrix's and Holly's families after their deaths. His
friends include Ella Fitzgerald, John Entwistle and James Taylor.
   And he has a bit of advice _ good advice, for once _ for anybody
hoping to open a place on 48th Street.
   ``When somebody walks in the store that's famous, I think they
get worse treatment than the standard customer,'' said Goldrich.
``We're not on them constantly. ... They come in here, they wander
through the store. I don't go in awe of these guys.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday AMs, Oct. 12</NOTE>
