<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1516EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Guatemala-Violence Adv15-2Takes   10-06 0805</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Guatemala-Violence, Adv 15-2 Takes,0827</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Wave of Violence Sweeps Guatemala</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new wave of violence, recalling the
worst of the brutal days of military rule, is sweeping across this
Central American nation.
   A rash of assassinations, kidnappings and bombings has eroded
the fragile hopes that a working democracy can take firm root.
   Shadowy organizations like the White Hand and Jaguar Justice are
on the prowl again. Grenades are tossed. Anonymous voices hiss
death threats into telephones. Student leaders, peasants, labor
leaders vanish or flee the country. A leading banker is gunned down
in his home.
   President Vinicio Cerezo has survived two coup attempts, but
people speak of a democracy defrauded and some claim Cerezo is
unwilling to do anything about it.
   ``Ambition, corruption and immorality in so many hearts have
bred monstrous personalities,'' Guatemala's Roman Catholic bishops
said in an anguished message about the wave of violence.
   The kidnappings, murders, tortures and bombings of recent weeks
stem from a lethal mix.
   Some of the killing is blamed on a 28-year-old leftist guerrilla
insurgency and the brutal effort to suppress it. Some is blamed on
right-wing extremists trying to destabilize the government, some on
elements of the state security apparatus. And then there is the
influx of drug traffickers.
   ``Is there any hope for Guatemala?'' asked Peter Kooijmans, a
special envoy from the U.N. Human Rights Commission drawn here by
the deteriorating situation. He does not have the answer.
   For an expert on torture like Kooijmans, this Ohio-sized country
of almost 9 million people is fertile ground. Bodies commonly turn
up with their hands chopped off or partly flayed or bearing signs
of electric shock.
   Neither violence nor political uncertainty is new to Guatemala.
What makes the current crisis so disturbing is that it represents
the crumbling of hopes _ again.
   ``The expectations of the 1985 elections have vanished in a
matter of months,'' said labor leader Sergio Guzman.
   Guatemala's previous experience with democracy ended in 1954
with a CIA-backed coup against President Jacobo Arbenz, a
reformist. An estimated 100,000 people died and 40,000 disappeared
in the three decades of political violence that followed under
military rule.
   Those deaths included thousands of victims of a brutal
counterinsurgency campaign that Defense Minister Hector Gramajo
once said ``used the techniques of an occupation army in our own
country.''
   Hundreds of Indian villages in rebel territory were wiped out.
The labor movement was driven underground. Labor leader Guzman
recalls unionists meeting secretly in churches and convents during
the early 1980s.
   Many Guatemalans saw the return of civilian government in 1986,
with Cerezo at the head, as the beginning of the end of a long,
bloody nightmare, but the optimism of those first years is dying.
   ``The most regressive forces in our country are trying to
neutralize the most progressive,'' said Edgar Agusto Portillo
Recinos, dean of the economics faculty at the University of San
Carlos.
   The current violence began heating up with a teachers' strike
over wages that began in May and lasted until August. There also
was a coup attempt in May. In July, when Cerezo tried to deliver a
nationwide address, a television station was blown off the air.
   On Aug. 21, armed men with walkie talkies began whisking student
leaders off the streets of Guatemala City in broad daylight.
   Four bodies bearing signs of torture turned up near the
University of San Carlos on Sept. 10. A fifth was found a week
later in a ravine used as a body dump during the dark days of
military rule. Five students are still missing.
   The Central American Report, independently published by
Inforpress Centroamericana and distrubuted to embassies,
businesses, educational institutions and other private groups,
lists 77 political killings since mid-August, but nobody knows how
bad it really is in the countryside.
   Maria Rumalda Camey was one case. She was the wife of a peasant
farmer and a member of a humans rights support group. Near the end
of August men came in the night and dragged her from her home.
   Her family _ seven children and three adults _ hid out with the
Red Cross for six weeks before making a terrified dash across a
rain-slicked sidewalk to a waiting Spanish Embassy van and
political asylum.
   Her husband, Jose, spent his last night in Guatemala hanging
tattered laundry and trying to patch together battered suitcases.
He tried to fight off despair as he faced raising two babies alone
in a strange land.
   ``I'll be afraid, but I would be afraid here,'' he said.
``Guatemala is returning to the bloody times.''
   Diplomats, political analysts and human rights activists all say
the student disappearances seem to be the product of a military
operation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
