<DOCNO> AP891006-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1517EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Guatemala-Violence Adv15-1stAdd   10-06 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Guatemala-Violence, Adv 15-1st Add,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>GUATEMALA CITY: military operation.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   One diplomat in close contact with the Guatemalan military said
the brazenness and the technical proficiency _ the weapons,
vehicles and communications equipment _ as well as the careful
targeting of victims are earmarks of a security forces operation.
   The students may have been suspected of links to leftist
guerrillas; several were involved in the teacher's strike. To many
conservatives here, association with a union movement is enough to
brand someone as an extreme leftist.
   Peasant and labor leaders and human rights activists also have
suffered in the backlash to a surge in political activity since
1986.
   Cerezo and his Christian Democrats blame a rightist campaign to
destabilize the government. But the government also is seen by some
as ineffective and incompetent, paralyzed by fear of rightist
violence.
   Mario Sandoval Alarcon, a former vice president and leader of
the right-wing National Liberation Movement, said Guatemalans will
be ready to vote for a law-and-order president, perhaps even a
military candidate, in November 1990.
   Gen. Efrain Rios Montt, who presided over some of Guatemala's
worst savagery in the early 1980s, when reported deaths and
disappearances ran as high as 500 a month, has already announced
his availability.
   The newest threat to Guatemalan peace and democracy appears to
be drug trafficking.
   On Aug. 24 four men broke into the home of banker Ramiro
Castillo Love and shot him to death.
   ``He refused to launder drug money,'' said Sandoval, a friend of
Castillo's. Sandoval's assessment was shared by several diplomatic
sources and political analysts.
   ``There is no doubt that it was an execution designed to put the
fear of god into the banking community,'' one diplomat said.
   The death Aug. 1 of Danilo Barillas, a Christian Democrat, is
also said to be linked to the drug trade. Barillas headed a
commission looking into corruption inside his party and is widely
believed to have found links to Colombian cocaine cartels.
   Many on the right believe the drug traffickers and the
guerrillas, reduced to perhaps fewer than 2,000 fighters, have
formed an unholy alliance.
   While there is no hard evidence of that, the guerrilla war has
taken a higher profile. The guerrillas have begun staging
attention-getting attacks close to urban areas.
   Diplomatic pressure is on Cerezo to rein things in, but so far
he has done nothing.
   The Central America Report and diplomats say the U.N. Human
Rights Commission is considering returning Guatemala to a list of
persistent human rights violators _ a list it left in 1987.
   A U.S. State Department travel-advisory warning of
``indiscriminate terrorist attacks,'' crime and clashes between the
army and guerrillas will probably cut into tourism.
   All U.S. aid was suspended in 1977 because of human rights
violations. Economic aid resumed early in the Reagan administration
and military aid in 1985.
   For 1989, non-military aid amounts to $153 million and military
aid to $9.5 million. The army has also bought 20,000 M-16 rifles
for $13.8 million _ $200,000 below a limit that would have required
U.S. congressional approval.
   Human rights advocate Nineth de Garcia believes Cerezo is doing
nothing because behind-the-scene negotiations after the coup
attempts gave the security forces a free hand.
   ``He has negotiated with the blood of the people,'' she charged.
   When Cerezo took office he said he would consider himself a
success if he handed over power to another elected president. In
today's Guatemala, that may well turn out to be his major
accomplishment.
   ``His government will survive,'' Portillo Recinos predicted
bitterly. ``But the country is being destroyed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 15</NOTE>
