<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-BeachErosion Adv08-1stLd-Writethru b0741 10-06 1308</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Beach Erosion, Adv 08-1st Ld-Writethru, b0741,1345</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Castles in the Sand: Beach Erosion Pits Private Wishes Against Public
Good</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS 23rd graf, South Carolina had ... dead zone., to show
South Carolina is appealing court decision on beachfront land.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Houses, condos and hotels sit like castles in the sand, a
developer's vision realized next to the waves of the Atlantic and
the Gulf of Mexico.
   But environmentalists see them as interlopers on the shifting
dunes, vulnerable to destructive storms such as Hurricane Hugo.
   ``There's foolishness in building in God's sandbox unreasonably
close to the ocean,'' said Dana Beach of the South Carolina Coastal
Conservation League. ``We have to make sure we're not building or
rebuilding on places that may not be there after the next storm.''
   While Hugo's roar and 135 mph punch have hit and run, a
philosophical squall still blows, pitting private property rights
against the public good.
   Sounding a charge to grow, developers argue people have a right
to build and protect their investment.
   Urging a strategic retreat, environmentalists counter that
overdevelopment is risky and can deny public access to eroding
beaches.
   States from New England to Florida and around to Texas have laws
attempting to preserve the oceanfront. In South Carolina, a 1988
law may prevent the rebuilding of an estimated 213 oceanfront
houses that were at least two-thirds destroyed by Hugo.
   The law prohibits building in a so-called ``dead zone'' 20 feet
behind an established dune line. Owners of damaged homes who don't
have enough property to move inland out of the zone may be out of
luck.
   ``Nature just delivered a very clear and enuciated message. We
have been setting ourselves up for a disaster the way we have
developed the shoreline,'' said Orrin Pilkey, a Duke University
geologist and an expert on coastal dynamics. ``If Hugo doesn't
prove that something has to be done, nothing will ever do it.''
   Barrier islands, beaches and dunes are natural lines of defense
that protect the mainlaind. They surrender sand to absorb the
energy of storm waves, then are replenished gradually.
   The problem comes if structures are built on the shifting
shores. Pilkey and others believe that barriers built to protect
buildings actually accelerate erosion.
   What Pilkey and his advocates want is to pull back to give
nature a buffer in which to work, even if it means letting homes
fall into the ocean.
   ``Hugo was a warning shot for the entire U.S. East Coast,'' said
Rob Thieler, a research assistant to Pilkey at Duke. ``We know how
to back up, but are we willing to start knocking down buildings in
New Jersey because Hugo hit in South Carolina?''
   That's an easy question for many developers and coastal
officials.
   Beaches are money machines that lure sun worshippers and tourist
dollars. Realtors and investors have capitalized on the nation's
love affair with the shore by making it attractive to visit.
   ``America is not going to abandon it's coast. People are going
to live at the beach,'' said Richard Beck, former mayor of the
barrier island community of Folly Beach off Charleston.
``Abandonment is a cruel joke. I defy anyone to show me where
abandoning property has brought back the beach.''
   Added John Singleton, an investor in heavily developed Myrtle
Beach, ``You can't expect a man who has a multimillion-dollar hotel
to walk away from it.''
   Another punch faces storm-battered South Carolina. The highest
tides in nine years are forecast for Oct. 16. A $65 million
emergency effort aims to rebuild the dunes to prevent flooding.
   ``It would be like pouring salt into a wound if the tides come
in without any protective barrier,'' said Tucker Eskew, spokesman
for Gov. Carroll Campbell.
   Meanwhile, to protect property from erosion, some beaches have
been armored with seawalls and bulkheads. But these intrusions can
deny public access to the shore, and critics object to spending
public money to protect the ocean views of private landowners.
   Others note that more than just property is at stake in the
debate. Future hurricanes could kill more people if they hit
overdeveloped spots.
   ``Our concern is about the potential loss of life,'' said Robert
Sheets, director of the National Hurricane Center. ``We need to
restrict the type of development we're seeing.''
   South Carolina had eight lawsuits filed before Hugo. In one
case, it was ordered to pay $1.2 million to a landowner unable to
build on two lots in the dead zone, but it is appealing the case.
   More lawsuits are expected, but other states have had their
share of legal storms after hurricanes.
   After Hurricane Alicia pounded Galveston in 1981, Texas
probihited many residents from rebuilding under its Open Beaches
Act. The court-tested law bans building on the seaward side of a
line of vegetation.
   Alicia's storm surge moved the vegetation line back by as much
as 175 feet.
   ``It's a poker game, building on the beachfront, and it's a
gamble with Mother Nature,'' said Ken Cross, an assistant Texas
attorney general.
   Under a 1981 law, North Carolina decreed that houses must be set
back behind the first line of stable vegetation at a distance 30
times the erosion rate. The distance for larger structures is 60
times. Structures built before the law cannot be rebuilt if they
suffer 50 percent damage in a storm.
   Since 1985, the state has banned seawalls, bulkheads and
revetments to guarantee that beaches are accessible to the public.
   ``It sends a message that these are not very safe places to
build,'' said George Everett, director of theNorth Carolina
Division of Coast Management. ``And we're not going to let
buildings impact on the public's right to have access. The beach
belongs to the public.''
   Florida, which has an 8,000-mile shoreline that is longer than
any state's except Alaska, protects its beaches in a number of ways.
   In one example, nothing can be built beyond the frontal dune,
which is the first raised portion of land from the water's edge. If
a hurricane destroys any building seaward of either the erosion
line or the frontal dune, it can't be rebuilt.
   ``Everybody wants to be able to walk out the door to the
water,'' said Andy Grayson, director of Florida's Division of
Beaches and Shores.
   In Massachusetts, permits are given on a case-by-case basis
under the state's Wetlands Protection Act, which gives the state
authority to deny building or rebuilding.
   ``If you can show you can build without harm to the beach or the
dune, you can do it. (But) we have the authority to deny,'' said
Jeff Benoit, chief of the state's Coastal Zone Management Office.
   Rhode Island, the Ocean State, prohibits building on barrier
beaches and dune crests. A structure built before the law that is
50 percent or more destroyed by a storm cannot be rebuilt without a
permit.
   ``If it's destroyed by a storm, that gives us a pretty good
indication that it may be in an area that's inappropriate to be
built on,'' said Tim Dillingham, a marine resource specialist.
   Georgia's Shore Assistance Act requires a specific set-back for
buildings proposed on sand dunes and barrier islands. An existing
building destroyed by a hurricane must comply with the set-back law.
   New Jersey allows rebuilding, but Gov. Thomas Kean has sought a
coastal protection commission to control development. Kean's order
to require state approval for oceanfront development is being
argued in appeals courts.
   Virginia and Delaware govern new buildings, but not existing
ones damaged by storms. Maryland also does not restrict rebuilding.
   ``There's no doubt people along the Eastern seaboard have built
too close to the ocean,'' said Clay Brittain, a hotel owner in
Myrtle Beach. ``We wouldn't do it again. But you can't move back
completely from a developed area. It's not practical to retreat.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
