<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0654EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv09   10-06 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 09,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Oct. 9, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Study Finds Cervical Cap 88 Percent Effective in Preventing Pregnancy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cervical cap is somewhat more effective
in preventing pregnancy than condoms and diaphragms, and two-thirds
of its failures are caused by improper use, according to a study of
3,433 women.
   ``There are a shrinking number of contraceptive options for
women,'' said Dr. Gary Richwald, of the University of California,
Los Angeles. ``The IUD is now recommended for limited use, and
while the pill has a lower failure rate _ 6 percent _ the cap
offers a new, relatively safe form of birth control, with fewer and
less serious side effects than the pill.''
   The UCLA study found about 12 percent of women who use the
cervical cap become pregnant within the first year of use. That
compares with first-year pregnancy risks of 16 percent for the
diaphragm and 14 percent for condoms, according to the American
College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists.
   Previous studies of the cervical cap's effectiveness found
first-year pregnancy rates ranging from 8 percent to 19 percent.
   Richwald says his eight-year study of 3,433 women who used the
birth control device is the largest, longest and involves patients
of doctors, nurses and midwives, ``which allows for greater
generalization of the findings.''
   About 70,000 women use the cervical cap, which is a small rubber
cup that fits over the cervix, or uterine opening, and stays in
place by suction. It was approved for widespread use in May 1988 by
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration, which said the cap should be
used with spermicide and worn for no more than 48 hours.
   Some studies have suggested the cap can induce precancerous
cervical abnormalities reflected by abnormal Pap smear results.
Richwald found few such changes but noted further studies are
needed to clarify the risk.
   Two-thirds of pregnancies among cap users were due to improper
use rather than failure of the cap itself, UCLA said in a news
release. A statement by the ACOG said the risk of pregnancy was
only 6 percent among ``near perfect'' cap users who never had
unprotected sex and always used spermicide in the cap.
   The study was published in the August issue of the journal
Obstetrics and Gynecology.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Acupuncture Kills Pain in Different Way Than Analgesic Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When acupuncture prevents pain, it doesn't
act on the same parts of the nervous system as painkilling drugs,
say scientists who studied patients undergoing surgery in China.
   ``Most anesthetic agents will change brain waves and alter how
nerve fibers conduct impulses, and one can measure these changes.
Acupuncture works by other mechanisms we currently have no way of
measuring,'' said Dr. Arnold Starr, of the University of
California, Irvine, College of Medicine.
   Starr, a neurology professor, and his colleagues visited
Hangzhou, China, to measure brain waves, nerve impulse conduction
and ability to perform tasks such as recognizing musical tones in
five patients undergoing surgery for removal of thyroid tumors one
to two inches in size.
   Acupuncture needles were inserted 20 minutes before surgery, and
the acupuncture points were restimulated during the operations, but
the patients remained alert and able to speak.
   They also received very small doses of painkilling drugs and a
muscle relaxant. Starr said the drugs alone would be inadequate to
block the pain of surgery, but may work in concert with acupuncture
to alter how the patients perceived pain.
   The patients' brain, nerve and sensory activity remained
unchanged during surgery, even though they felt no pain, Starr and
colleagues reported in September's issue of the journal Archives of
Neurology.
   The findings suggest acupuncture acts on the body's system of
endorphins, which are chemicals that bind to parts of the nervous
system to reduce the perception of pain, Starr said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Oct. 9</NOTE>
