<FIRST>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   10-06 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retailers Enjoy A Good September, But Some Trouble Spots Persist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Retail Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest retailers reported mixed September sales
results as Americans spent freely on clothing last month but
hesitated about expensive items like home appliances.
   Retailers who depend on apparel for much of their business said
Thursday they had strong sales gains, but other stores, including
the nation's biggest retailer, Sears, Roebuck and Co., did not fare
as well.
   Overall, sales ``were pretty good ... better than we would have
expected,'' said Jeffrey Edelman, a retail industry analyst with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Apparel retailers got a boost when cooler weather in many areas
sent consumers in search of warmer clothing during the last week to
10 days of September, analysts said.
   But sales of more expensive durable goods, which include items
such as home appliances, continued slumping because consumers were
still juggling high amounts of installment debt, said Jeffrey
Feiner, an analyst with Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.
   Analysts said this trend was most noticeable in the performance
of Sears. The company reported its overall sales rose 0.4 percent
when compared with September 1988, but declined 1.8 percent at
stores open at least a year, known in the industry as same-store or
comparable-store sales.
   Retailers and analysts consider same-store sales a more accurate
reflection of a company's performance than totals that include
sales at recently opened stores.
   Sears, the nation's largest retailer, has been unable to
overcome a severe sales slump despite a new ``everyday-low-price''
and merchandising strategy.
   Other mass merchandisers and discount retailers fared better.
   K mart Corp. said its overall September sales increased 6.1
percent, while same-store sales were up 3 percent.
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. said its overall sales were up 31 percent
in September, and same-store sales rose 16 percent.
   J.C. Penney Co. said its overall September sales rose 11.7
percent, while same-store sales increased 10.7 percent.
   May Department Stores Inc., whose department store chains are
heavily dependent on apparel sales, said its overall results rose
8.9 percent last month as same-store sales rose 6.5 percent.
   Limited Inc., the nation's largest specialty apparel retailer,
said its September sales increased 10 percent overall and 6 percent
on a same-store basis.
   Feiner, the Merrill Lynch analyst, described consumers as
``muddling along,'' but Drexel's Edelman was more upbeat.
   ``The consumer's willing to spend,'' he said. ``Spending will be
maintained at a fairly decent pace.''
   The retailers are moving into the most critical part of the
year. In the fourth quarter, which includes the holiday shopping
season, they typically make half their annual profits.
   Economists also will be watching sales in the final quarter of
the year as a barometer of how the economy is faring. Consumer
spending, which includes retail sales, accounts for two-thirds of
the gross national product.
   Analysts warned that when October's sales figures are in, they
may not look as rosy because they will be compared with the strong
performance of October 1988, when the apparel industry began its
recovery from a yearlong slide.
   The figures reported Thursday were from major general
merchandise chains and apparel retailers. The government's monthly
retail sales report is more comprehensive, including sales at auto
dealers, supermarkets, restaurants and elsewhere.
   In other reports:
   _Dayton Hudson Corp. said its overall sales were up 16.4 percent
in September, while same-store sales increased 8.6 percent.
   _Woolworth Corp. said overall sales rose 8.5 percent last month
and same-store sales were up 3.9 percent.
   _Montgomery Ward &amp; Co. reported its sales rose 1 percent in
September. The company did not release same-store results.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
