<DOCNO> AP891006-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0207EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AMR-CrandallProfile     10-06 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AMR-Crandall Profile,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMR Chief Known As Skilled, Tough-Minded Executive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: With PM-AMR-Trump, Bjt.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert L. Crandall sits at the top of the nation's
largest airline, a tough-minded executive whose goal is to make AMR
Corp. a survivor in deregulated skies.
   ``Some people see him as the kind of man who might step over his
grandmother to get to a business deal that will be good for
American Airlines,'' one unnamed former executive told the Dallas
Times Herald in a 1982 interview.
   ``But he's honest, and that's what make him the most respected
man in the business,'' said the executive.
   Crandall also is usually included on lists of the airline
industry's top executives.
   The 53-year-old chairman, president and chief executive of AMR
is in many ways the antithesis of Donald Trump, the flashy, New
York billionaire who has proposed a $7 billion buyout of AMR.
   Trump is an active member of New York society and attaches his
name to most of his holdings, from the Trump Shuttle, the airline
he bought from Eastern Airlines, to the Trump Princess, his private
yacht.
   Crandall is a much more private man, unaccustomed to giving
interviews. He is, however, blunt.
   ``You must remember that Bob Crandall doesn't bluff,'' says one
industry analyst. ``He threatens, but he doesn't bluff.''
   Trump himself has high praise for Crandall, saying the buyout
proposal ``reflects the enormous respect that I have for the
company, its management team and the company's employees.''
   The bid comes at a time when Crandall has been anticipating
expanding American's 21.8 percent share of the domestic market.
   ``Crandall is licking his chops to get at United and some of his
more leveraged competitors,'' said Kevin Burke, an analyst for
First Union Corp., a bank holding company in Charlotte, N.C.
   UAL Corp., parent of former number one carrier United Airlines,
is undergoing a $6.75 billion buyout by employees and management.
   ``He's an airline builder,'' Burke said of Crandall. ``By
building the best and largest airline in the U.S., he wants to be
one of the global survivors in what has been a cut-throat
industry.''
   Crandall took over as chairman and chief executive of AMR and
American Airlines Inc. on March 1, 1985, adding to his duties as
president, which he had held since 1980. He has been on American's
board since 1976.
   He joined American in 1973 as senior vice president-finance and
a year later was named senior vice president-marketing.
   As head of marketing, Crandall helped institute American's Super
Saver and frequent flier fare structures, its shift to hub
operations and creation of SABRE, the computerized reservation
system now considered one of the airline's key assets.
   Prior to coming to American, he spent six years at TWA,
including stints as vice president of data services and vice
president and controller.
   Before that, he worked at Eastman Kodak, Co., Hallmark Cards and
Bloomingdale's Department Stores in New York.
   He is a native of Westerly, R.I., and is a 1957 graduate of the
University of Rhode Island, with a master's degree in business
administration from the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891006-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0208EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Trump-Forays Bjt   10-06 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trump-Forays, Bjt,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Has History of Takeover Feints</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like a high-stakes baccarat player at one of his
Atlantic City casinos, real estate tycoon Donald Trump has made
some profitable bluffs to help bankroll his ambitious and splashy
acquisitions.
   ``I keep a lot of balls in the air, because most deals fall out,
no matter how promising they seem at first,'' Trump says in his
best-selling book, ``The Art of the Deal.''
   His shrewd acquisitions have expanded his empire of
hotel-casinos and prime Manhattan real estate. Most recently, Trump
purchased Eastern Airlines' lucrative Northeast shuttle service for
$365 million in early June, pledging to turn it into ``an absolute
diamond.''
   In July 1987, Trump took control of Resorts International Inc.,
a New Jersey gaming and real estate company he won in a takeover
battle. He sold Resorts last year to entertainer Merv Griffin.
   Trump has added other jewels to his crown: New York's landmark
Plaza Hotel and the Trump Tower apartment-retail-office complex,
the Trump Plaza apartment tower, several casinos in Atlantic City,
N.J., and the Bahamas, buildings in West Palm Beach, Fla.m and
undeveloped land holdings.
   But not all his deals have ended up by putting properties in his
hands. Trump also has made takeover feints at Golden Nugget Inc.,
Pan Am Corp. and United Airlines parent Allegis Corp., now called
UAL Corp.
   In each case, he accumulated shares in the company _ sometimes
indicating he might be interested in mounting a buyout _ and later
sold all or some of his shares at a profit after the price rose on
the ensuing takeover speculation or when another bidder emerged.
   With Allegis, for example, Trump is believed to have paid about
$50 a share for his 4.9 percent stake, which exceeded 2.5 million
shares. He later reportedly sold them at nearly $74, netting around
$80 million on the deal.
   Trump also sought and received federal antitrust clearance to
buy up to 15 percent of Federated Department Stores Inc.'s shares
in 1988, although he never made a buyout offer. He is estimated to
have netted $100 million on his investment in Federated, which he
made two weeks before Canadian retailer Campeau Corp. launched a
hostile, and ultimately successful, bid.
   In Trump's latest move, a $7 billion buyout proposal for AMR
Corp., parent of American Airlines, his strategy is different. He
came out openly with an outright buyout proposal in a letter to AMR
Chairman Robert L. Crandall, offering to pay $120 a share in cash
in a deal that would be the biggest airline buyout ever.
   Trump's track record of making runs at companies has made some
financial analysts wary of his intentions concerning AMR.
   ``I'm very skeptical of everything this man does,'' said Andrew
Geller, an airline analyst at Provident National Bank in
Philadelphia. ``He wants to put (AMR) in play and make profits from
it.''
   Wall Street showed its skepticism. AMR stock closed Thursday at
$99.87{ a share in heavy trading on the New York Stock Exchange, up
sharply from $83 on Wednesday but well below Trump's bid of $120.
   Trump is believed to have discreetly snapped up AMR shares in
recent weeks, keeping his holding below 5 percent of AMR's total
outstanding shares, the level at which a stake must be reported to
the Securities and Exchange Commission. Observers speculated
Thursday that the developer paid $70 to $80 a share _ allowing him
a tidy profit if he sells out.
   Still, his reputation could be on the line. Because he's made
his buyout intentions official this time, Trump has to be prepared
to have his bluff called by AMR or this could be ``his last deal,''
Geller suggested.
   Trump insists he's not in it for the money, except as a ``way to
keep score.''
   ``The real excitement is playing the game,'' he says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
