<FIRST>r f PM-AirlineLBOs     10-06 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airline LBOs,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Approves New Powers for DOT</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AMR-Trump, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate committee has approved legislation
that would broaden the authority of the Secretary of Transportation
over debt-financed buyouts of airlines.
   The legislation, approved Thursday by the Senate Commerce,
Science and Transportation Committee, will prevent any buyer from
acquiring 25 percent or more of an airline without prior approval
of the secretary.
   The bill would require the secretary to certify that the deal
would not damage the airline's ability to operate or to expand its
business.
   ``The Congress must send a strong message that highly leveraged
buyouts are not tolerable,'' said Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., who
with Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., sponsored the legislation. ``The
safety and efficiency of our aviation system is a public trust.
   ``I don't want to wake up when all U.S. carriers have been
leveraged and bought out, when foreign interests are manipulating
our markets, to decide that something should be done to regulate
the buying and selling of major parts of our transportation
network.''
   The bill now goes to the full Senate. A House aviation
subcommittee is examining different legislation to address the
issue.
   On Wednesday, Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner told
Ford's aviation subcommittee that his work in the proposed
Northwest Airlines takeover would have been easier had be been
given the opportunity to approve the transaction in advance.
   The department forced a modification of the takeover last week,
getting the Dutch airline, KLM, to reduce its investment in and
influence over the new company. The transaction had been announced
in June.
   But Skinner said he didn't necessarily favor new legislation to
deal with acquisitions in the airline.
   Current law restricts foreign ownership of airlines to 25
percent of the stock. Although it requires the department to
approve changes of ownership, advance approval is not required.
</TEXT>
