<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0210EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Trade     10-06 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mosbacher Sas Trade Deficit Still Shrinking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher says the
U.S. trade deficit is likely to shrink to between $100 billion and
$110 billion this year, with Japan accounting for about half of
that imbalance.
   Through the first seven months of the year, the trade deficit
has been running at an annual rate of $105.8 billion, down 11
percent from the 1988 deficit of $118.5 billion.
   The trade deficit for this year is improving at exactly half the
pace of last year, when the gap between imports and exports fell by
22 percent, down from a record $152.12 billion in 1987.
   Mosbacher predicted Thursday that the deficit with Japan would
total $50 billion this year, meaning that one country will account
for about half of the total deficit.
   The huge imbalance in Japanese trade makes that country ``our
prime target'' in administration efforts to lower the imbalance,
Mosbacher said in testimony before the House Foreign Affairs
Committee.
   In a separate congressional appearance, U.S. Trade
Representative Carla Hills was also blunt about the need for Japan
to do more to open its markets.
   ``Japan is an economic superpower, but they must contribute to
the system and not just take from it,'' Hills said. She said this
is the message she will convey next week during a round of trade
discussions in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
