<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0255EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-USX Bjt   10-06 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USX, Bjt,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Icahn Raises Stake in USX, Says Takeover Bid Possible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Carl Icahn says he is studying the
feasibility of making a bid for USX Corp. after buying an
additional 4.25 million shares of the steel and oil giant.
   His purchase of $155 million worth of shares this week raised
his stake in the Pittsburgh-based company to 13.06 percent from
11.41 percent.
   Icahn said in a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission on Thursday that a group led by him wants to explore a
``meaningful restructuring that would substantially enhance
shareholder value.''
   Icahn, who owns Trans World Airlines Inc., said his group was
considering making proposals for ``business combinations'' with
USX, a phrase that a source close to Icahn said meant the investor
was considering a friendly takeover offer.
   Icahn's filing said he was discussing the feasibility of a deal
with USX in combination with other possible participants and
sources of financing. He said he also was considering asking other
shareholders to elect nominees proposed by Icahn to the USX board
of directors.
   Icahn reserved the right to sell his USX shares, but said he was
not interested in selling them back to the company at a premium _ a
practice known as accepting ``greenmail.''
   The relevant pages of Icahn's filing with the SEC were supplied
to some reporters late Thursday, after the stock market closed, by
Steven Rubin, a lawyer for Icahn in New York.
   USX shares fell 37{ cents to close at $38.37{ Thursday in New
York Stock Exchange trading after surging over the last several
days on rumors that Icahn might be making another move with his
stake in the company.
   The stock rose $1.75 to $34.87{ on Monday, when USX announced it
is offering to sell natural gas and oil reserves that analysts say
could bring about $1.5 billion.
   The stock rose $1.37{ to $36.25 the next day amid talk that
Icahn was buying additional shares, and it surged $2.75 Wednesday
to $38.75. He acquired his additional shares Tuesday and Wednesday.
   Icahn, who won a takeover battle for TWA and sold a stake in
Texaco Inc. for $2 billion, bought his USX stock at prices believed
to average in the low $20s. He once suggested a buyout at $31 a
share, or around $7 billion, but never made a tender offer.
   The United Steelworkers union, meanwhile, requested Thursday
that USX reopen its existing labor agreement to restore sacrifices
granted by members in the 1982-83 and 1986-87 rounds of bargaining.
   USW local presidents met in Pittsburgh on Wednesday and Thursday
to discuss the proposal, which was overwhelmingly approved. The
presidents represent about 18,500 steelworkers.
   The Steelworkers current master agreement expires Jan. 31, 1991.
   ``A new and improved pattern of compensation now prevails in the
steel industry as a result of the current round of collective
bargaining,'' USW President Lynn Williams wrote in a letter to USX
Chief Executive Officer Charles Corry. ``Similar improvements have
been made throughout American industry during recent months.
   ``USX employees and retirees are certainly no less deserving
than other steelworkers and those who work in other industries,''
he said.
   Also Thursday, USX said it filed a lawsuit accusing Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. of deception when it sold the steelmaker $24
million in short-term commercial paper issued by financially
troubled Integrated Resources Inc.
   USX contends in the civil complaint filed Tuesday in U.S.
District Court that as underwriter of the paper, Drexel withheld
information about problems at Integrated, which defaulted on its
debt shortly after the USX purchases.
   Integrated, a former high-flying real estate and insurance
concern, on June 9 defaulted on $955 million in short-term
obligations and declared a moratorium on all debt payments while it
restructured.
   ``We have not yet seen the complaint. We believe we have
fulfilled our obligation to purchasers of Integrated's commercial
paper,'' Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder said Thursday.
</TEXT>
