<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Europe-InterestRates Bjt   10-06 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Europe-Interest Rates, Bjt,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Europe's Interest Rate Increases May Slow Growth Too Much</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Europe's interest rate increases were greater than
the financial markets expected, and some critics warned they might
do the job too well, slowing economic growth too much.
   Britain is the most vulnerable nation to economic and political
repercussions from the decision Thursday by European governments to
raise their interest rates to combat inflation and stabilize their
currencies.
   The upward move was led by West Germany, which raised its key
rates an unexpected full percentage point.
   The British government responded by raising rates a full point
as well, to 15 percent, their highest in nearly eight years. It was
a politically risky move to defend the pound.
   Other European central banks, including those of France,
Switzerland, and Austria, moved their rates up as well to ease
downward pressure on their currencies and keep them within trading
ranges imposed by the European Monetary System, which links the
currencies of most Common Market nations in order to minimize rate
swings. Britain doesn't participate.
   The dollar finished higher anyway on Thursday, but European
stock markets were unsettled.
   The dollar closed at 1.8845 West German marks, up from 1.8770
marks on Wednesday, and the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index of the British exchange fell 30.5 points, or 1.3
percent, to close at 2,281.6.
   The previous tandem interest rate increase took place in late
June. The markets had been watching a Thursday meeting of the West
German central bank's council for a possible rise, but many were
stunned by its size.
   The increases ``could be dangerous to the economy and could be
too high,'' said Peter Pietsch, an economist with Commerzbank in
Frankfurt.
   John Banham, director-general of the Confederation of British
Industry, called them ``wholly unnecessary.''
   ``High interest rates have done their job by curbing overheating
in the economy, and this further rise will be counterproductive,''
he said.
   British lawmaker John Smith, the opposition Labor Party's
spokesman on trade, said: ``This is appalling news. For millions of
mortgage payers and for businesses all over Britain living costs
will rise and investment will become even more expensive.''
   The Bundesbank raised its discount rate, the rate at which a
commercial bank can borrow funds from the central bank, from 5
percent to 6 percent and pushed up its Lombard rate from 7 percent
to 8 percent.
   The Lombard rate is the rate at which the central bank lends
funds using securities as collateral.
   The last time the Bundesbank raised key rates by more than half
a point was in February 1980.
   The West German government bank said the increases were designed
``to combat continued inflationary danger resulting from an
exuberant economy.'' It also said they were aimed at stabilizing
the mark.
   West Germany's economy is growing at a rate of 4.5 percent
compared with the previous 2 percent, and inflation is at 3
percent, said David Morrison, an economist at Goldman Sachs
International Corp. in London.
   He speculated that West Germany wanted to get interest rate
increases out of the way well before a 1990 national election.
   ``This probably reflects a peak for interest rates,'' he said.
   But British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, the
Cabinet member responsible for national finances, said on British
Broadcasting Corp. television that he couldn't promise that
Britain's rates wouldn't go even higher.
   Soon after the German move, the Bank of England signaled the
full percentage point increase in the British commercial banks'
base rates to the 15 percent level, the 11th increase since June
1988, when rates stood at a decade low of 7.5 percent.
   Britain has the highest interest rates among the major Western
democracies.
   Britain's Treasury said the European rate hikes reflected ``a
general concern to take no risks on inflation.''
   Lawson told BBC radio that with his Conservative Party opening
its annual convention Monday, the increase was ``extremely
awkward.'' But he said, ``It's necessary to do the right thing.''
   British markets had expected a rate increase since poor trade
figures were announced last week, pressuring the pound. The Bank of
England has since intervened in currency trading repeatedly to
support the pound.
   Lawson has maintained that a strong pound is essential to the
government's fight against inflation, whose annual rate stood at
7.3 percent in August, down from 8.2 percent in July but more than
double the 3.3 percent in January 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
