<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-06 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rising In Calm Trading, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in Europe early today, stunning
the markets with its resilience against higher European interest
rates. Trading was calm.
   Gold prices moved lower.
   West Germany's central bank led the interest rate increase on
Thursday by pushing up its key interest rates a full percentage
point. The central banks of Britain, France, Switzerland and other
European countries responded by raising their rates as well.
   The move was designed to curb inflation and steady their
currencies, but it failed to weaken the dollar.
   The market was waiting for the release of U.S. employment
figures for September, which were expected to show a flat jobless
rate of 5.2 percent and a rise in non-farm payrolls of 279,000.
   Strong job data could provide the dollar with the momentum to
rise further, a U.S. dealer in Frankfurt said.
   In Tokyo, where the dollar began its day, the U.S. currency rose
1.40 yen to 142.45 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted higher at
142.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
prices, included: 1.8885 West German marks, up from 1.8845; 1.6405
Swiss francs, up from 1.6365; 6.3965 French francs, up from 6.3900;
2.1351 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1200; 1,382.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,380.25; and 1.1780 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1746.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.6060 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6100 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $363.40 a troy ounce,
down from late Thursday's $365. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price of $363.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $363.60, down from $364.75.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.91 to close at a bid $364.20.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.16 a troy
ounce, down from Thursday's $5.27.
</TEXT>
