<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0743EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-06 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed against the Japanese yen today,
while share prices closed broadly lower on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar ended the week at 142.45 yen, up 1.40 yen from
Thursday's close of 141.05 yen. It opened at 141.95 yen, and traded
between 141.80 yen and 142.75 yen.
   Volume totaled $9.483 billion, down from Thursday's $10.358
billion.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 140.19-point
gainer Thursday, shed 313.64 points, or 0.88 percent, closing the
week at 35,209.35.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 700 million
shares, compared to Thursday's 900 million.
   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's strength to an upswing
in overseas markets Thursday despite interest rate hikes by West
European central banks. Higher interest rates are supposed to
support a currency against other currencies.
   Earlier Thursday, the Bundesbank, West Germany's central bank,
raised its key lending rates by 1 percentage point, including the
official discount rate, to 6 percent annually. The measure was
aimed at curbing the dollar's strength in order to help stem
inflationary pressures in West Germany.
   Central banks in Britain, France and other European nations
followed with similar measures Thursday.
   Masaaki Tanahashi, a dealer with Mitsui Bank, said Japan's
central bank intervened selling many millions of dollars, but said
``the intervention helped little'' to stop the dollar's upward
pressure.
   The Bank of Japan does not comment on its monetary activities.
   Tanahashi said the market is awaiting U.S. umemployment figures
for September, due out later today in Washington, as a factor in
finding the dollar's direction.
   Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto meanwhile told a news
conference today Japan will watch carefully for any impact from the
raise in West European interest rates. He added, however, ``We are
not considering any change in our monetary policy'' for now.
   On the stock market, the market's main barometer fell following
three bullish sessions this week apparently due to the higher West
European interest rates.
   They said concern over the upcoming jobless rate was another
factor that sent many investors to the sidelines.
</TEXT>
