<FIRST>u f PM-AirlineReport     10-06 0109</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airline Report,0114</SECOND>
<HEAD>Complaints Drop Against Airlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer complaints against airlines dropped
11 percent last month and were 42 percent below a year ago, the
Transportation Department said.
   The government's monthly Air Travel Consumer Report, released
Thursday, said complaints against all airlines totaled 1,104 for
September, while there were 1,244 filed in August and 1,913 in
September 1988.
   Complaints tallied so far this year are less than half last
year's level, the report said.
   Airlines reported that 74.6 percent of their flights were on
time in August, a slight decline from July's 76.9 percent. The
statistics do not include flights delayed because of mechanical
problems.
</TEXT>
