<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 0912EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GM-ChryslerTransmissions     10-06 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM-Chrysler Transmissions,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joint Transmission Project Pending for GM, Chrysler</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. and General Motors Corp. will form
what apparently is the first joint manufacturing venture among the
nation's Big Three automakers, building manual transmissions at two
plants.
   GM and Chrysler said in a joint statement Thursday that the
project would involve plants in Muncie, Ind., and Syracuse, N.Y.,
and supply transmissions for a wide range of cars and trucks sold
by both companies.
   In the past, the Big Three have supplied parts to each other,
but representatives for all three said they were not aware of any
common manufacturing projects.
   Chrysler's Acustar subsidiary will own 64 percent of the
yet-to-be-named company and GM will own the rest, the announcement
said. Neither company would disclose financial terms of the joint
venture.
   The deal is in the form of a letter of intent and must be
approved by federal officials. The joint venture could be in place
by Jan. 1, the statement said.
   One antitrust expert said the deal, which must be approved by
the Federal Trade Commission or the U.S. Justice Department, may
face close scrutiny.
   ``I am certain the companies will argue that it is a very
limited arrangement,'' said law Professor Martin Adelman of Wayne
State University in Detroit. ``But if they start with a small joint
venture, how do you know the companies won't talk about other
arrangements?''
   Ford Motor Co. spokesman Tom Foote said his company did not have
immediate comment on the deal. ``We have to learn more about it,''
he said.
   GM spokesman John Hartnett said he expects the federal
government to consider the antitrust implications of the deal later
this year. He said he did not anticipate any problems.
   Hartnett and Chrysler spokesman James Kenyon said GM's Muncie
plant was not being used to its capacity while Chrysler's Syracuse
plant had too much work.
   Neither company would give the production levels of either
plant. The 2,700 workers at the Syracuse plant and the 1,400 at
Muncie factory should be unaffected, Hartnett and Kenyon said.
   ``Muncie is under-utilized to a degree and this could add
employment,'' Hartnett said.
   Transmissions from the two plants will go to a variety of GM and
Chrysler cars, trucks, minivans and Jeeps with manual
transmissions. Profits or losses generated by the plants will be
shared in the same proportion as the ownership.
   GM President Robert Stempel said the venture would enhance
efficiency at both plants.
   ``This ... alliance is a win-win situation that means greater
job security for both facilities,'' Chrysler Vice Chairman Gerald
Greenwald said.
   Engineers from GM, Ford and Chrysler are involved in a joint
project looking into uses of plastics for cars and trucks of the
future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
