<FIRST>r f BC-Braniff     10-06 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Braniff,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Braniff Announces More Discount Fares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Braniff Inc., a week after filing for
Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, has announced more discount air
fares in a bid to lure passengers.
   Orlando-based Braniff said Thursday it was offering one-way
fares ranging from $29 to $189 on most of its regional flights and
transcontinental fares from $99 to $199.
   Until Oct. 16, Braniff will continue offering $99 one-way fares
as part of a promotion as it reorganizes.
   Beginning Oct. 16, the airline will offer three fare levels,
including three- and seven-day advance-purchase schemes, as well as
a Y Special fare requiring no advance purchase.
   ``Our fare structure will be easy for the consumer to
understand, easy for the travel agent to book and easy for Braniff
to process,'' said Tom Volz, the airline's senior vice president
for marketing.
   Under the new fare program, all tickets purchased under all
three fare schemes can be booked up to 331 days in advance of
travel dates. All fares will be locked in at the new prices,
Braniff said.
   Fares under the seven-day advance plan will be $99 one way _
when purchased on a round-trip basis between any two cities served
by Braniff, except Chicago and Phoenix, Ariz.
   Fares to those two cities are lower, the airline said.
   Braniff said only a limited number of seats will be available on
each flight under the seven-day advance-purchase plan.
   Braniff also will offer a three-day advance-purchase fare of
$109 one way on nonstop flights between Kansas City, Mo., and New
York; Newark, N.J.; Washington, D.C.; Orlando; Dallas-Fort Worth,
Texas; San Diego, Calif.; Los Angeles; and San Francisco.
   The fare for flights between any other two cities in the Braniff
network purchased under the three-day advance plan will be $139 one
way.
</TEXT>
