<HEAD>Crop Futures Slip On Harvest Pressure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
lower on the Chicago Board of Trade today amid profit-taking and
harvest-related selling.
   ``We should have real good harvest progress this week,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., citing
forecasts for dry, cool conditions in the Midwestern corn and
soybean country.
   Wheat futures opened higher on rumors the Soviet Union was
seeking to buy some U.S. wheat, but the market turned lower on
spillover selling from the neighboring corn and soybean pits.
   The Agriculture Department announced late Thursday that the
Soviets had bought 400,000 metric tons of U.S. corn. But corn
prices rallied in Thursday's session in anticipation of a deal and
corn prices opened lower today on profit-taking.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 1 cent to 1{ cents lower
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.09{ a bushel; corn
futures were 2 cents lower to \ cent higher with December at $2.41\
a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1{ cents lower with December at
$1.45} a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents lower to 1{ cent higher
with November at $5.71{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures prices were narrowly mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .30 cent lower to .07 cent higher with October
at 71.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .13 cent lower to .05
cent higher with October at 83.10 cents a pound; live hogs were .15
cent lower to .28 cent higher with October at 45.85 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .12 cent lower to .10 cent higher with
February at 48.30 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Thursday while pork futures
advanced.
