<FIRST>r f BC-Taiwan-Evergreen 1stLd-Writethru   10-06 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Taiwan-Evergreen, 1st Ld-Writethru,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Evergreen Airways Buys Planes From Boeing, McDonnell Douglas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: rewrites throughout with details.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evergreen Airways Corp. of Taiwan said it signed
contracts with Boeing Commercial Airplanes and McDonnell Douglas
Corp. today for the purchase of 26 aircraft valued at a total of
$3.6 billion.
   According to the agreements, Boeing will deliver eight 747-400
and four 767-300ER passenger jets to Evergreen between 1992 and
1997 while McDonnell Douglas will deliver 14 MD-11 craft.
   In Seattle, Boeing Commercial Airplanes spokesman Craig Martin
said Boeing's share included firm orders for four of the long-range
747 jumbo jets and two of the extended-range 767s. Evergreen took
options on an equal number of aircraft, he said.
   The total Boeing order, including options, is worth $1.93
billion in delivery-year dollars, the price Evergreen will pay when
it actually receives the planes, Martin said.
   The 747-400, which entered service in the past year, can carry
412 passengers 8,400 miles. The 767-300ER is a twin-engine widebody
jet that can carry 210 passengers 6,900 miles.
   It was not known if the current strike against Boeing by its
machinists, in its third day Friday, would affect the aircraft
maker's delivery schedule.
   McDonnell Douglas' MD-11, which is due to enter service next
year, is a long-range, three-engine jumbo jet that will carry about
320 passengers in two classes.
   Evergreen, which was founded in March, plans its first flight
for 1992. The airline's initial destinations are expected to be in
Asia while flights to the United States and Europe will be added
later.
   When it begins flights, Evergreen will be Taiwan's second
international airline operator. China Air Lines is the other.
   Evergreen is owned by Evergreen Group, said to be the world's
largest container-ship operator, possessing 66 modernized container
vessels that travel to over 30 ports worldwide.
</TEXT>
