<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     10-06 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher Despite Intervention, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in busy European trading Friday,
as new investor demand and short covering helped overcome a round
of concerted central bank intervention.
   Gold prices fell.
   The dollar was quoted at 1.8880 Deutsche marks, up from 1.8845
marks late Thursday in London.
   The dollar was also changing hands at 142.50 yen. Earlier in
Tokyo, the dollar rose 1.40 yen to 142.45 yen.
   Overnight intervention by central banks from the United States,
West German and Japan was ignored as the dollar hit the day's high
of 1.9030 marks early in the European afternoon.
   One senior dealer said the U.S. currency was boosted by short
covering. Many market players had taken short positions in the
morning, and were forced to unload them when stop loss orders were
triggered around 1.8800 marks.
   Dealers appeared nonchalant about news that the U.S.
unemployment rate rose 0.1 point to 5.3 percent in September, while
non-farm payrolls rose a smaller-than-expected 209,000.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.6435 Swiss francs, up from 1.6365; 6.4035 French
francs, up from 6.3900; 2.1350 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1200;
1380.25 Italian lire, unchanged; and 1.1760 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1746.
   The British pound sterling traded at $1.6030, compared with
$1.6100 late Thursday.
   Gold dropped $1.75 in London, and sold at a late bid price of
$363.25 a troy ounce.
   In Zurich, gold was lower, closing at a bid $362.80 compared
with $364.75 late Thursday.
   Gold in Hong Kong fell $2.91 to close at a bid $364.20.
   Silver bullion prices skidded on the London market to a late bid
price of $5.14 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $5.27.
</TEXT>
