<DOCNO> AP891006-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1759EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AMI-Offer     10-06 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AMI-Offer,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital Management Firm Pondered Offer Lowered by $230 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group that bid $1.9
billion for American Medical International Inc. in July said it has
lowered its offer for the hospital management company by $230
million.
   The new $1.67 billion cash offer by IMA Acquisition Corp.,
announced Thursday, represents the investment group's concern over
a tax bill that would make the acquisition more costly, according
to an analyst.
   AMI, based in Beverly Hills, was reviewing the offer early
Friday, and could not say when it would comment on the lower bid.
   ``The offer was given to a special committee of the board of
directors, and they have not responded,'' said Suzanne Hovdey,
spokeswoman for AMI.
   The investment group, financed by Chicago's Pritzker family and
First Boston Corp., said it would not be able to arrange financing
for the offer before it expired Oct. 11, and therefore could not
pay the original $28 per share. The new IMA offer would pay
shareholders $26.50 per share.
   The group initially planned to finance about $250 million of the
offer with payment-in-kind bonds, but the proposed tax change would
take away the tax deduction for the interest payments on those
bonds. The group has applied for an exemption to the new tax bill
submitted after IMA's July 7 offer.
   The bill has passed the House and has not been acted on by the
Senate.
   By submitting the lower bid, the group has given AMI executives
a new opportunity to put the hospital chain on the auction block,
according to Kenneth Abramowitz, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein
&amp; Co. in New York.
   ``If no one offers more money, it (the amended bid) is a fair
offer,'' he said.
   Abramowitz said the partnership is citing uncertainty about the
new tax law to gain leverage with AMI. ``They used the IRS issue as
an excuse,'' he said. ``They reduced the price because they thought
they could get away with it.''
   Another analyst, Seth Shaw of Prudential Bache Securities in New
York, predicted AMI would accept the new bid.
   ``I still think it's a good offer for shareholders,'' he said.
``Anything over $18 is good.''
   First Boston was to have financed part of the deal with about
$700 million in junk bond sales, and several analysts pointed out
that IMA would have to pay millions of dollars more in interest to
attract bond buyers now that the junk bond market has softened.
   ``The conditions in the junk bond market have changed
dramatically since the original agreement,'' said John Hindelong,
an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp. in New
York.
   ``The change is reflected in this offer. I think (AMI)
shareholders, given the changes in the junk bond market, will be
pleased with the offer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891006-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1625EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     10-06 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0184</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market hit new highs again today in
buying inspired by the latest evidence of sluggish economic growth.
   Before the opening the Labor Department reported that the
civilian unemployment rate rose a tenth of a percentage point in
September to 5.3 percent.
   The data also showed an increase of 209,000 in nonfarm payroll
employment, well short of advance estimates on Wall Street in the
range of 275,000 to 300,000.
   Analysts said traders interpreted the report as a fresh signal
that the economy was making only sluggish progress. The widespread
inference from that, brokers said, was that chances were improving
for a further easing of the Federal Reserve's credit policy sooner
or later.
   The report sent interest rates lower in the credit markets.
Rates on short-term Treasury bills fell about 20 basis points, or
hundredths of a percentage point.
   Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite
direction from interest rates, rose more than $5 for each $1,000 in
face value.
</TEXT>
