<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1741EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-06 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Finishes Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed in U.S. trading after
marching higher overseas as investors remained bullish about the
U.S. currency despite ongoing efforts by central banks to squelch
demand.
   Gold finished higher in New York after falling in Europe and
Asia. Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid late in
the day at $363.25 an ounce, up from $363.10 late Thursday.
   Dollar traders mostly ignored efforts by central banks from the
United States, West Germany and Japan to push the currency lower,
raising more questions about the Group of Seven industrial nations'
attempts to stabilize world currency markets.
   ``Central banks don't seem to know what they want,'' said
Lawrence A. Veit, international economist with Brown Brothers
Harriman &amp; Co. ``Unless the central banks show a sign of getting
their act together we will see a stronger dollar.''
   The dollar firmed in early trading after showing surprising
resilience on Thursday despite coordinated interest-rate increases
by central banks in Europe. Normally, such a move would blunt the
dollar's attraction in global markets in favor of foreign
currencies.
   The dollar dipped briefly in U.S. trading after a Labor
Department report suggested the economy is softer than expected,
but quickly resumed its climb.
   The government reported that the nation's civilian unemployment
rate rose to 5.3 percent in September from 5.2 percent in July and
August and that the economy added 209,000 non-farm payroll jobs in
September, fewer than expected. Analysts said the markets had
expected a sharper gain of up to 300,000 non-farm payroll jobs.
   A softer economy could prompt the Fed to lower interest rates to
avoid a serious slowdown, making the dollar less appealing to
foreign investors. However, without evidence that the Fed was
moving to ease monetary policy the dollar resumed its upward climb.
   ``The short-term employment numbers were overridden by
longer-term bullishness on the dollar,'' said David Johnson,
currency broker at First National Bank of Chicago.
   Analysts said the Fed probably would wait for more confirmation
to see if indeed the economy is slowing down before altering its
credit policy.
   ``They're not going to ease rates because of a single set of
employment numbers,'' Johnson said.
   In Europe, the dollar was quoted at 1.8880 West German marks, up
from 1.8845 marks Thursday. In late New York trading, the dollar
climbed to 1.8885 marks, from 1.8848 on Thursday.
   The dollar rose 1.40 yen to 142.45 yen in Tokyo and changed
hands at 142.50 yen in London, up from 142.30. In New York,
meanwhile, the U.S. currency dipped to 142.35 yen from 142.55 yen a
day earlier.
   In London trading, the British pound rose to $1.6030, from
$1.6100 late Thursday. But in New York, the pound fell to $1.6055
from $1.6115 on Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.6420 Swiss francs, up from 1.6360;
1.17525 Canadian dollars, down from 1.17625; 6.4050 French francs,
up from 6.3865; and 1,383.25 Italian lire, up from 1,380.00.
   Other dollar rates in Europe late Friday compared with
Thursday's rates, included: 1.6435 Swiss francs, up from 1.6365;
6.4035 French francs, up from 6.3900; 2.1350 Dutch guilders, up
from 2.1200; 1380.25 Italian lire, unchanged; and 1.1760 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1746.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $363.70 an ounce, up from $363.40 on Thursday.
   Gold dropped $1.75 in London to a late bid of $363.25 a troy
ounce. In Zurich, gold fell to $362.80 compared with $364.75 late
Thursday. Gold fell in Hong Kong by $2.91 to close at $364.20 an
ounce.
   Silver bullion prices skidded on the London market to a late bid
price of $5.14 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $5.27.
   On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery settled
at $5.117 an ounce, down from from $5.166.
</TEXT>
