<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1747EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-06 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Tumble As Coffee Meeting Ends Without Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices sank for the fourth straight day Friday,
hitting 14-year lows after a meeting of the world's biggest coffee
producers and consumers ended with no price-support agreement.
   ``They're going to keep the door open for negotiations and
that's it,'' said Kim Badenhop, a market analyst with Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets Inc.
   On other commodity markets, corn and soybeans slumped while
livestock, precious metals and energy futures were mixed.
   Coffee futures finished 2.5 cents to 2.79 cents lower with
December at 70.39 cents a pound, the market's lowest settlement
since the summer of 1975.
   The sell-off coincided with the close of the International
Coffee Organization's two-week semiannual meeting in London, a
session that produced only a vague resolution interpreted by
analysts as an attempt to keep the bottom from falling out of the
world coffee market.
   ``They put their signatures on a goodwill declaration to meet in
the future when conditions are right,'' said Bert Ruiz, a vice
president with Balfour Maclaine Corp. ``The big news from the
meeting was no news.''
   The 74-nation group is not scheduled to meet again for six
months.
   Prices for near-month delivery of coffee in New York have fallen
by 38 percent since early July, when ICO producers, led by Brazil,
balked at demands by the consumers, led by the United States, for
increased availability of top-quality coffees and a halt to sales
of coffee at discount prices to nonmembers. The disagreement led to
a suspension of the export quotas that had supported coffee prices.
   Few observers expected the differences to be ironed out at the
London meeting. But pessimism about the organization's future
multiplied following statements made Tuesday by Jorio Dauster,
president of the Brazilian Coffee Institute, that he saw no chance
for a return to international price supports for at least six
months.
   Corn and soybean futures drooped on the Chicago Board of Trade
in anticipation of heavy harvesting activity this weekend in the
Midwest.
   Wheat futures firmed slightly amid rumors that the Soviet Union
is seeking to buy an unknown quantity of U.S. wheat.
   The rumors in the wheat market reflected a general increase in
export activity. Similar rumors supported the corn market all week.
   The Agriculture Department confirmed a sale of 1.1 million
metric tons of corn to the Soviets late Friday, bringing to more
than 3.6 million metric tons the amount confirmed since the weekend.
   Wheat futures settled } cent to 4 cents higher with December at
$4.11{ a bushel; corn was 4 cents to 5\ cents lower with December
at $2.38} a bushel; oats were 2} cents to 3} cents lower with
December at $1.43{ a bushel; soybeans were 3\ cents to 6{ cents
lower with November at $5.67{ a bushel.
   Frozen pork-belly futures fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange amid lower fresh belly prices on cash markets and
speculation that cash prices would drop even further next week due
to a rise in hog slaughters.
   Hog and cattle futures finished mostly lower although near-month
live cattle futures gained on expectations for stronger cash
markets next week.
   Live cattle settled .23 cent lower to .37 cent higher with
October at 71.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .25
cent lower with October at 82.97 cents a pound; live hogs were .28
cent lower to .58 cent higher with October at 46.15 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .68 cent to 1.30 cents lower with February
at 47.12 cents a pound.
   Gold futures settled 40 cents lower to 30 cents higher on New
York's Commodity Exchange with October at $363.70 a troy ounce;
silver was 4.9 cents to 6.7 cents lower with December at $5.19 a
troy ounce.
   Energy futures finished mixed in uneventful trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 8 cents to 10 cents lower
with November at $19.87 a barrel; heating oil was .15 cent lower to
.30 cent higher with November at 58.18 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .10 cent to .31 cent lower with November at 54.80
cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
