<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1758EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AMR-TrumpFinancing Bjt   10-06 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AMR-Trump Financing, Bjt,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Well Positioned to Finance AMR Deal, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AMR-Trump, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Having written the book on the art of the deal
in real estate, casinos and the airline business, Donald Trump is a
good bet to secure the financing he needs to pull off his $7
billion offer for American Airlines parent AMR Corp., experts
believe.
   His chances for success were viewed positively Friday, despite
recent turmoil in the credit markets.
   ``He's borrowed in the past and paid back and he's viewed as a
good customer,'' said Lawrence Cohn, a banking analyst at
investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Trump, who promised to put up a staggering $1 billion of his own
money for the deal, seems to have a winning combination: a string
of blue-chip real estate and casino properties he could borrow
against, and the highly regarded AMR itself _ whose assets could be
considered as collateral.
   Dallas-based AMR includes American, the nation's largest
airline; SABRE, the leading computer reservations system valued at
around $1.5 billion; and a modernized jet fleet more than half of
which is owned by the carrier, rather than leased.
   Trump's relations with bankers have been warm, and he appears
capable of surmounting a less than hospitable investment climate,
anxiety in Washington and some skepticism about his intentions.
   ``I think it will be difficult. Seven billion dollars is a lot,
even for Donald Trump,'' said Marilyn Cohen, president of Capital
Insight Inc., an investment firm in Beverly Hills, Calif. ``That's
not to say the man can't pull it off.''
   Big corporate borrowing is a lot more difficult these days, in
the wake of recent trouble in the ``junk-bond'' market, Ms. Cohen
noted.
   Prices of the high-risk, high-yield bonds plunged in
mid-September after Campeau Corp., a major retailer and junk-bond
issuer, said it would have trouble paying its bills. The Campeau
crisis mushroomed throughout the junk-bond market and spilled over
into bank lending _ since many of the big banks also finance
mergers and acquisitions, including some junk-bond deals.
   Nevertheless, ``really good deals do continue to get done,''
said Drexel's Cohn. ``If it's a solid deal, then the banks are
going to lend on it.''
   Mark Daugherty, an airline analyst at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.,
said it would take at least $3 billion of equity for Trump's offer
to be a healthy one. That's assuming Trump would assume AMR's $1.5
billion in debt, putting the real value of the deal at around $8.5
billion, and figuring a desirable ratio of two-thirds debt to
one-third equity.
   But Louis Marckesano, who follows the industry for the
Philadelphia brokerage of Janney Montgomery Scott Inc., said $1
billion in equity was sufficient for the deal to fly.
   In addition to the dampened borrowing climate Trump faces,
observers also note the rumbling drumbeat of anxiety coming from
the Bush administration and Congress about high levels of debt
being created by the wave of takeovers and proposed buyouts in the
airline industry.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner has recently expressed
concern about the debt piled up by big airline buyouts and the
participation of foreign carriers in the deals. His department has
intervened in two airline deals _ the $3.65 billion takeover of NWA
Inc., Northwest Airline's parent, and the proposed $6.75 billion
buyout of United Airline's owner, UAL Corp.
   Congress also has grabbed on to the issue, scheduling committee
hearings and studying legislation on airline takeovers.
   Trump's offer for AMR ``is another instance of quick-profit
speculation in the airline industry that is endangering the
nation's air transportation system,'' said Rep. Byron L. Dorgan,
D-N.D. ``None of this makes any economic sense,'' he said in a
telephone interview from Washington.
   Some analysts question Trump's sincerity in the bid, in light of
his track record of making takeover runs at companies and then
turning a quick profit by selling his stock.
   But others jump to his defense. ``I think he is extremely
serious about this and it's a mistake to think otherwise,'' said
Helane Becker, an airline analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
