<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1803EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     10-06 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices soared Friday on expectations the
Federal Reserve might soon lower interest rates following a
government report showing a sharp decline in manufacturing jobs in
September.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond was up 21-32 point, or
about $6.56 for every $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which falls
when prices rise, dropped to 8.01 percent from 8.07 percent late
Thursday.
   The Labor Department reported Friday that the nation's civilian
unemployment rate rose a notch to 5.3 percent in September from 5.2
percent in July and August.
   A separate survey of employers showed that the economy added
209,000 non-farm payroll jobs in September, despite an artificial
increase reflecting the return of some 75,000 striking telephone
workers. Analysts said the markets had expected a sharper gain of
up to 300,000 non-farm payroll jobs.
   More important, economists said, was a loss of 103,000
manufacturing jobs, including 33,000 at auto plants. Payrolls
either declined or were flat within all manufacturing industries
except food processing.
   ``That's going to get people's attention and raise some concerns
since it's not just a special factor,'' such as autos, said Jean
Buckley, money market economist at BankAmerica Capital Markets
Group in San Francisco.
   ``The concern will be that the manufacturing sector is much
weaker than people have been expecting,'' she said.
   Buckley said analysts are estimating that industrial production
will be 0.4 percent lower and capacity utilization 0.6 percent
lower following the employment report.
   A weakening economy is bullish for fixed-income instruments such
as bonds because long-term investments more attractive during an
economic slowdown.
   The jobs report could encourage the Federal Reserve to ease
interests rates in the near term to reinvigorate the economy. But
on Friday the central bank's action in draining some bank reserves
was perceived as a signal that Fed policy had not changed.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments rose by between 5-32 point and 9-16 point, intermediate
maturities climbed by as much as 19-32 point and long-term issues
rose as much as 29-32 point, according to Telerate Inc., the
financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, jumped 5.75 to 1,185.21.
   In corporate trading, industrials rose. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a portfolio of
80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, shot up
2.25 to 333.50.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds was 9223-32, up ] point. The average yield
to maturity fell to 7.33 percent from 7.37 percent late Thursday.
   Yields on Treasury bills were down sharply. Three-month bills
fell to 7.82 percent as the discount plunged 17 basis points to
7.58 percent. Yields on six-month bills fell to 8.02 percent as the
discount fell 18 basis points to 7.62 percent. Yields on one-year
bills fell to 8.06 percent as the discount dropped 21 basis points
to 7.51 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 813-16 percent, down from 9 percent late
Thursday.
</TEXT>
