<FIRST>u f AM-BordenPlants     10-06 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Borden Plants,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Borden to Sell 14 Dairy Plants in 10 States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Borden Inc. said Friday it plans to sell
14 dairy plants in 10 states as part of a restructuring to reduce
its work force and concentrate in markets where it has performed
well.
   It was the first indication which of the company's 265 plants
worldwide will be closed or sold.
   Company spokeswoman Chris Tilton said the company will sell
plants in Dayton, Youngstown and New Bremen, all in Ohio; Miami,
Pensacola and Tampa, all in Florida; Albany, N.Y.; Albuquerque,
N.M.; Detroit; High Point, N.C.; Indianapolis, Lexington, Ky.;
Macon, Ga., and Milwaukee.
   Ms. Tilton said the company intends to find buyers who will
retain the 2,400 employees affected by the sales.
   ``We've made the announcement to employees throughout the past
week,'' she said. ``These are the actions we're taking in 1989.
This completes our dairy announcements for this year.''
   The corporate restructuring, announced Sept. 28 at the company's
headquarters in New York, will result in cutting 7,000 jobs _ 15
percent of the company's work force. Romeo J. Ventres, chairman and
chief executive officer, said 65 plants will be closed or sold over
the next two to three years.
   Ms. Tilton said the company has potential buyers for some of the
14 plants. She would not identify buyers or the plants.
   ``We have had interest expressed by a number of buyers for many
of the locations. ... We would certainly expect to have offers
coming in for all of them,'' she said. ``Local management is
getting the right of first refusal.''
   All of the plants market and distribute fluid milk products.
   The company said the restructuring will reduce Borden's
worldwide employment from 46,000 to about 39,000.
   Borden said food and non-food operations also will be
restructured to eliminate some of the less efficient and older
plants the company has acquired in recent years.
   Borden will take a $571 million pre-tax charge against its
third-quarter income, resulting in a quarterly loss of $300 million
to $305 million and a loss of $47 million to $58 million for the
full year.
   The one-time charge, amounting to about $404 million after
taxes, will be used to consolidate Borden's six business lines. The
goal is to cut costs and boost pre-tax profit by aboubt $340
million through 1993.
   Although Borden is based in New York, its administrative offices
are in Columbus.
</TEXT>
