<DOCNO> AP891006-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1849EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Boeing Bjt   10-06 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing, Bjt,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Arrested in Picketing Incident; Union, Boeing Trade Barbs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production continued slowly at Boeing Co. plants
Friday as a strike by 57,800 machinists stretched into its third
day without the company or union scheduling new talks to end the
walkout.
   Separately, Boeing announced it had gained another
multibillion-dollar aircraft order, from Evergreen Airways Corp. of
Taiwan, further adding to the company's huge backlog of airliner
orders.
   Federal mediator Douglas Hammond said no new talks had been
scheduled.
   Union officials have said they would resume talks whenever
Boeing indicated it was ready, although Boeing spokesman Harold
Carr said the Machinists had made no specific offer and had not set
a date for when they would be willing to return to negotiations.
   The union went on strike Wednesday after its three-year contract
with Boeing expired and the parties were unable to reach agreement
on a new pact.
   Boeing is offering cost-of-living raises, bonuses a reduction in
mandatory overtime and other improvements.
   The Machinists _ who represent the bulk of Boeing production
workers _ want a larger than offered share of Boeing's financial
prosperity and a bigger reduction in hours of mandatory overtime at
the company, which is pressing hard to increase aircraft production
because of record aircraft orders.
   Work was still far from normal Friday at many Boeing plants, a
company spokesman said, and members of another Boeing union said
they were getting some harassment from striking machinists.
   Strikers include 43,300 in the Seattle area, 12,000 in Wichita,
Kan., 1,700 in Portland, Ore., and others at several locations
nationwide.
   All Boeing plants are open, though Boeing Commercial Airplanes
spokesman Jack Gamble said things were ``going very slowly'' at
aircraft production plants, where supervisors were manning
production lines.
   A Malaysian Airlines 747-400 should be delivered this week,
Gamble said, but he was not aware of any other planes that had been
scheduled for delivery in the past few days. The Malaysian plane
has been awaiting only final FAA certification for delivery, he
said.
   Boeing has 93 planes scheduled for delivery between now and the
end of the year and Gamble said about 40 of those were near
completion.
   Before the strike, Boeing was producing about 30 planes a month,
and was running near capacity.
   Boeing, the world's largest commercial jet builder with 65
percent of the free world's market, is in its fifth consecutive
year of record jetliner orders.
   Evergreen Airways ordered 26 jets from Boeing and McDonnell
Douglas Corp. Boeing's share includes firm orders for four 747-400s
and two extended-range 767-300ERs, plus options for four 747-400s
and two 767-300ERs. Boeing spokesman Craig Martin said the total
Boeing order, including options, eventually would be worth $1.93
billion.
   Charles Bofferding, president of the Seattle Professional
Engineering Employees Association, the second-largest union at
Boeing after the Machinists, sent his 27,000 members letters saying
that some SPEEA members ``are meeting with resistance and mild
harassment'' when going to work.
   Bofferding urged his members to wear union identification and to
decline to do Machinists' work.
   On Thursday night, a picket outside Boeing's Everett plant that
builds widebody 747 and 767 jetliners received a broken arm when
struck by a pickup truck at the plant's west gate, according to
Everett police spokesman Ken Murray. A friend of the injured man
then struck the driver with his fist and was arrested for
investigation of assault, Murray said.
   The driver of the truck was not cited. Murray said witnesses
said he attempted to stop and couldn't swerve because of other
pickets in the street.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
