<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1858EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AMR-Trump Bjt   10-06 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AMR-Trump, Bjt,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politicians, Labor Lining Up Against Trump's AMR Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of American Airlines'
second-largest union met with advisers Friday to discuss possible
ways to help management fend off developer Donald Trump's $7
billion buyout proposal.
   Michael Kelleher, president of the 16,000-member Association of
Professional Flight Attendants, was notified of the offer by
management early Thursday. He traveled to New York Friday to meet
with ``legal and labor advisers to prepare contingency plans in
light of any events that may transpire,'' said Alan Fahringer, a
spokesman for the independent union.
   Also Friday, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, exchanged letters with
Trump, expressing concern over the wave of airline takeovers.
Bentsen is a member of the Senate Committee on Commerce, Science
and Transportation which Thursday recommended legislation that
would require federal approval of takeovers.
   In a letter to Bentsen, Trump said he was ``sensitive'' to the
concerns, especially ``regarding excessive leverage, as evidenced
by my stated intention to commit at least $1 billion of equity to
an acquisition of the company.''
   ``Airlines must be financially fit enough to meet rigorous
safety standards, replace aging aircraft, contribute their fair
share to improve airport facilities, as well as maintain an
adequate and well-trained labor force,'' replied Bentsen, who is
working on having legislation retroactive to cover Trump's proposal.
   Other local and national politicians also began lining up
against Trump, criticizing the real estate tycoon's lack of
experience in running an airline, plus the amount of debt expected
to be included in the deal.
   Trump, who is based in New York, bought Eastern Airlines'
lucrative Northeast shuttle service for $365 million in early June.
   Trump's offer of $120 for each of the 58.9 million outstanding
shares of American's parent AMR Corp. was revealed Thursday by the
airline.
   AMR remained silent on Trump's offer Friday, declining all
comment. On Thursday, the company said the offer would be
considered ``in due course,'' but refused to say when the board of
directors would meet. Trump officials said no meeting between the
two sides had been scheduled.
   Trading in AMR stock slacked off Friday on the New York Stock
Exchange, as 3.4 million shares changed hands. The stock closed at
$103.37{ a share, up $3.50. On Thursday, more than 8.3 million
shares were traded as the stock opened at $106.50 a share, but fell
back to close at $99.87{.
   Analysts have suggested one possible defense against Trump would
be a competing offer from a management-employee group, similar to
the $6.75 billion offer currently pending for United Airlines
parent UAL Corp. to block investor Marvin Davis.
   Fahringer said it is too early to say if the flight attendants
would participate in such a deal. ``Everybody's talking and
everybody's trying to keep their options open,'' he said.
   Officials of the other unions at American were unavailable to
discuss the matter. The airline is widely considered to have good
labor relations.
   Employees at American's biggest hub at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport were cheering for management to win the
battle.
   ``Bobby Crandall's got everybody in the company behind him,''
said Sollie Pearson, referring to AMR Chairman Robert L. Crandall.
   ``There's a big difference between American and (Trump's) little
shuttle,'' said Bryan Atkins, a member of a ground support crew.
   In his letter, Trump told Crandall that through the Eastern
shuttle purchase he ``gained substantial insight'' into the
competitive airline business.
   ``I think that's a silly statement,'' said Tom Luce, a candidate
for the Republican gubernatorial nomination in Texas and former
attorney for billionaire H. Ross Perot. ``I don't think they need
the advice of Donald Trump and I think American is crucial to the
economy, not only of the region, of the state, and I think and hope
that they will remain an independent company.''
   In Washington, Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., called Trump's
proposal ``another instance of quick-profit speculation in the
airline industry that is endangering the nation's air
transportation system.''
   Dorgan, a member of the House Ways and Means Committee, has
introduced legislation to disallow interest deductions on debt used
for hostile acquisition of an airline.
   ``Loading the half-dozen healthy airline companies up with debt
is placing them in serious jeopardy when we suffer another economic
downturn,'' Dorgan said.
</TEXT>
