<DOCNO> AP891006-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1910EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-USX-Icahn 1stLd-Writethru   10-06 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USX-Icahn, 1st Ld-Writethru,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Icahn's Interest Renews Speculation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf with closing stock price</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. edged higher Friday in active
trading as the disclosure that investor Carl Icahn has increased
his stake in the company revived speculation that USX may be headed
for a takeover or a restructuring, including the possible sale of
its steel interests.
   USX was the most actively traded issue on the New York Stock
Exchange Friday, closing up 12{ cents at $38.50 after more than 4.8
million shares changed hands.
   Late Thursday, Icahn disclosed that he had raised his stake in
USX to 13.06 percent from 11.41 percent, confirming recent rumors
that he was intensifying pressure on the company.
   Icahn's sale of a record 42-million share block of Texaco Inc.
stock for $2 billion last June led to reports he again was eyeing
USX.
   The investor made a $7.19 billion, or $31-a-share bid, offer for
USX in early 1987, but dropped the bid after the USX board rejected
it. When he made his bid, there were charges he only wanted to
drive up the stock price and profit from it, but he did not sell
his shares when he abandoned the offer.
   In a filing Thursday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Icahn, who owns Trans World Airlines Inc., said a group
he leads wants to explore a ``meaningful restructuring that would
substantially enhance shareholder value.''
   Icahn's purchase of $155 million worth of shares in the steel
and energy company this week has raised his stake in USX to 13.06
percent, or 33.6 million shares, from 11.41 percent.
   ``He obviously wants to force the company into doing something
... but whether he just wants to move the price of the stock, we
don't know. That's the $64 question,'' said Greg Drahuschak, an
analyst for Butcher &amp; Singer of Pittsburgh. ``Whatever it is, it's
a little more than saber rattling.''
   Icahn and USX declined to comment on his latest move. In his SEC
filing, Icahn said USX's market price doesn't reflect the value of
its assets and businesses, and he is studying a buyout financed by
a ``business combination.''
   ``There are some interesting phrases in the filing ... is he
making political statements or are they fair warning of things to
come?'' Drahuschak said. ``It's very improbable that Icahn alone
would be willing to move on USX ... but the `business combination,'
is that a political game or a statement of reality?''
   USX stock surged early this week on speculation Icahn was
increasing his stake and USX's announcement it would sell its
shares of Texas Oil &amp; Gas, valued by analysts at $1.5 billion.
   Rather than make a renewed bid for a fullscale takover, Icahn
could be prodding USX's new chairman, Charles A. Corry, to speed up
a restructuring or to sell major assets, analysts said. Icahn has
long advocated a spinoff of USX's steel division, formerly known as
United States Steel.
   Some analysts, including Andy Gray of Donaldson, Lufkin and
Jenrette Securities Corp. of New York, say USX stock is undervalued
and might be worth $60 a share if assets are sold.
   Others consider it fully valued at $35 to $40 a share, citing
debt liabilities estimated at nearly $6 billion and a softening
steel market.
   ``He could be acquiring just enough to speed up the
restructuring,'' Gray said. ``The bottom line scenario is he was
getting impatient ... (USX) hasn't had a major restructuring
involving billions of dollars in assets in quite a few years.''
   Corry said proceeds from the Texas Oil &amp; Gas sale would be used
to decrease USX's debt and buy back shares, thus increasing
shareholder value. Gray speculates USX may use the $1.5
billion-plus revenues to buy back Icahn's shares. Icahn has said he
is not seeking a better deal than other shareholders.
   No matter what Icahn's ultimate objective is, his latest move
likely will accelerate action by USX, Drahuschak said.
   Corry reportedly was in New York on Friday, possibly to meet
with Icahn, steel industry sources said.
   ``USX has been one of the weakest-performing Dow Jones stocks
for years and its institutional holders have not been
compensated,'' Drahuschak said.
   ``They're at the point in time where they want their due.
They've been patient enough,'' he said.
</TEXT>
