<FIRST>r f AM-ChevronClimb     10-06 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chevron Climb,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chevron Stock Continues Climb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock of petroleum giant Chevron Corp.
continued its climb Friday, jumping to $66 a share from $64.75, but
company officials had ``no comment'' on reasons for the increase.
   The stock has been moving up, partly in response to a recent
article in Business Week magazine that quoted an industry analyst's
report estimating the company's breakup value at $116 per share.
   ``We never comment on market rumors or speculation,'' said
company spokesman Larry Shushan.
   The magazine article quoted Fred Leuffer, a veteran oil analyst
at C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell. Leuffer could not be reached for
comment on Friday. The article said Leuffer ``believes that British
Petroleum is interested in Chevron's five West Coast refineries,
which he values at nearly $3 billion.''
   John Andes, a spokesman for BP America in Cleveland, also had
``no comment.''
   ``Our policy is that if we have something to announce we will,''
he said.
   Steve McLennan, investor-relations manager for Chevron, would
not comment on Friday and did not return telephone calls.
   Chevron has sold $6.2 billion of assets since 1984 and has
several other current candidates for divestiture, including Alaskan
refining-and-marketing operations.
</TEXT>
